<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     03-23 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Says It Seized Confidential Files; Police Deny It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army says
it seized confidential files on cross-border security from the car
of two senior police officers it killed in an ambush this week.
   But the Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police
force, said in a statement that the guerrillas escaped only with the
officers' personal diaries.
   Chief Superintendent Harry Breen and Superintendent Bob Buchanan
were killed in South Armagh as they returned Monday from a meeting
with police officials of the Republic of Ireland.
   The outlawed IRA made it claim in a message to Belfast news
organizations Wednesday night.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to drive the British from
Northern Ireland and to unite the Protestant-led province with the
95 percent Catholic Irish Republic under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
