<FIRST>r a PM-People-MissAmerica     03-23 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Miss America,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Role Model Halfway Through Her Reign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss America Gretchen Elizabeth
Carlson is midway through her reign, but only one event so far has
been less than enjoyable for the 22-year-old self-described
overachiever from Minnesota.
   She said Miss America pageant officials had set her up as the
victim on a ``bloopers and blunders'' television show, an episode
that forced her to ad-lib a description of a complicated satellite
dish.
   ``It was the perfect joke for me _ an attempt to make me look
stupid,'' she said. ``That's my biggest pet peeve _ making me look
stupid.''
   Her most memorable occasion so far was meeting President Reagan
in the Oval Office.
   ``He reminded me exactly of my grandfather _ I wanted to hug
him,'' she said.
   As she discussed her reign at its halfway point, the Anoka,
Minn., resident shivered and explained she is recovering from a
cold. She was deliberately keeping a quiet schedule Wednesday until
a Salvation Army luncheon, where she had to play the violin.
   Such performances are a part of many functions, giving Miss
Carlson the opportunity to show off the talent that won her the
crown.
   ``I wouldn't mind if the pageant got away from the crown,'' she
said. ``Yes, it makes you immediately recognizable, but that's not
the point. I'd rather have people know me from the inside rather
than the outside.''
   During the past six months, she has visited schools, conventions,
nursing homes, ribbon cuttings, state pageants and endless events on
behalf of the pageant sponsors.
   On a typical evening, she irons her outfit for the next day and
writes back to admiring young girls and women who have asked for her
photograph.
   After her reign, Miss Carlson intends to complete her senior year
at Stanford University. She wants to go to law school, and to become
``a very successful corporate executive.''
   She added, however, that she doesn't consider herself a celebrity.
   ``I like the term `role model,''' she said. ``The more
approachable I am, the better.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
