<FIRST>r w PM-HouseRepublicans Bjt   03-23 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House Republicans, Bjt,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Off the Back Bench and onto the Firing Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republicans gave new status to their most
ardent Democrat-basher by electing Newt Gingrich as their No. 2
leader, but they also put him on the firing line with the Democrats
loaded up.
   ``I think it is manna from heaven,'' said House Majority Whip
Tony Coelho, D-Calif., who said Democrats would remind voters of the
many controversial stands _ such as support for Social Security cuts
_ that the right-wing Georgia lawmaker has taken over the years.
   ``We're no longer talking about someone who is just another
member of the Republican Party,'' Coelho said.
   Gingrich emerged from a closed meeting of House Republicans on
Wednesday with an 87-85 victory over Edward Madigan of Illinois in
the race to become House minority whip, the post made vacant when
Dick Cheney became secretary of defense.
   His was a victory for those Republicans who, after 34 years of
minority status in the House, want more confrontation with the
Democrats. The GOP now holds just 174 of the 435 House seats.
   Gingrich filed the complaint last year that launched an ethics
committee investigation into House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas. And
that was only the most notable salvo in a career of using television
and the House rules to agitate against the majority party.
   After the vote, Gingrich insisted he also could work with the
Democrats as one would expect in his new leadership role, if they
give him a chance. He walked across the aisle in the House chamber
that divides the two parties and shook Democratic hands.
   ``I will be fair with anyone who will be fair with me,'' he told
reporters. ``But I'll be ruthless on corruption,'' he said,
insisting that he won't give up his fight against Wright.
   Democrats said they hoped Gingrich was sincere about focusing on
the vote-counting and other legislative tasks of the whip and would
leave behind his longstanding tactics of disruption. But they were
skeptical and wasted no time serving notice that Gingrich will feel
the political heat.
   ``One of the prices on leadership is a certain moderation.
Sometimes learning that is a costly lesson,'' said Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich., the chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee.
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., took to the House floor to confront
Gingrich.
   Gingrich had ``made his name'' with a ``personal attack on the
good name of Jim Wright,'' Alexander said, because of allegations
surrounding the speaker's book publishing royalties.
   Now questions are being raised this week about Gingrich's
financial arrangements surrounding a 1984 publishing deal of his own.
   ``I think he should answer for all of the members of this House
and for all of the American people who have observed this action,''
Alexander said.
   Wright himself made the same point, but with subtly, in the
unusual way in which he congratulated Gingrich.
   The speaker sent Gingrich a copy of his book, ``Reflections of a
Public Man,'' and inscribed it:
   ``For Newt, who likes books too. Congratulations! And if you
think a two-vote victory is thin, try it sometime with one, as I had
to settle for in '76. To be chosen by your peers is a great honor,''
Wright said, referring to his first leadership race.
   Wright signed and dated the inscription, and decorated it with a
sketch of himself, bushy eyebrows and all, wielding a gavel overhead.
   While Gingrich telephoned Coelho and House Majority Leader Thomas
S. Foley in a spirit of conciliation after the vote, he didn't call
Wright and Wright didn't call him.
   Gingrich also made clear that his spirit of conciliation was
limited and not in the mold of Bob Michel, the Republican leader.
   ``All too often in the Republican Party and in the news media,
bipartisanship means ... Republicans have to be passive and
surrender while Democrats and liberals get what they want. That's
nonsense,'' he said.
   With that kind of aggressive stance, Gingrich could well be a
unifying factor for the Democrats.
   Rep. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., said if Republicans were looking for
legislative accomplishments, they would have picked Madigan, the
deputy whip and widely respected master of the legislative process.
``They really missed the bet,'' he said.
   Gingrich was ``fully predictable'' in his tactics, he said.
``Maybe he's trying to wear the robe of a statesman, but I don't
think that's going to work,'' he said.
   Many Democrats said they didn't expect Gingrich to be much of a
problem either way.
   ``Is a newt like a chameleon? Can they change and adapt to the
environment?'' asked Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y. Either way, he said,
``We lived with the old Newt. We'll live with the new Newt.''
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., said he hoped for a new Newt, and
in either case the answer would be known quickly.
   ``I think you'll see very clearly which way it's going to go,''
he said. ``I don't think it's going to be a secret.''
</TEXT>
