<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeff Healey, the 22-year-old blind
guitarist who has rocked the charts with ``Confidence Man,'' says he
didn't have to cram much for a featured role in the Patrick Swayze
movie, ``Roadhouse.''
   ``The movie's about a bar band playing cover tunes in a cruddy
dive,'' said Healey. ``I've certainly done that enough in my life,
and I'm happy all that practice came in handy.''
   The Canadian-born Healey said he hopes the soon-to-be-released
movie will provide his band with exposure.
   He said his blindness has caused him few problems as a musician.
``I did drop off of a stage once into a bunch of people,'' he
recalled. ``But I was able to get right back up. I joked about it,
and everything was fine.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Grateful Dead's Jerry Garcia is among
the performers lined up for 10 benefit concerts to help fight AIDS.
   ``We're frustrated and we want to do something,'' Garcia told
reporters Tuesday at the Fillmore Auditorium.
   ``We are not making any sacrifice here. We're doing what we
always do, which is playing music for people. ... We want to raise
money to do something about this.''
   Other performers getting set for the concerts May 21-28 include
Grammy winner Tracy Chapman, Los Lobos, Tower of Power and guitarist
Joe Satriani. Organizers hope to raise $3 million to fight the
deadly disease.
   Pat Gallagher, senior vice president of the San Francisco Giants,
said members of the baseball team also will participate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Roy Clark has become the
first national goodwill ambassador for the U.S. Committee for UNICEF.
   ``As a musician, Roy Clark joins the compassionate tradition
started by Danny Kaye, UNICEF's first international ambassador,''
Lawrence E. Bruce Jr., the U.S. Committee president, said in
announcing the appointment Wednesday.
   Kaye was the first in a line of celebrities to become goodwill
ambassadors for UNICEF. Clark is the first such ambassador for the
U.S. Committee.
   The committee is the oldest and largest of 34 national committees
that promote UNICEF worldwide. UNICEF, the United Nations Children's
Fund, is a semi-autonomous agency within the United Nations with its
own budget and executive board.
   It promotes the welfare of children worldwide through
immunizations, nutrition programs, education and other projects.
   ``You can achieve success and win awards,'' said Clark, in
accepting the appointment, ``but this is a way to share all that
with you people. As young people go, so goes our world.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis and ghostwriter Jane Scovell have
been working on a memoir of Mrs. Dukakis' experiences on the
presidential campaign trail.
   Scovell, who helped Elizabeth Taylor write her book, ``Elizabeth
Takes Off,'' was chosen as a collaborator by Mrs. Dukakis, wife of
Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   She did not make clear whether Scovell's name will appear on the
book cover.
   Scovell already has begun working on the book, Susan Kaplan, a
spokeswoman for the governor, said Wednesday. Mrs. Dukakis announced
her choice of Scovell at a news conference March 9 when she returned
from monthlong treatment for alcoholism.
   Scovell and Mrs. Dukakis began working on the book last week at a
private home on Martha's Vineyard.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schoolchildren joined dozens of best-selling
authors and publishing executives to start a nationwide literacy
program sponsored by the nation's largest bookseller.
   ``Team Read,'' a program organized by Waldenbooks, will ask
children to read, write their own stories and raise money for
teaching other youths to read.
   The bookseller will conduct, among other events, a
``read-a-thon,'' with sponsors agreeing to pay a child for each book
completed, and a writing contest, with $1,000 savings bonds awarded
to the authors of the best stories and poems.
   Among the authors at Wednesday's kickoff of the program were
animal rights activist Cleveland Amory, children's book writers Stan
and Jan Berenstain, mystery writer Mary Higgins Clark, former
basketball star Walt Frazier, Muppeteer Jim Henson, historian James
McPherson, and Bob (Captain Kangaroo) Keeshan.
