<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Kemp-EnterpriseZones     03-23 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kemp-Enterprise Zones,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Secretary Says Tax Incentives Needed to Make Zones Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing secretary Jack Kemp says congressional
inaction to create tax incentives is holding up designation of
federal enterprise zones.
   ``President Bush is in favor of it. It's in the budget. Kemp is
in favor of it. It's now up to Congress to move,'' he said Wednesday
after his appearance before the House Banking, Finance and Urban
Affairs subcommitte on economic stabilization.
   ``In this case we're not looking for an appropriation, we're
looking for a tax change. ... I don't want to make any announcements
of zones ... until there's actually a tax change,'' Kemp said.
``Let's not pass a bill that simply authorizes a zone but doesn't do
anything to put a dramatic change in that entrepreneurial climate.''
   Kemp said reduction or abolishment of capital gains taxes,
same-year tax deduction on up to $100,000 worth of investment and
credits on employee income taxes for individuals and businesses
located in the zones were needed.
   Neither the House nor Senate tax committees has held or scheduled
hearings to consider the proposed changes.
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development received 270
applications for the designation before the January 17 deadline.
Thirty-seven states and the District of Columbia have enacted local
enterprise zone programs.
   The Housing and Community Development Act of 1987, as amended by
the McKinney Homeless Assistance Act of 1988, authorizes the HUD
secretary to designate up to 100 federal enterprise zones, one-third
of which must be located in rural areas.
   The zones are expected to encourage economic development and
employment in previously depressed areas through tax incentives and
reductions, improvements in public services, reductions in
government bureaucracy and involvement of public and private
agencies to provide jobs and job training.
   But a December 1988 study by the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, found the program in Maryland ``did
not stimulate local economic growth as measured by employment or
strongly influence most employers' decisions about business
location.''
   GAO said the Maryland program was similar to many of the federal
programs that had been proposed since 1980 when then-Republican
congressman Kemp and Rep. Robert Garcia, D-N.Y., first initiated
legislation.
   ``I just don't want to go through another eight years of getting
these GAO studies of some zone some place that shows that nobody
started a business because there were no incentives,'' said Kemp.
   Whether successful or not, the program ``won't cost anything,''
Kemp said.
   But GAO estimated more than $1 billion in lost tax revenues
during the first three years of a program that involved 75 zones and
$4.75 billion during the first six years of operation. The Bush 1990
budget estimates $1.05 billion in lost revenues over a four-year
period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
