<FIRST>r i PM-Fashion     03-23 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fashion,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saint Laurent Closes Shows With Statement Of Elegance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yves Saint Laurent closed the winter ready-to-wear
collections with a pithy statement of elegance. His show Wednesday
was short and to the point, with beautiful no-nonsense daytime wear
and a burst of colorful folklore for evening.
   This classic couturier no longer has to invent anything, as he
has done it all. But his unmistakably Saint Laurent silhouette and
color palette made good sense for women who want to look chic and
sexy.
   Tailoring was easy, emphasizing softness, though the inimitable
Saint Laurent sleeves under padded shoulders still gave shape to the
outfits.
   At the end of the show Saint Laurent looked pale and
hunched-over, his smile somewhat pained as he walked out and took a
bow, kissing a model who wore a smooth and plain black jersey gown.
Spokesmen for the designer say he is suffering only from fatigue.
   The short, knee-revealing or longer skirts were both split,
modified versions of Saint Laurent's theme last season. He wisely
carries over ideas from his more expensive couture looks,
translating them into clothes many more women can afford in
ready-to-wear.
   The fluid charcoal or oxford gray capes over knickers or wrap
skirts, worn with nailhead-studded belts, kicked off the show and
set the relaxed tone.
   Lots of pants and wrapped skirt suits were in caviar tweeds, gray
or flecked mustard yellow, with short, fitted jackets.
   No matter in what color of tweed, flannel or jersey, Saint
Laurent's pants were invariably fullish with pleats at the hips, and
tailored to ankle length.
   Not all of the wrapped or split skirts looked comfortable, but
they didn't look brazen, either.
   Saint Laurent's ace in the hole was a sleek exercise in false
modesty: a semi-fitted, black, midlength jersey dress piped in
satin, with a line of big buttons marching down the front and up the
sleeves.
   Black, black and more black came out in many tuxedo looks, first
created by Saint Laurent in 1966. The elegant simplicity of all this
was highlighted by an occasional jewel, like a rhinestone star at
hip level where the skirt split.
   But when Saint Laurent got into color he did it in a big way,
using shades of violet, prune and teal in one tuxedo outfit with
soft jersey pants.
   While some fairly loud folklore prints have been seen in Paris
this week, Saint Laurent didn't pull his punches, and offered some
of the most showy models in folklore-knit sweater suits with
dazzling color combinations of yellow, gold and pink or green and
turquoise.
   Although color combinations in cocktail dresses and pajama suits
were shimmering with colors like flame red, shocking pink and
fuchsia, the whole effect was as light as the softest caress.
   The handsome Turkish zouave idea for party time featured short
velvet-calfskin jackets trimmed with arabesques of gold braid with
satin blouses and easy gathered satin pants, sashed with a
nailhead-studded belt _ all topped by a fez-type hat with nailheads.
   The beauty of all this was that any item could be worn separately
with other clothes, especially if they are signed Yves Saint Laurent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
