<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SuperCollider     03-23 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Super Collider,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bevill: Foreign Countries Must Agree To Contribute Before Congress
Acts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress wants a solid financial commitment
from foreign countries before moving ahead with the $4.6 billion
superconducting super collider, but the foreign countries want
Congress to take the first step.
   Rep. Tom Bevill, chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee on energy and water development, said Wednesday: ``They
are going to have to put their name on the line. We like to talk in
specific terms and Congress likes to hear specific figures. I don't
like to be vague about it.''
   But Energy Secretary James D. Watkins said foreign countries are
waiting for Congress show its commitment to building the high-energy
physics project in Texas before they chip in.
   Watkins complained it's a ``chicken and egg situation this year''
and testified Wednesday that everyone ``is looking for the next
person to make the next commitment.''
   India is the only country that has signed a cost-sharing
agreement and will provide $50 million.
   Bevill, D-Ala., countered there won't be much incentive for other
countries to participate once the United States takes on the funding.
   When Congress agreed to spend $100 million on the super collider
last year, ``that's getting pretty serious, that's pretty
committed,'' Bevill told Watkins.
   Asking Congress to approve the project without knowing exactly
how much is coming from non-federal sources is ``asking for
trouble,'' Bevill said.
   The Energy Department is proposing $1.8 billion toward the cost
come from non-federal sources, including $1 billion from the state
of Texas.
   But even Texas is not willing to begin spending its share if
Congress is not committed to construction, and wants a refund clause
in case the federal government backs out.
   President Bush has proposed a $250 million appropriation for next
fiscal year, including $160 million for construction. Congress
restricted last year's appropriation to research and development.
   The DOE has chosen a site around Waxahachie for the super
collider, a 53-mile underground tunnel in which beams of protons
would smash into each other with 20 times the energy of today's most
powerful accelerators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
