<FIRST>r w PM-US-Mideast     03-23 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Appeal to PLO Under Consideration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials are sorting through the views
expressed in four hours of discussion with the Palestine Liberation
Organization in which the PLO was urged to ease tensions in
Israeli-held territory.
   Assessing Wednesday's meeting in Tunisia between U.S. Ambassador
Robert H. Pelletreau Jr. and Yasser Abed-Rabbo of the PLO, State
Department officials were unable to draw any immediate conclusions.
   ``There was no definitive answer,'' said one official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity. He said the two sides would have to
analyze the four-hour discussion and meet again at a date to be
determined.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III hopes the meeting will be a
springboard to eventual peace talks and immediate
``confidence-building'' measures on the West Bank and in Gaza where
a Palestinian uprising helped propel the United States into dealing
with the PLO.
   ``The idea is to try to move toward dialogue and away from
fighting with some practical steps,'' the official said. But, beyond
that, ``the idea is to keep in mind there are ultimate goals.''
   ``Basically, now is the time for considering each other's views
for future discussion,'' the official added.
   In the meeting, Pelletreau, under instruction from Baker, asked
the PLO not to stand in the way of Palestinians on the West Bank and
in Gaza who might be willing to talk to Israel.
   The U.S. side stressed ``the need to get inhabitants on the
ground involved'' in steps toward peace, the official said.
   Pelletreau made those points without going into much detail on
the measures. But Baker's aim is known to include an easing of the
15-month Palestinian rebellion in exchange for Israel's release of
Arabs detained in the violence that has taken a death toll of more
than 400 civilians.
   ``It's a two-way street in this respect,'' the official said.
   While Baker wants to begin the peace process in small steps, he
has told Congress his goal is a dialogue between Israel and
Palestinians _ or the PLO, if that is the only ``meaningful'' form
of negotiations.
   He also told the House Foreign Affairs Committee on Tuesday that
Israel should trade land for peace ``as a solution to the problems
in the Middle East.''
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir declines to negotiate with
the PLO and holds it responsible for continuing terrorist attacks
against his country. Shamir will be here early next month for talks
with Baker and President Bush.
   Abed-Rabbo, the head of the PLO delegation, is second-in-command
of the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   The faction was accused by Israel last month of sending
guerrillas on an infiltration mission despite Chairman Yasser
Arafat's renunciation of terrorism last December. The guerrillas
were intercepted in southern Lebanon, across Israel's border.
   The U.S. government, in its ``Terrorist Group Profiles,''
described the Democratic Front, which is headed by Naif Hawatmeh, as
Marxist-Leninist and pro-Soviet in policy. It has ``repeatedly
affirmed its hostility and resistance to U.S. policy in the region''
and carried out bombings and grenade attacks against Israel, the
document said.
   Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., said ``it troubles me that the
person meeting with the American ambassador is a leader of an
organization that continues to participate in terrorism even after
Arafat's promises.''
   In December, Hawatmeh called for an escalation of the Palestinian
uprising against Israeli control. From its headquarters in Syria, he
said ``maneuvers to stop the uprising under slogans of a partial
truce or deals with occupation forces will never succeed.''
   Hawatmeh added: ``We warn the PLO to beware of becoming a victim
of this trap.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
