<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-23 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's nothing funny about a 5 percent
jump in the cost of a good yuk, according to the man who compiles
the annual Cost of Laughing Index.
   The tab for rubber chickens, Groucho Marx glasses,
arrow-through-the-head novelties and copies of Mad magazine remained
stable during the past year, but prices of some humorous singing
telegrams have gone up 18 percent and admission to some comedy clubs
has climbed, Malcolm Kushner said Wednesday.
   ``This year's index has some good news and some bad news,'' said
the attorney-turned-humor-consultant.
   ``The good news is rubber chicken prices have stabilized after
jumping 23 percent between 1986 and 1988. The bad news is they're
still too expensive to come home to roost.''
   Rubber chickens cost $48 a dozen wholesale from a supplier in New
York state, and Groucho glasses run $12 a dozen, he said.
   Kushner said he's found an average 6.9 percent jump in comedy
club admissions. While the Comic Strip in New York is holding the
line at $12, The Punch Line in Atlanta went up $2 to $10, the Laugh
Factory in Los Angeles added $2 to its $6 charge and the Holy City
Zoo in San Francisco went up $1 to $8, he said.
   Among other increases, the minimum fee for writing a television
situation comedy went up 5 percent to $8,733 under the Writers Guild
of America contract, Kushner said.
   The consultant gives speeches and seminars on how to use humor in
business to clients ranging from International Business Machines
Corp., General Electric Co. and the Internal Revenue Service. He
says he thinks he made the right move leaving the law for laughs.
   ``Whether or not you think the world needs a humor consultant,''
he said, ``it can definitely use one less attorney.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONROE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elementary school principal who
pledged to go to great heights to spur his pupils to read did just
that _ he spent the day on the school's roof.
   Whitehall Elementary School Principal John R. Muller told pupils
at the start of the school year he would spend a day on the roof _
despite his fear of heights _ if they would read 1 million pages.
   The 650 pupils reached their goal this month, helped by guest
speakers and parents whose reading to the children was counted in
the total.
   So on Tuesday, Muller relinquished his duties to a fifth-grader,
put on a heavy winter coat, gloves and hat and was hoisted onto the
roof by the Cecil Fire Co.
   ``Someone suggested that I sleep overnight,'' Muller said. ``If
it would get them to read another million pages, I'd probably do
it.''
   Pupils now are working on another million-page goal with a prize
of a field day in June complete with a picnic lunch and rock band.
In three weeks, they have turned over about 30,000 pages, according
to Marcia Peitrowski, a reading specialist at the school.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PROMPTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town of Prompton supposedly earned its
name because its inhabitants always paid their bills on time.
   The tradition certainly continues.
   Judith Knash, director of the Wayne County Tax Claim Bureau, said
Tuesday that there weren't any Prompton residents on the bureau's
list of property owners who hadn't paid their 1988 taxes by the Feb.
28 deadline.
   Prompton, which has 142 taxable parcels this year, last had no
delinquent taxes in 1981, Ms. Knash said.
   None of the 27 other tax districts in the northeastern
Pennsylvania county could claim a similar record since the tax
bureau was created in 1976, she said.
   ``The trend here has been increasing numbers,'' she said.
Delinquencies countywide have risen from 6,124 in 1983 to 6,608 in
1987, she said.
</TEXT>
