<FIRST>r w PM-DC-Congress     03-23 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-Congress,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Moves to Put Federal Government in Charge of DC Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman added to the widespread pressure
to end a wave of drug trafficking and violence in the nation's
capital by calling for the federal government to take over public
safety in the District of Columbia.
   Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va., says he will introduce legislation that
would authorize President Bush to appoint a National Capital Public
Safety Director responsible for managing the district's police and
fire departments, emergency ambulance service, and corrections
system for a five-year period.
   ``The situation in our nation's capital is clearly out of
control,'' Parris said Wednesday in a statement. ``The drug dealers
are perpetuating their bloody carnage with impunity, since they know
there is little that will done to them.''
   Parris' proposal was the second from Congress in less than a
week, and it came as the drug-related crime spree in the nation's
capital has gained new attention.
   Last Thursday, Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., touched off a furor by
suggesting a ``federal constabulary'' might need to be created to
help slow the city's record murder rate. Sen. Ernest Hollings,
D-S.C., said he would endorse such legislation.
   Last year, a record 372 people were killed in the district, and
police blame 60 percent of those killings on drugs. That total, and
the highest per-capital murder rate of any city in the country, gave
Washington the distinction of ``Murder Capital of America.'' Through
Wednesday, 119 murders had occurred in the district during 1989,
roughly twice as many as in the comparable period in 1988.
   Parris' Northern Virginia district includes the city-run Lorton
Corrections Facility. Despite his plans for stepped-up law
enforcement, Parris says he is opposed to any expansion at that
3,800-acre jail facility.
   John C. White, Mayor Marion Barry's spokesman, said Barry has not
seen Parris' bill and will not comment until he reads it.
</TEXT>
