<DOCNO> AP890323-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NRC-WitnessPaid     03-23 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NRC-Witness Paid,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Technician Says NRC Paid Him to Prevent Publication of Evidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nuclear plant technician says he
believes the Nuclear Regulatory Commission paid him $4,000 to
testify against the agency's No. 2 investigator only so it could
quash evidence against other high-ranking officials.
   Douglas S. Ellison said Wednesday that he was giving the NRC
information about Roger A. Fortuna, the deputy director of the
agency's Office of Investigations, late last summer when NRC
officials offered to pay him.
   He said the unsolicited and highly unusual offer came after he
warned NRC officials that he would ``scream fire and foul play'' if
the commission did not follow up on his alleged evidence of
wrongdoing against Fortuna and other NRC officials.
   The NRC's contract with Ellison, under a section titled ``special
terms and conditions,'' specifies that Ellison ``may not discuss
this contract or the information to be furnished the NRC hereunder
with any person.''
   ``The effect of it was to gag me, to prevent me from going in
front of the media,'' Ellison said in a telephone interview from New
Smyrna Beach, Fla.
   Ellison claims the NRC has done nothing with his information and
only moved recently to fire Fortuna after Ellison took his
information to federal prosecutors in Manhattan. He said the NRC is
ignoring evidence he provided against other high-ranking commission
officials, singling out Fortuna as a scapegoat.
   NRC spokesman Frank Ingram declined comment on Ellison's
accusations and other aspects of the Fortuna investigation, saying
the case was ongoing. The NRC wants to fire Fortuna, citing his
refusal to testify before a court reporter on allegations of
misconduct originally leveled by Ellison.
   Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., had provided The Associated Press a
copy of an NRC purchase order that authorized Ellison to be paid $40
per hour for ``the 100 hours of effort estimated under this
contract,'' plus $117 a day in expenses.
   In a letter Wednesday to NRC Chairman Lando W. Zech Jr.,
Gejdenson and Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., charged that the payment
``appears to be part of an ongoing effort by the NRC to undermine
the effectiveness and independence'' of the agency's Office of
Investigations.
   The Office of Investigations probes wrongdoing by plant
operators. The NRC is often accused by lawmakers and other critics
of being too soft on the industry it is assigned to regulate.
   Ellison, 40, worked at the Nine Mile Point Unit I plant in
Scriba, N.Y., when he told NRC investigators in 1986 about alleged
safety problems at the plant. Fortuna decided against pursuing the
allegations, and federal prosecutors in Syracuse, N.Y., declined
prosecution, according to Gejdenson.
   In August, Ellison charged that Fortuna discussed ``sensitive and
confidential NRC information and strategies concerning several OI
investigations with unauthorized third parties'' and ``matters
involving (Ellison) with third parties,'' according to a partial
transcript of his testimony from Sept. 12, 1988.
   One of the third parties was Stephen B. Comley, a Massachusetts
anti-nuclear activist. In the interview Wednesday, Ellison charged
that Comley urged Fortuna not to take action on the evidence Ellison
provided because it would interfere with Comley's personal
investigations of the nuclear industry.
   Ellison says he has 42 secretly recorded tapes of conversations
with various NRC and plant officials. He says he made the tapes by
strapping a miniature tape recorder around his ankle and attaching a
microphone to his belt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Elections     03-23 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Elections,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Rally Draws Thousands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people demonstrated on behalf of
popular reformer Boris N. Yeltsin and condemned what they call the
perks and privileges of a corrupt Communist Party bureaucracy.
   Yeltsin, who was ousted as Moscow party boss last year because of
his outspoken views, is running for a seat representing Moscow in
the newly created Soviet legislature, the 2,250-seat Congress of
People's Deputies.
   A rally Wednesday on his behalf, the second in less than a week,
was also a protest against the party elite.
   ``Yeltsin is strongest in the struggle with bureaucracy and
dishonesty in society,'' said Olga Ulitova, a Communist Party member
for 27 years. ``He is the only one in 70 years of Soviet power who
did not take the privileges offered by his high position.''
   ``He struggles for the party, for a clean party!'' Moscow worker
Valery Reptov shouted to the crowd.
   Several hundred Yeltsin supporters gathered near a statue to
Moscow's medieval founder, Yuri Dolgoruky, across from city council
headquarters. The crowd soon grew to about 5,000, many of them
onlookers.
   Authorities did not grant permission for the demonstration, which
came in the final days of campaigning before Sunday's elections.
Busloads of police were present but did not try to stop it.
   Also Wednesday, members of the Academy of Sciences considered a
new election for its delegates to the new legislature after a
rebellion against old guard candidates gave new life to the
candidacy of human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov.
   The day before, more than 1,200 academy members approved just
eight of a list of 23 candidates presented by its leadership. The
academy has been alloted 20 seats and a new election must now be
held to fill the 12 vacancies.
   A new slate of nominees is to be presented in two weeks, but it
is not yet clear how they will be chosen. The previous selection
process was widely criticized as undemocratic.
   ``This was a result of a great grassroots movement of the
scientific intelligentsia. If they choose me to be a candidate and a
deputy, I will not refuse,'' said Sakharov, a physicist who won the
1975 Nobel Peace Prize.
   The Soviet Union's first experiment with contested elections has
spurred rare open debate and criticism of the government.
   Even Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said the
Soviets were feeling their way toward democracy, and he said the
present election law likely will be changed after the new
legislature is seated.
   Gerasimov said the new Soviet electoral law ``was passed a little
too quickly without sufficient study of foreign legislatures.''
   He made his comments to the French Diplomatic Press Association
in Paris, which he is visiting in part to make arrangements for a
July trip by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Gerasimov also acknowledged that Yeltsin has become an opposition
symbol.
   He said that ``on listening to Yeltsin you get the impression
that his platform is not different from the party's. At the same
time some of his ideas make you think he is deviating from the party
line.
   ``Moreoever, those who want such a divorce (from the party) have
rallied around him. He is on the way to becoming the symbol of the
opposition. If it is not already the case, it's starting to happen.''
   Gerasimov said he did not find a Sunday demonstration by several
thousand Yeltsin supporters in Moscow unusual in the context of a
political campaign.
   ``The best means for public opinion or at least a part of it to
express itself is to peacefully demonstrate,'' he said.
   Yeltsin, who did not appear at Wednesday's rally, was Moscow
party chief until his ouster in November 1987 for criticizing the
slow pace of reforms and warning that a cult of personality could
develop around Gorbachev.
   He has remained popular among Muscovites as he runs for the
legislature against Yevgeny Brakov, director of the giant ZIL
factory that produces limousines and household appliances.
   Both as Moscow party leader and in his campaign, Yeltsin has
lashed out at the privileges party and government officials receive.
They include chauffeurs and access to special stores stocked with
scare goods.
   The Congress of People's Deputies, which will meet only one day a
year, is to elect the country's acting full-time legislature from
among its membership and choose the Soviet president.
   A total of 750 seats in the congress are alloted to organizations
like the Academy of Sciences and the Communist Party. The rest are
to be filled in Sunday's nationwide elections.
</TEXT>
