<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-23 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops, Stocks Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against the Japanese yen
Thursday, while share prices were firmer on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
after falling for four consecutive trading days.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues, which shed 211.56 points
Wednesday, gained 145.42 points or 0.46 percent to finish at
31,588.66.
   The dollar closed at 130.88, down 0.52 yen from the previous
day's 131.40-yen finish. The currency started trading at 130.73 yen
and moved in a range of 130.60-130.91 yen.
   Currency traders said the dollar's weakness at the start of
trading followed an overnight decline in New York after a U.S.
government report indicated economic growth was slowing.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Wednesday that American
factory orders for major durable goods fell 3.6 percent in February,
the second consecutive monthly decline and the largest drop in seven
months.
   On the stock exchange, share prices rebounded following the
Commerce Department report, said Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko
Sercurities. He said the figure, which indicates a slowdown in the
U.S. economy, wiped away some worries of interest rate hikes.
   ``Although there are still some concerns over inflation, a series
of economic indicators released recently seemed to be at least
encouraging for the stock market,'' Shimoyama said.
   The U.S. consumer price index released Tuesday grew 0.4 percent
in February, compared to 0.6 percent in January.
