<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     03-23 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Asks West to Reopen Embassies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has appealed to the
United States and other western countries to reopen their embassies,
saying the country has not become a ``bloodbath'' after the Soviet
withdrawal as had been feared.
   A Foreign Ministry statement containing the appeal was read to
foreign reporters on Wednesday. Ministry spokesman Mohammed Nabi
Amani said it would be delivered to the United Nations.
   The United States and 11 other western nations closed their
embassies in January and February as the Red Army completed its
withdrawal after nine years of helping the Marxist Kabul regime
fight U.S.-supported Moslem guerrillas.
   The insurgents began fighting after a Communist coup in April
1978.
   Speaking to a group of about 20 foreign journalists, Amani
repeated official allegations that closing the embassies was a
propaganda maneuver designed to undermine the Kabul government and
boost guerrilla morale.
   Amani, whose remarks were translated by aides from Dari into
English, said the embassies were closed ``on a pretext of insecurity
and they were saying after the Soviet withdrawal, Afghanistan will
change to a bloodbath. The last 40 days have demonstrated that this
was not correct.''
   The ministry statement specifically asked the United States, as a
guarantor of the U.N.-sponsored agreement under which the Soviets
withdrew, to reopen its embassy.
   Remaining U.S. Embassy staff members were evacuated Jan. 31 and
the 11 other embassies also closed, including those of Britain,
France and Japan.
   Only 19 diplomatic missions have remained open in Kabul since the
last Soviet soldiers left on Feb. 15.
   After the Soviets were gone, the insurgents launched a major
offensive against government troops in Jalalabad, 75 miles east of
the capital. Kabul has come under rocket attack, but not to the
extent of last year.
   Amani said 159 guerrillas, eight Afghan soldiers and 10 civilians
had been killed in the battle for Jalalabad in the previous 24
hours, but said he did not have total casualties in the fighting,
which began March 6.
   Reports on official Kabul Radio put the death toll since the
battle began at more than 1,900, but guerrilla accounts of their own
casualties usually are only about 10 percent of those claimed by
Kabul.
   Residents of Kabul say government troops in the city have been
firing Soviet-made Scud-B missiles toward Jalalabad daily. The
missiles have a range of at least 175 miles.
   Government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the insurgents had fired at least 50,000 rockets at Jalalabad.
   Huge Soviet Ilyushin-76 transports have landed with increasing
frequency at Kabul's airport during the battle for Jalalabad, which
is considered strategic because it is on the highway that connects
Kabul and the Pakistani border.
   Staff members of U.N. agencies said they counted 112 landings by
the Ilyusihins last week and 109 by smaller Antonov-12s.
   When asked what the planes brought, Amani said they were
``Aeroflot cargo planes carrying supplies from the United Nations.''
He said they were bringing part of the $600 million in food and
medicine pledged by the Soviet Union to a $2 billion U.N. relief
program.
   Leon de Reidmatten, the U.N. aid representative in Kabul,
responded: ``We have not been informed about this'' and noted that
all supplies intended for the program must be distribted through
U.N. offices.
   Douglas Manson of the U.N. Development Program said he did not
know what the Soviet aircraft were hauling.
   Noting that an Ilyushin can carry 40 tons of cargo and an Antonov
six tons, he said: ``If they're bringing food, none of it is showing
up in the silos and marketplaces.''
   Afghanistan has said it will continue to receive military
supplies from the Soviet Union as long as the United States arms the
guerrillas.
</TEXT>
