<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0429EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-HongHong     03-23 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Hong,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Wants Bill Right Of Rights For Hong Kong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
is proposing a bill of rights for Hong Kong to ensure civil
liberties are protected there after China takes over the British
colony in 1997.
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe proposed the idea on
Wednesday during a meeting of the House of Commons Foreign Affairs
Committee.
   Questioned about prospects for human rights in light of China's
suppression of recent nationalist demonstrations in Tibet, Howe
noted that drafts of a new constitution for Hong Kong have not yet
addressed the issue out in detail.
   He said despite Beijing's commitment to observe international
conventions on human rights, ``it may be desirable to consolidate
the (human rights) provisions of international covenants into a Hong
Kong Bill of Rights.''
   Hong Kong Governor Sir David Wilson told the committee that
Britain and China would ensure that Hong Kong has a system of
representative government but said its development would be gradual.
Britain plans to hold Hong Kong's first democratic elections in 1991.
   Asked if a bill of rights was planned, Wilson said: ``It's
certainly one of the things we'll want to look at'' in the final
version of Hong Kong's new constitution.
   He said the proposed constitution calls for enforcing
international covenants on human rights through the laws of Hong
Kong, ensuring that same rights and freedoms that now exist will be
protected when the colony becomes a ``special administrative
region'' of China in 1997.
   The committee was meeting for an update on the status of the 1984
Sino-British agreement that will transfer Hong Kong to Chinese
jurisdiction. A key part of its implementation is the drafting of
the constitution, known as the Basic Law. A committee composed of
Hong Kong and Chinese members has completed a second draft of the
law.
   China has promised that Hong Kong's capitalist system and
lifestyle will remain unchanged for 50 years after the transfer of
sovereignty.
   Wilson told the committee, which will visit Hong Kong and Beijing
next month, that plans still are under way to have elections in Hong
Kong.
   ``There's no change of objective,'' Wilson said, reiterating
plans to have 10 members elected by universal suffrage to the
Legislative Council in 1991 for three-year terms and an additional
15 to an enlarged council of 80 in 1995.
   Until now, the only elected members of the Council have been
elected from limited groups.
   ``The whole process is one of steady and gradual evolution of
representative government,'' he said.
</TEXT>
