<FIRST>u a PM-Nussbaum Bjt   03-23 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nussbaum, Bjt,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>On Eve Of Steinberg Sentencing, Nussbaum Getting Life Together</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATONAH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As her former companion, Joel Steinberg,
awaits sentencing in the death of their illegally adopted daughter,
Hedda Nussbaum is preparing to leave a psychiatric hospital and
rebuild her life.
   Since November 1987, doctors have worked to repair physical and
mental wounds she said she incurred during the 11 years she shared a
New York City apartment with Steinberg, a disbarred lawyer.
   She underwent surgery for physical injuries and was kept for a
time in a locked unit with the criminally insane.
   Now, ``she's about ready to go out on her own,'' said Dr. Samuel
Klagsbrun, executive medical director of Four Winds Hospital in
suburban Westchester County, where she has been living since March
1988.
   ``We're doing discharge planning for her now,'' he said. ``There
are details to work out.''
   The actual release could occur within a month, but Klagsbrun said
she must still decide how to resume her life, including where she
will live and what kind of job she wants. He said Ms. Nussbaum was
not available for an interview.
   ``Right now, release depends on the practical matters,'' said
Klagsbrun. ``She has to look for some work to support herself, just
like the rest of us.''
   Ms. Nussbaum had worked as a children's book editor, a job from
which she was fired after repeatedly missing work. She has a $3.6
million civil lawsuit pending against Steinberg.
   At first, Ms. Nussbaum was charged along with Steinberg in the
beating death of 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg in November 1987.
   At the time, Ms. Nussbaum's lips were split and swollen, her
broken nose had an ulcer on the bridge and a clump of hair appeared
to have been snatched from her head. She was bruised and wounds on
her legs were badly ulcerated and infected. She walked with a stoop
and her hair was matted and gray.
   Charges against her were dropped when prosecutors determined she
was too physically and mentally incapacitated to be responsible for
the girl's death.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, testified under immunity as the star
prosecution witness in Steinberg's trial, during which defense
attorneys contended she was responsible for Lisa's fatal beating.
   A jury convicted Steinberg in January of manslaughter, rejecting
a murder charge because, as one juror said, Ms. Nussbaum could have
saved Lisa's life.
   Steinberg's sentencing is Friday. He could receive a maximum
prison term of eight to 25 years.
   During the past year, Ms. Nussbaum has undergone individual and
group therapy, psychodrama therapy and what Klagsbrun called
``expressive therapy.''
   ``She's done a lot of photography and artwork,'' he said. She
will need to participate in outpatient support groups once she is
released, Klagsbrun said.
   Ms. Nussbaum was returning from a support group meeting March 13
when she received two traffic tickets _ for driving with an expired
license and for failing to keep right.
   Klagsbrun said the license had expired because her mail had not
been properly forwarded. The license was renewed the day after she
was ticketed. She pleaded guilty and will be fined a maximum $100
next week.
   The Steinberg case focused national attention on domestic
violence and the question of who should report cases of suspected
child abuse.
   Janet Segal, director of clinical services at Four Winds,
testified at trial that Ms. Nussbaum's situation was like being a
prisoner of war. She also likened it to the battered spouse
syndrome, in which victims suffer ``an erosion of spirit, of will,
of judgment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     03-23 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Arms Wound Up In Hands of Enemies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional report charges that American
arms produced jointly with U.S. allies were sold to countries
``patently unfriendly'' to the United States, violating a U.S. ban
on third-country sales.
   The General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative arm, found
that the United States had 18 coproduction agreements with six
countries _ West Germany, Greece, Italy, Japan, South Korea and
Switzerland _ and that three of those countries violated the pacts.
   The GAO would not release the names of the three countries in the
report issued Wednesday. But it did say that the breaches involved
in agreements covering tanks, helicopters, Stinger anti-aircraft
missiles and ammunition.
   The State Department, which is responsible for handling incidents
of noncompliance, took some action on the cases, the GAO said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Candidates for Army Training Range Narrowed to Four</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army has narrowed to four the number of
bases under consideration to become the home to an expanded infantry
training range.
   The service said Wednesday, said the four finalists included Fort
Stewart, Ga.; Fort Chaffee, Ark.; Fort McCoy, Wis., and Fort Lewis,
Wash.
   The Army disclosed the four in announcing it would soon launch an
environmental impact study for expansion of what it calls the Joint
Readiness Training Center.
   ``The proposal will involve (the stationing of) approximately
2,000 permanently assigned personnel and training support to about
35,000 rotating unit personnel,'' the service continued.
   The Army currently operates the JRTC at Fort Chaffee, but
considers that facility too small for modern-day infantry training.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Teacher Pay Passes $29,000</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Education Association says the
average salary for American teachers grew slightly faster than
inflation in the past year, rising to $29,567 for the current school
year.
   The figure represented a 5.6 percent increase over the $28,044
average salary during the 1987-88 school year, the group said on
Wednesday. Inflation over the same period hovered at about 4.5
percent.
   Current average salaries range from a high of $41,693 in Alaska
to a low of $20,480 in South Dakota.
   According to the teachers union, the average gain in real
purchasing power for public teacher salaries is estimated at 12.3
percent for the period 1978-79 to 1988-89. That's an
inflation-adjusted gain of $1,844 over the decade.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Doctors Told of Ulcer Dangers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commonly prescribed arthritis and
pain-relieving drugs pose a serious risk of peptic ulcers,
intestinal perforations and other gastrointestinal problems, the
Food and Drug Administration is warning.
   The FDA is requiring manufacturers to add to their labels a
warning reporting that studies show up to 4 percent of patients on
long-term therapy with these drugs may have serious gastrointestinal
reactions.
   The new labeling announced Wednesday is required for Voltaren,
Nalfon, Tolectin, Indocin, Dolobid, Meclomen, Feldene, Ponstel,
Anaprox, Naprosyn, Orudis, Butazolidin, Rufen, Motrin, Ansaid and
several generic versions of ibuprofen, indomethacin and
phenylbutazone.
   Nonprescription ibuprofen does not have to carry the new warning
because the risk of serious reactions with over-the-counter products
appears to be ``much less, particularly if they are taken as
directed over a shorter period of time,'' the FDA said.
</TEXT>
