<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     03-23 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Rebound In Tokyo, Dollar Off Slightly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded today on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange after four consecutive losing days, while the U.S. dollar
was off slightly against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 211.56-point loser
Wednesday, recouped 145.42 points, or 0.46 percent, to finish at
31,588.66.
   Although the market's key index suffered some setbacks as
speculative investors sold issues for profit-taking in the afternoon
session, the Nikkei maintained earlier gains as other participants
traded a variety of issues, dealers said.
   ``The foreign exchange market that has been stabilized for the
last couple of days and oil prices that don't seem to be rising
further were two encouraging factors for the Nikkei's rise today,''
said a broker with a major securities firm in Tokyo.
   Trading was moderate with volume estimated at 800 million shares.
Among the winners were steel and department store issues.
   In currency dealings, the dollar ended trading at 130.88 yen,
down 0.52 yen from the previous day's 131.40-yen finish. The
currency started trading lower at 130.73 yen and moved in a range of
130.60-130.91 yen.
   The dollar's lower start in Tokyo followed a similar trend in New
York overnight after comments by Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan and a government figure on factory orders for durable
goods Wednesday.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported American factory orders for
major durable goods fell 3.6 percent in February, the second
consecutive monthly decline and the largest drop in seven months.
   Recent economic reports have indicated some softening of the
economy in February. Retail sales, industrial production and orders
for durable goods lasting for more than three years have all fallen.
   Greenspan, in response to a question at a House Banking
Subcommittee hearing, said the conditions that led to interest rates
in the high teens in the 1980s are not present today.
   ``It's our view that the actions we have taken to date probably
have made interest rates, certainly in the long end of the market,
significantly lower than they would have otherwise been,'' he said.
   An analyst with a commercial bank in Tokyo said, ``The dollar-yen
rate hardly moved after it marked 130.88 at the end of the morning
session.''
   He said trading became thin as a majority of participants stepped
to the sidelines before the Easter holidays in New York and European
markets, in addition to a general lack of market incentives.
   The New York market is closed for a three-day weekend starting
Friday, while the London market reopens on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
