<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Defectors     03-23 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Defectors,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Defectors Say Countrymen Brainwashed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two defectors from North Korea said
today that there is little public resistance in their former country
to the transfer of power from President Kim Il Sung to his son.
   The North Koreans, both students, were studying in Czechoslovakia
when they defected on Feb. 13.
   ``All people in the north are brainwashed to believe that Kim
Jong Il (Kim Il Sung's son) is a genius and they, therefore, think
he must succeed to his father,'' one of the students, Cho Sung-kun,
told a news conference.
   ``But I think Kim Jong Il is a bum and most Czechoslovakians I
have met said the succession problem shows that North Korea is not a
communist nation, but a feudal state,'' he said.
   Other North Koreans have defected while traveling abroad but the
defection of Cho, 22, and Kim Un-chui, 23, was the first time North
Korean students who had studied abroad have defected.
   Both had attended a medical college in Prague.
   North Korean official radio broadcasts confirmed the students'
defection and said they were ``dopes who did not like to study.''
   Kim Il Sung, 76, has ruled North Korea for four decades, building
a personality cult that has virtually deified him in his country and
maintaining strict isolationist policies.
   He has designated his eldest son as his successor, creating the
world's first communist dynasty.
   Kim Il Sung He became premier in 1948, commanded North Korea
forces in the 1950-53 Korean War and was named president in 1972.
   Cho, a son of a North Korean army colonel, said that after living
in Czecholovakia for nearly two years he realized that leaders of
the Pyongyang government were lying to their people about the
outside world, especially South Korea.
   ``In Czechoslovakia, we knew by publications that South Korea is
one of the fastest developing economies and is rich enough to hold
the Olympics. This is quite contrary to what has been known in the
north,'' he said.
</TEXT>
