<FIRST>r w PM-TMIReunion 1stLd-Writethru a0457 03-23 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TMI Reunion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ten Years After: Nuclear Nightmare Recalled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to recast; SUBS 12th graf pvs, bgng That man, to change
helicoptered; picks up 13th graf, ``One of</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years after Three Mile Island, officials
who faced the nation's largest nuclear emergency vividly recall a
time of fear one says he'll never forget ``as long as I live.''
   There was the fear on the faces of expectant mothers, evacuation
plans in which two counties used the same bridge but in the opposite
directions, the U.S. Army Signal Corps building phone lines and the
White House trying to commandeer lead bricks from the military.
   ``You really don't want to revisit this event. You hope you or
anyone else never has to deal with it again,'' said U.S. Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh. ``This whole event was like a roller
coaster. You didn't know when it was going to stop or when it was
going to end.''
   Thornburgh was in his 72nd day as governor of Pennsylvania on
March 28, 1979, when the worst commercial nuclear accident in U.S.
history riveted world attention on a power plant 10 miles south of
Harrisburg.
   At a reunion dinner Wednesday night, Thornburgh was host for
those who faced what he said was ``something that had never happened
before on the face of the earth, when the worst fear of modern man
almost came to pass.''
   The participants swapped stories about the lack of reliable
information, the response of government and the complexity of making
steam by splitting atoms in a nuclear reactor.
   ``If it goes wrong, there's no human capability of dealing with
it. The bottom line is we were very lucky at Three Mile Island,''
said Eugene Eidenberg, an assistant to former President Carter.
   Other White House staffers recalled the difficulty in getting
accurate details about an accident in which a series of mechanical
breakdowns and human error robbed the reactor of cooling water and
released radioactivity into the air.
   ``What we really had to fear was what we didn't know,'' said
Jessica Mathews, a staffer on Carter's National Security Council.
``We were in the dark. We really didn't know what we were talking
about.''
   ``No one really knew what was going on,'' said Jack Watson, who
was White House counsel at the time.
   At the peak of the crisis, when some federal officials were
urging a general evacuation of residents, Thornburgh pleaded with
Carter to ``send me one good man, somebody who can translate this
foreign, technical information.''
   That man was Harold Denton, chief of operating reactors at the
U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission. He traveled by helicopter to the
site and brought ``instant credibility,'' Thornburgh said.
   ``One of the things we learned was you can't manage a crisis from
100 miles away,'' Denton said. He called TMI and the accident at
Chernobyl in the Soviet Union ``a reminder of the downside of
nuclear power if it's not successful.''
   Two days after the accident, Thornburgh wrestled with the
decision of having to order a general evacuation. After gleaning
information from his staff between 9 a.m. and 10 a.m., he advised
pregnant women and young children living within five miles of the
plant to leave.
   ``I will never forget that hour as long as I live,'' Thornburgh
said.
   Much of the dinner talk recalled fears about a hydrogen bubble
that formed in the reactor. Robert Wilburn, former director of the
state's office of management and budget, remembered a report about
the NRC saying the bubble was becoming potentially explosive.
   ``You could hear the sounds of the cars starting up and leaving
the city,'' Wilburn said.
   Two dozen reporters stormed into the governor's office at that
time and wanted to know if they should leave too. ``They weren't
worried about reporting the story anymore. They were worried about
their own safety,'' said Paul Critchlow, Thornburgh's former press
secretary.
   Former Lt. Gov. William Scranton III, now a private businessman
in California, recalled the optimistic statements from Metropolitan
Edison Co., the plant's owner, which downplayed the seriousness of
the near-catastrophe.
   ``I got this sinking feeling like a stone out of an airplane that
this was bigger than any of us thought,'' Scranton said.
   No one from the utility was invited to the reunion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
