<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-Amish     03-23 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Amish,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amish And Mennonites React To President's Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The students of the Penn Johns School for
Amish and Mennonite children spent their recess soaking up the
spring sun and talking about the important man who had just stopped
by.
   ``He looked different than in the pictures,'' said Ellis Reiff, a
third-grader at the two-room schoolhouse, shortly after President
Bush and his entourage went bounding back down the winding, country
roads of southeastern Pennsylvania to their next destination.
   ``He looked a little older,'' Ellis added, as some of his many
cousins with the same last name nodded.
   Wearing a blue windbreaker, dark blue pants and a short-brimmed
hat with a scoop in the middle, Ellis and his classmates said they
would have to watch neighbors' televisions Wednesday evening to see
if they made the national news. Their Amish beliefs forbid them from
owning television sets or radios.
   ``When he came into the room, I couldn't believe my eyes,'' said
Ivan Reiff, a fourth-grader.
   Both boys spoke with Pennsylvania Dutch accents.
   Some of the boys said they would like to be president one day,
but conceded that their futures would probably be linked to family
farms since their beliefs also prevent them from holding public
office.
   Bush spoke briefly with the school's 55 children in first through
eighth grades and then met with about a dozen Amish and Mennonite
leaders for about 30 minutes. The president chatted with the
students about his dog's puppies, his trip to Asia, and how his
large staff of Secret Service agents keeps him safe.
   The children said he mentioned nothing of the only thing he had
talked about before and after his meeting with them: the nation's
drug problem.
   Earlier in the day, Bush spoke to about 3,500 students and guests
in the stuffed-to-capacity Conestoga Valley High School gymnasium.
After leaving the Amish school, he traveled to Wilmington, Del., to
meet with community organizations fighting drug abuse.
   Ben Martin, an Old Order Mennonite minister, stood in stark
contrast to the giggling, red-cheeked schoolchildren when he
discussed the meeting with Bush.
   Amish historians believe the meeting could be the first with a
sitting president and members of their community, which is more
traditional than the Mennonite sect, from which it separated in the
17th century.
   Martin, 57, a farmer by profession, said the leaders told Bush
their strong family ties and emphasis on religion helped keep
children and teen-agers away from drugs.
   But, he added, the Amish and Mennonite communities are not
perfect.
   ``We realize we are just human like everybody else and we don't
want to forget that,'' he said.
   Martin said the president shook hands with each of them and even
remembered his first name when saying goodbye.
   ``He was a down-to-earth president,'' Martin said.
   Elmer Burkholder, 44, a father of three of the children who
attend Penn Johns, said he was nervous talking with the nation's
chief executive, but overcame the jitters when he ``kept on
talking.''
   Burkholder said he told the president of how his two sons, ages
18 and 22, had been offered drugs.
   ``The children are taught values from the parents and those are
passed on,'' he said. ``I was thankful that my sons were able to
withstand the temptation.''
   The president, accompanied at the meeting by Attorney General and
former Pennsylvania Gov. Dick Thornburgh and Bush's drug control
policy director, William J. Bennett, told the leaders their
community, ``is a shining example of what family and faith can do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
