<HEAD>The Circus Comes To Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The Ringling ...' to add dropped word `and'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A different kind of animal prowled the streets of
New York City in the wee hours today.
   At 1 a.m., the first stage of the procession emerged from the
Queens-Midtown Tunnel onto the dark streets of Manhattan.
   First came the police cars with their flashing lights. Then came
the tigers.
   In cages.
   ``That one was big,'' exclaimed Manhattanite Anita Nirenberg.
``Can you imagine scooping that litter box?''
   About 75 people gathered in the cold clear night and cheered as
the circus came to town.
   ``Ooh'' they said, and ``Aahh.'' And ``Uh oh'' as the odd empty
tiger cage passed.
   The Ringling Bros. and Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus animals travel by
train to Queens, then march through the tunnel and across Manhattan
to Madison Square Garden. Trucks pull the tiger cages.
   The procession included about 20 elephants, some with riders and
many linked trunk-to-tail. Next came teams of prancing white horses
and a pair of camels, then pairs of llamas and black ponies.
   One of the parade spectators, Jackie Markland, said she journeyed
all the way from the eastern tip of Long Island but doubted she'd
buy a ticket to see the real show.
   ``I actually don't like the circus,'' she said.
