<FIRST>r a PM-DartmouthCase     03-23 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dartmouth Case,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whites' Civil Rights Lawsuit Against Dartmouth Dismissed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE MAGRUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for three white students didn't
prove they were discriminated against when Dartmouth College
suspended them after a confrontation with a black professor, said a
judge who dismissed the case.
   U.S. District Judge Shane Devine concluded the students were
``not entitled to relief under any set of facts they could prove.''
   Sean Gorman, an attorney for Dartmouth, said Wednesday the ruling
vindicated his claim the lawsuit was ``a public relations stunt.''
   A companion lawsuit is pending in a state court, however, and one
of the students' lawyers said Wednesday that the real action will be
there.
   ``The focus of our efforts ... has always been the First
Amendment (free-speech) claim in the state court,'' said Art
Ruegger. ``We're looking forward to a trial in front of a jury on
those claims.''
   The plaintiffs _ Christopher Baldwin of Hinsdale, Ill., John
Sutter of St. Louis, and John Quilhot of Fort Wayne, Ind. _ worked
for The Dartmouth Review, an off-campus weekly newspaper that is
criticized as racist, sexist and anti-homosexual. Defenders call it
a courageous bastion of conservatism and traditional values
persecuted by a liberal campus.
   At issue in the lawsuits was a February 1988 classroom
confrontation between the three and William Cole, a black music
professor described by a Review article as part of ``Dartmouth's
Dynamic Duo of Mediocrity.''
   Though the students accused Cole of grabbing Quilhot by the arm
and breaking the flash on his camera during the angry encounter, a
campus disciplinary board found them guilty of harassing him, and
they were suspended.
   Shortly before the March 1988 suspensions, Dartmouth President
James Freedman spoke at a rally held during the furor triggered by
the incident.
   ``I feel dreadful about the attack on Professor Cole,'' Freedman
said. ``I do not want one minority or woman student to decline to
come to Dartmouth because of the perception that this incident is
representative of the true Dartmouth. It is not.''
   In a ruling issued Tuesday, Devine rejected the students' claim
that those comments and others demonstrated Freedman's bias against
them.
   Though it could be inferred that Freedman believed the students
acted on racial motives in confronting Cole, ``it is not reasonable
to infer that President Freedman's motives in making his comments
were racial ... that the plaintiffs' race was the reason for his
actions,'' Devine said.
   Another of the students' lawyers, Francis Murphy Jr., said the
students may appeal or ask the judge to reconsider.
   Devine noted that state Superior Court Judge Bruce Mohl ruled in
January that he found ``no persuasive evidence'' to support the
students' political discrimination claim.
   In that ruling, Mohl ordered Baldwin and Sutter reinstated
because one member of the panel that disciplined them had been
biased against the Review.
   Dartmouth could have renewed disciplinary action against them,
but did not, and they returned to campus soon afterward. Quilhot
already had completed his six-month suspension.
   Dartmouth spokesman Alex Huppe said all three were off campus
Wednesday for semester break.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
