<FIRST>r a PM-ManchinImpeachment     03-23 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manchin Impeachment,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislative Committee in W.Va. Recommends Impeaching State Treasurer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Judiciary Committee has
overwhelmingly recommended that the state treasurer be impeached for
his role in the loss of $279 million from the consolidated
investment fund.
   The legislative committee voted 19-6 Wednesday night to recommend
Treasurer A. James Manchin's impeachment.
   Committee Chairman John Hatcher said one more formal vote is
needed before the impeachment resolution can be sent to the House of
Delegates floor. He gave no timetable for that vote or a related
decision on whether to reprimand state Auditor Glen Gainer.
   If 51 of the 100 House members vote to impeach Manchin, the
popular two-term Democrat will be tried in the state Senate, where
two-thirds approval of the 34 members is needed to remove him from
office.
   The resolution accuses Manchin of neglect of duty, incompetence,
maladministration and high crimes and misdemeanors for either
failing to report the losses, the bulk of which occurred from April
to June 1987, or for failing to supervise his staff.
   Manchin blames his employees, primarily former Associate
Treasurer Arnold Margolin and former Investment Director Kathy
Lester, for the losses. He says he didn't learn of them until
December 1988.
   Manchin was not in his office when the committee voted and a
person who answered his home telephone Wednesday evening said he was
not home.
   Shortly before the committee voted, however, Manchin, 61,
appeared on a television newscast in Charleston.
   ``I've been in public service for 41 years,'' he said. ``Neglect
of duty? I wouldn't know how to neglect duty. I work constantly.''
   After endorsing the impeachment, committee members voted to have
their staff lawyers draft a resolution reprimanding or publicly
censuring Gainer.
   Some committee members were upset when Gainer testified last week
that he delegated many of his duties to his top aide, Don Adams, and
did not take an active interest in Board of Investment activities.
   That board, made up of the treasurer, auditor and governor, sets
general policies for the investment fund, and the treasurer's office
takes charge of day-to-day investments.
   ``He didn't seem to know anything,'' said Delegate Jack Roop.
   ``The Legislature in its wisdom did not put him on the Board of
Investments to be a potted plant,' said Delegate Rick Staton.
   The committee spent more than three hours over two days on a
line-by-line review of the impeachment resolution but engaged in no
debate before the vote.
   It defeated most attempts to weaken or make major modifications
to the impeachment resolution Wednesday but agreed to delete
allegations that Manchin or his staff solicited treasurer's office
employees for campaign contributions, which would violate state law.
   ``If you impeached every elected officer whose subordinates
solicited campaign contributions, you'd have to impeach every
elected official who ever served in the state of West Virginia,''
said Delegate Danny Jones.
   The committee also eliminated an allegation that Manchin asked
Margolin to solicit funds from brokers with which the state did
business.
   ``I think it amounts to an attempted extortion,'' said Delegate
David Grubb, who fought to retain the solicitation allegations.
   Other committee members said no evidence existed that Manchin
knew about or condoned the solicitation of his employees or that his
request of Margolin to seek funds from the brokers broke any laws.
   ``Let's not throw up a bunch of mud on the wall and see what
sticks,'' Staton said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
