<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WellsFargo-Struggle     03-23 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wells Fargo-Struggle,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Granddaughter of Would-Be Presidential Assassin Assists Wells Fargo
Defense</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young woman whose presence provides a
vivid reminder of the long, sometimes violent struggle for Puerto
Rican independence sat quietly at the defense table during the Wells
Fargo robbery trial.
   Her grandfather, Oscar Collazo Lopez, was convicted of trying to
assassinate President Harry S. Truman nearly 40 years ago in a crime
carried out in the name of Puerto Rican independence.
   ``It's more like a personal interest, since I grew up in the
independence movement,'' Loarina DeJesus Collazo, 23, said Wednesday
during a break in closing arguments. ``It's history and, politically
speaking, it's pretty exciting.''
   The government claims that the $7.1 million Wells Fargo robbery
was carried out by Los Macheteros, a violent Puerto Rican
independence group, to finance its revolutionary activities.
   In closing arguments Wednesday, Leonard Weinglass, defense
attorney for the man accused of masterminding the robbery, said his
client knew beforehand about the 1983 robbery, received the money
after the crime and helped the robber escape.
   But Weinglass told the U.S. District Court jury that the
government failed to offer any physical evidence or testimony to
prove that his client, Juan Segarra Palmer, was responsible for the
robbery itself.
   ``He knew what was going to occur. He wanted the robbery to
succeed, but he was not there and the government has not proven he
took steps to help it succeed,'' Weinglass said.
   Segarra and four other men have been on trial since Oct. 11 on
charges stemming from the robbery. Segarra faces 150 years in prison
if convicted on all 16 counts against him.
   For her part, DeJesus volunteered to come to Hartford in May to
work as an interpreter and legal aide to the attorney representing
another defendant, Carlos M. Ayes Suarez, who is accused of using
$20,000 from the 1983 robbery to finance a toy giveaway in Hartford
as a publicity stunt for the group.
   Her grandfather was 36 on Nov. 1, 1950, when he and another
nationalist, Griselio Torresola, tried to shot their way into Blair
House, where Truman was staying while the White House was being
renovated.
   Truman was uninjured, but Collazo's companion and a White House
guard were killed.
   Collazo was sentenced to die in the electric chair, but Truman
commuted his sentence to life in prison in 1952.
   President Carter granted Collazo clemency in 1979 with three
other Puerto Rican nationalists convicted in a 1954 shooting attack
on the U.S. House of Representatives. Five congressmen were wounded
in the attack.
   Collazo, now 75, was freed from federal prison at Leavenworth,
Kan., and is living with his daughter in Vega Baja, Puerto Rico.
   ``Surely I am proud of her,'' Collazo said of his granddaughter
in a telephone interview.
   He said he saw no similarity between what he did and what she is
doing except ``for the fact that we are fighting for the same
cause.''
   ``I was (involved) in a violent action. This case is more a
political action than violent action,'' he said.
   DeJesus, who attended Lehman College of the City Univerity of New
York for one year as a psychology major, said she may remain in
Hartford after the current trial ends to assist in the defense of
nine other Wells Fargo defendants still awaiting trial.
   ``I consider it totally political,'' she said of the trial.
``They did it with political and ideological purposes _ if it's true
that they did it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
