<DOCNO> AP890323-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0626EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Navajos-MacDonald     03-23 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders MacDonald Not to Exercise Tribal Powers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tribal court has issued a temporary
order prohibiting Navajo Chairman Peter MacDonald from exercising
his authority and barring him from his offices.
   Navajo District Judge Robert Yazzie's order late Wednesday told
MacDonald and 27 others not to enter or stay in tribal offices
``except for the purpose of removing personal belongings, unless
further authorized by this court.''
   Yazzie ordered MacDonald and the others to appear before Friday
to show why the order should not be extended indefinitely. Among the
27 named in the order were Vice Chairman Johnny R. Thompson, press
secretary Tazbah McCullah and Marshall Tome, director of Navajo
public safety.
   ``I feel a sense of relief,'' said interim tribal chairman
Leonard Haskie, who was appointed by the Tribal Council majority two
weeks ago. ``This has been a lengthy and exhausting process.''
   Majority council members, meanwhile, filed a lawsuit Wednesday
asking for a permanent injunction against the chairman.
   Tribal offices were closed late Wednesday, and MacDonald could
not be reached for immediate comment on whether he would obey the
order, which came in response to a motion filed by the council
majority.
   The council placed MacDonald on paid administrative leave last
month following U.S. Senate testimony linking him to alleged graft.
MacDonald contends the council action was illegal and has refused to
leave.
   He has continued to use his office and has changed the locks on
the Tribal Council chambers.
   Yazzie's order banned MacDonald from using tribal funds or
equipment, including airplanes, and from issuing tribal directives
or making contracts.
   Haskie said he was confident tribal police would enforce the
order. Council delegates noted that police are funded by the U.S.
Bureau of Indian Affairs, which has requested that they not take
sides in the dispute.
   However, Tome, head of the police, has been one of MacDonald's
staunchest allies, and police disregarded Yazzie's order last year
prohibiting closure of the Navajo Education and Scholarship
Foundation headed by MacDonald rival Peterson Zah. Police closed off
the building and changed the locks.
</TEXT>
