<FIRST>r a PM-SheriffBombing     03-23 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sheriff Bombing,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Admit Sheriff Bombing Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff says he must have been living on
borrowed time for more than 12 years while his predecessor and three
others plotted to kill him.
   Cyrus ``Bobby'' Tardo, a former Lafourche Parish sheriff, and
three others pleaded guilty Wednesday to planting the homemade bomb
that nearly killed Sheriff Duffy Breaux last December.
   ``It looked like I lived a little bit longer than I thought I was
going to live,'' said the 60-year-old Breaux, who is still on
crutches. ``It was really surprising to hear what went on in the
courtroom today, the testimony that these people gave themselves.''
   Federal prosecutors said the scheme was fueled by political
rivalry, revenge and dreams of unfettered drug trafficking in the
coastal parish, or county, about 40 miles southwest of New Orleans.
   Federal prosecutor Lance Africk said the scheme began in 1976
when Breaux defeated Tardo for sheriff and culminated with the
remote-control detonation of a pipe bomb in the Thibodaux Civic
Center parking lot on Dec. 15, 1988.
   Breaux's left foot was maimed. A part-time deputy was injured in
the blast.
   The four who pleaded guilty were Tardo, 58; Marshall K.
McClendon, 42; Ralph J. Bergeron, 42; and John G. Tullier Jr., 23.
   They were accused of conspiracy, possession of an unregistered
destructive device and damaging a law enforcement vehicle. Tardo
also pleaded guilty to soliciting to commit a violent crime.
   Sentencing was set for May 31. Tardo faces a maximum of 45 years
in prison and $1 million in fines. Tullier, Bergeron and McClendon
each face a maximum of 35 years in prison and $750,000 in fines.
   Tardo, McClendon and Tullier also face state charges of attempted
murder. Authorities said attempted murder charges against Bergeron
had been dropped in exchange for his cooperation.
   In 1979, Tardo made an unsuccessful attempt to unseat Breaux, and
discussed again having the sheriff killed, Africk said.
   ``Tardo's motivation to kill Breaux grew through this time
period. Breaux was Tardo's political enemy and Tardo blamed Breaux
for personal and employment-related failures he suffered,'' Africk
said.
   In 1984, Tardo became president of the parish but he was not
re-elected in 1987. It was then, Africk said, that Tardo and
McClendon, a former police officer in Baton Rouge and New Orleans,
decided to kill Breaux with a bomb.
   McClendon enlisted the help of Bergeron, a former Houma
policeman, and later Tullier to create the remote-control bomb and
plan its use.
   Federal authorities estimate that Tardo paid McClendon a total of
$34,000 over the years to kill Breaux. Several days after the
bombing, Tardo gave McClendon $8,000, most of which went to Tullier
to buy cocaine for sale, Africk said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
