<FIRST>u i PM-Egypt-Israel     03-23 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Israel,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak To Israel: `You are Living In Illusion ... Say Yes To Peace'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak told visiting Israeli
journalists that by always rejecting Arab overtures for peace, their
government is acting as the Arabs did for 40 years.
   ``You are still living in illusion. Everything has changed,''
Mubarak said, sitting surrounded by Israelis in a sunlit garden of a
presidential palace. ``We used to live in illusion before but got no
result.
   ``The Arabs from 1947 until recently have been saying no to every
Israeli suggestion. Now I find you have become like the Arabs of
old: We are saying yes, you are saying no.''
   In December, the Palestine Liberation Organization through its
chairman, Yasser Arafat, renounced terror as a weapon in its fight
for a homeland and recognized for the first time that Israel too has
a right to exist in the Middle East.
   Ezer Weizman, Israel's minister of science and research, sat next
to Mubarak during Wednesday's news conference. Weizman, who had just
held talks with Mubarak, was among several Israeli Cabinit ministers
in Cairo since Sunday for a seminar on Middle East peace.
   The session occurred days before the 10th anniversary on Sunday
of Egypt's peace treaty with Israel, still the only peace accord
between an Arab country and the Jewish state.
   Citing Arafat's December proclamations as evidence, Mubarak said
the Arabs have changed their intransigent positions and are making
proposals for peace. He said they encounter repeated negativism from
Israel, which has refused to deal with the PLO.
   Mubarak noted that there has been discord in the region for four
decades and warned that 40 more years without peace would be
disastrous, especially in light of the ``new weapons of mass
destruction.''
   The only answer, he said, is for Israel to talk peace with the
PLO, repeating a common Egyptian theme.
   ``There's no way, don't bother. You will have to talk to the
PLO,'' the president said.
   ``We can't fool ourselves. The PLO is everywhere. Those at your
end won't stop unless they have some hope in life. Believe me they
won't talk to you alone, and I know what I am saying.''
   He referred to Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip who
for the last 15 months have had almost daily riots against Israel's
occupying forces. Israel seized the West Bank and Gaza in the 1967
Middle East war.
   The conference was mostly in Arabic. Mubarak, usually
mild-mannered, appeared sometimes angered, sometimes exasperated in
his comments.
   Joking with peace advocate Abie Nathan, who said he would beam
Arabic lessons on a radio station he runs, Mubarak said in English:
``I am giving you a good lesson in the Arabic language to persuade
your people to learn Arabic and cooperate with the Arab people.''
   Then, changing to a more serious tone, he said:
   ``You are living in an Arab world. It's better just to cooperate
with them.''
</TEXT>
