<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IndianRelic     03-23 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Relic,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Museum Officials Meet With Cree Seeking Sacred Relic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Cree Indians who are asking the
American Museum of Natural History to return a sacred symbol will be
true to their heritage and wait patiently for the museum's decision,
their spokesman said.
   After meeting with Jim Thunder and three other Cree Indians from
western Canada Wednesday, museum officials said it could take them a
week to decide whether to give up the cloth bundle holding bear
claws, sweet grass and a clump of tobacco.
   Officials are concerned about Jim Thunder's standing among the
Cree people, his self-proclaimed ``mandate'' to claim the object and
his relationship to Chief Big Bear, who created the relic more than
150 years ago, museum spokesman Herb Kurz said.
   Thunder completed a 2,700-mile run from Edmonton, Alberta, on
Tuesday to voice his claim for the artifact.
   The 38-year-old Cree has said he was inspired by numerous dreams
and visions in which Big Bear directed him to fetch the sacred
bundle, which has been in the museum collection for more than 50
years. Thunder wants to return it to his people for use in
traditional religious ceremonies.
   ``It's our tradition as Cree people to respect and have patience.
The bundle is away for 55 years so I think we can wait for another
few days,'' said Lewis Cardinal, spokesman for the Indians.
   Kurz said a curator in the anthropology department would consider
Thunder's presentation and make a recommendation to museum
officials. He said Thunder had downplayed his role as a political
representative of the Cree and stressed that he had a ``spiritual
mandate'' to return the relic.
   ``To us a political mandate would be, to make it as simple as
possible, numbers of persons who agree that he should be the person
to take it out of the (museum),'' Kurz said.
   Other Cree, whom Kurz would not identify, have told museum
officials Thunder does not represent the majority of their people
and have asked that the museum keep the sacred bundle in its
collection or give it to them, the spokesman said.
   Thunder admits he is not a blood relative of the chief. He was
adopted several years ago by a woman who was Big Bear's
great-granddaughter.
   The sacred bundle, made by Big Bear when he was 13 years old, was
given to a museum anthropologist in 1934 for safekeeping by a son of
Big Bear. Since then, it has been in the museum's research
department but has never been on public display.
</TEXT>
