<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     03-23 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>120 Dead As Bloody Violence Continues In Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 120 people have been killed
this week in an upsurge of political violence by Sinhalese
extremists trying to topple the Sinhalese-dominated government,
authorities said.
   The government of President Ranasinghe Premadasa has vowed to
deal harshly with the rebels, who it blames for the rise in murders
on this strife-torn Indian Ocean island.
   ``We have to get rid of subversives one day or another. The
sooner the better,'' Deputy Defense Minister Ranjan Wijeratne told a
news conference late Wednesday.
   Wijeratne said at least 60 people were killed in northern
Anuradhapura province on Tuesday, a Buddhist holiday.
   Officials said at least 53 people were killed Sunday and Monday,
and nine were killed Wednesday as the extremists crippled the island
with a daylong strike by threatening violence against anyone trying
to do business.
   Most of the victims have been members of the governing United
National Party or policemen, Wijeratne said.
   ``The laws will be ameded to strengthen the hand of the security
forces against the subversives,'' he said late Wendesday. ``We are
now working without emergency laws, subversives cannot be controlled
by ordinary laws.''
   Subversives is the official term for members of the extremist
People's Liberation Front, which contends the government has offered
too many concessions to the minority Tamils, who have been fighting
for a separate homeland in the north and east since 1983.
   Wijeratne said the Sinhalese extremists were killing security
personnel and government suppoers because they were ``desperate''
following military and police operations.
   ``The pressure is on them and we are closing in,'' he said.
   Premadasa, elected to a six-year term on Dec. 19, took office on
Jan. 2. The newly elected members of Parliament, controlled by the
United National Party, were convened on March 9.
   The front claims the elections were fraudulent.
   Tamils are mostly Hindus and make up 18 percent of the island's
16 million people. They say they are denied jobs and education by
the majority Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population
and control the government and military.
   The government signed an accord in July 1987 aimed at ending the
insurgency by offering the Tamils limited autonomy in exchange for
surrender of weapons. But many Tamil militants rejected the accord
as insufficient.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
