<FIRST>r a PM-PokerShutdown     03-23 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poker Shutdown,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>District Attorney Shuts Down Poker Tournament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The district attorney has shut down the
Third Annual Cajun Cup professional poker tournament, forcing 1,400
players to fold.
   Ken Pyle, who started the tournament, blamed religious protests
for the abrupt end to the 12-day event that was to have run through
the weekend.
   A Baptist group was picketing the hotel when District Attorney
Nathan Stansbury called organizers aside Wednesday, told them the
event violated gambling laws and ordered it stopped, said Pyle. No
arrests were made.
   ``They (the protesters) had sent nasty letters about the
tournament to the police chief, the sheriff, and the governor,'' he
said.
   The district attorney allowed the tournament in previous years on
grounds that, as a private event, it did not violate gambling laws.
   ``We have always told them to warn us before if they have a
problem, and we would find another city,'' Pyle said. ``They always
said, `No problem.'''
   Stansbury has an unlisted telephone number and could not be
reached this morning.
   Pyle and world champion poker player Eldon Elias started the
Cajun Cup two years ago.
   ``We treated this as another convention in our community,'' said
Gerald Breaux, director of the Lafayette Convention and Visitors
Commission.
   He said the average tourist spends $140 a day, so 1,400 players
would have spent $2.3 million in 12 days. ``Moral issue or non-moral
issue, it's an economic issue,'' Breaux said. ``It was good for
Lafayette.''
</TEXT>
