<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0501 03-23 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0501,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Gunners Join Artillery Bombardment In Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with witnesses saying Syrian gunners
firing into Christian-held areas. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian forces today helped Moslem militias
launch artillery and rocket attacks on Christian regions, witnesses
said. Police said nine people were killed and 26 wounded in the
fighting.
   Police said more than 5,000 shells and rockets hit the capital,
the Christian-dominated region to the north and Druse-held territory
to the southeast during nine hours of bombardments by the Christian
army, the Syrians and Syrian-backed militiamen. The Christian
enclave was hit with 40 rockets a minute before the firing subsided
at 3 a.m.
   The new casualties raised the toll to 75 people killed and 237
wounded since March 8, when the latest fighting broke out between
Christian troops of Gen. Michel Aoun and Syrian-backed fighters of
Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt.
   A statement by Aoun's command accused Syrian troops of
involvement in the bombardment of the 310-square-mile Christian
heartland, where 1 million Christians are trapped in a
crescent-shaped enclave.
   Residents in Aramoun, seven miles southeast of Beirut, said they
saw the Syrian army firing from several positions near the village.
The witnesses, insisting on anonymity, said the Syrians suffered an
unspecified number of casualties in shelling from Aoun's forces.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said all
foreign forces except U.N. peacekeepers should leave Lebanon.
   Asked if that included the withdrawal of Syria, the main power
broker in Lebanon with 40,000 troops, Redman said: ``That would be
all those non-Lebanese armed elements and organizations currently on
Lebanese soil, with the exception of (the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon), whose mandate ... is renewed every six months at the
specific request of Lebanon.''
   Amid the violence, Aoun said: ``Let (Syrian) President Hafez
Assad relinquish power. That will be better for Lebanon, Syria and
the Middle East.''
   Aoun, 53, heads the Christian cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government. He was responding to editorials by Syria's official
media that called for his ouster as a condition to curbing the
violence in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   Minutes after Aoun's statement was broadcast by Christian radio
and television his command at the Defense Ministry in suburban Yarze
was shelled, the police spokesman said.
   The thuds of exploding shells shook Beirut and the surrounding
wooded hills. Trails of light behind missiles lit up the skies as
residents huddled in basements and bomb shelters.
   ``Don't forget to turn off butane cylinders before heading to
shelters. Do not use lifts. Keep windows open to avoid shards from
shattered glass in case of explosions,'' Voice of Lebanon, the main
radio station in Christian east Beirut, warned listeners.
   The latest violence broke out two days after Aoun blockaded
militia-run ports to reactivate tax collection at five government
harbors on Lebanon's 130-mile Mediterranean coast. Syria's militia
allies rejected the move.
   The latest crisis began Sept. 22 when parliament could not meet
to elect a successor to President Amin Gemayel. Gemayel appointed
Aoun head of an interim military cabinet. Syrian-backed Moslems
rejected the appointment.
</TEXT>
