<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Shevardnadze     03-23 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Shevardnadze,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Urges Foreign Policy Debates In Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze says a new
parliament now being formed should debate foreign policy issues in
order to prevent the kind of closed-door decision making that sent
Soviet troops into Afghanistan.
   In an interview published Wednesday by the government newspaper
Izvestiya, Shevardnadze said, ``I foresee the time when open debates
on some or other international problems will become natural
practice.''
   ``High officials of the Foreign Ministry, the minister included,
will be giving answers to informal questions from deputies, when
referendums and public opinion polls will be held before taking
fundamental decisions,'' he said.
   The Soviet policy of glasnost, or greater openness on some
issues, has affected mainly internal issues. Dissent on questions of
foreign policy has only recently surfaced in the media.
   The Congress of People's Deputies is being formed now. It will
consist of 750 representatives of the Communist Party, its
affiliates, professsional and social organizations, and 1,500
members elected from geographical districts.
   Voting for geographical districts will take place Sunday, but the
organizations are electing their deputies now. The congress will
then choose from among its members a new Supreme Soviet parliament.
   Shevardnadze said the new parliament, by serving as a forum for
foreign policy debates, could bring about ``new forms of glasnost in
foreign policy and diplomacy,'' Shevardnadze said.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who launched the current
reorganization, also says the new legislature must take a greater
role in setting policy.
   Under the Soviet Constitution, any decision to use armed forces
abroad must be sanctioned by the Supreme Soviet, Shevardnadze said.
   Top Soviet officials have criticized the process that led to the
Afghanistan intervention in 1979, saying a narrow group of people
made the decision without consulting anyone.
   The Soviet Union pulled its remaining troops out of Afghanistan
last month after nine years of war and an estimated 15,000 dead.
</TEXT>
