<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Explosion     03-23 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Explosion,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Hunt For Detonators After Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PETERBOROUGH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today searched for dangerous
detonators that were strewn across an area when a truck carrying
explosives blew up, and the government announced new rules for the
transport of explosives.
   A firefighter was killed and more than 80 people were injured, 11
seriously, after the truck caught fire and blew up Wednesday at an
industrial park in Peterborough, 75 miles north of London.
   Transport Minister Peter Bottomley said the changes in government
regulations, which had been planned before the blast, will require
vehicles to advertise that they carry explosives.
   Bottomley told the House of Commons that the new rules, expected
to take effect in July, will require placards to be displayed on
vehicles and better training of drivers.
   ``We must learn the lessons both on how to make existing
regulations work and on how to make sure regulations can be modified
at least to maintain safety,'' he said.
   Bottomley said the death of fireighter John Humphries was the
first in an accident involving the transport of explosives since
1957.
   Police said about 10 percent of the more than 750 detonators in
the truck at the time of the blast had been found by late morning,
some on the roofs of neighboring buildings. Police sealed off the
area and were using sniffer dogs to track down the copper cyanide
detonators, which they said will explode if dropped or struck hard.
   ``The experts are there to search the area and make it safe,''
said Sgt. Tom Stevens of the Cambridgeshire Police, speaking of the
bomb experts, police, fire and transport officials at the scene.
   The tanker truck had been carrying explosives and detonators to a
nearby fireworks factory when it caught fire outside in an
industrial park.
   Soon after firefighters arrived, and before the park could be
evacuated, the truck blew up. Witnesses said it was ``torn to
shreds'' and the wreckage was strewn more than 900 feet.
   The Fire Brigade said it was not told the truck was carrying
explosives.
   The truck had a small label in the back saying it carried
explosives, said Dick Robson, a spokesman for ICI, the company that
owned the truck.
   Robson said the cause of the explosion was under investigation by
the company and government officials.
</TEXT>
