<HEAD>Milton Berle's Straight Man Milton Frome Dead At 78</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Milton Frome, a comic actor who appeared in
more than 50 movies and was Milton Berle's straight man during
television's golden age, has died at age 78.
   Frome died of heart failure Tuesday at the Motion Picture and
Television Hospital in Woodland Hills, said his son, Michael Frome.
   The actor appeared opposite such stars as Buddy Ebsen, Mickey
Rooney and Ann Miller in a career that spanned vaudeville to
television.
   He was a regular on Berle's show during the 1950s and played an
autocratic studio boss on ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' from 1964 to
1967.
   His film credits include ``Ride 'em Cowboy!,'' ``Bye Bye
Birdie,'' ``With Six You Get Egg Roll,'' ``Batman'' and ``The Nutty
Professor.'' The latter film starred funnyman Jerry Lewis, with whom
Frome appeared in 16 movies.
   He also appeared in such stage productions as ``Follow the
Girls,'' ``The Student Prince'' and ``The Top Banana,'' and toured
with Rooney and Miss Miller in ``Sugar Babies.''
   Frome is also survived by his wife, Marjorie, and a brother.
