<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     03-23 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Opposition Party Demands Resignation Of Takeshita, Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Clean Government Party today joined other
opposition groups in demanding the prime minister and his Cabinet
resign, saying a stock scandal has stripped the government of its
mandate to rule.
   Junya Yano, chairman of the second-largest opposition party, told
reporters that public distrust in the government ``has reached a
critical level'' because of the so-called Recruit stock scandal
involving Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and a number of prominent
figures in the governing circle.
   An unpopular 3-percent sales tax, effective April 1, will further
erode public confidence in government, Yano said.
   ``The Cabinet should immediately resign to let opposition parties
form an interim government for the management of new, general
elections,'' Yano told a news conference at the Japan National Press
Club.
   Yano was referring to the Recruit scandal, in which the
information conglomerate Recruit Co. offered hundreds of thousands
of unlisted shares in its real estate subsidiary to more than 150
people, including politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen.
   Takeshita's secretary was implicated, as was former Prime
Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone's secretary, in the scandal in which many
recipients of the stock sold the shares for handsome profits.
   The scandal, rocking the Japanese establishment since the summer,
has seen the arrest of 13 people and the resignation of three
Cabinet ministers.
   All opposition groups but the Clean Government Party had been
demanding that the Cabinet resign and the powerful lower house of
Parliament be dissolved to clarify the responsibility of the
government.
   Yano explained that his party had waited for Takeshita to make an
honorable retreat by dissolving the Cabinet on his own initiative.
``But, we have come to a conclusion that Mr. Takeshita has an
illusion that he can survive the crisis.... Now we'll fight to
topple his government.''
   The Clean Government Party, backed by the huge Buddhist
organization Soka Gakkai, has 200,000 members nationwide and holds
79 seats in the two houses of Japan's Parliament, making it the
second-strongest opposition force after the Japan Socialist Party,
which has 128 seats.
</TEXT>
