<HEAD>10-Year-Old Drug Dealer Ordered to Spend 18 Months at Children's
Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old convicted of selling crack
has been sentenced to 18 months at a home for troubled youngsters,
where care-givers say his behavior is improving and he is ``thrilled
he can finally read.''
   Family Court Judge Donald Auperin on Wednesday sent the boy to
the Little Flower Children's Services home in Wading River, 30 miles
from his home on Long Island.
   The boy was arrested Jan. 14 as he and a 14-year-old tried to
flee a drug raid in Wyandanch. Police said he dropped a bag
containing three $20 vials of crack. Police also found $226 on the
boys.
   Auperin found the child delinquent. The 14-year-old's case is
being handled separately.
   The judge agreed to open the proceedings against the 10-year-old
because of public interest in the case but asked that the boy's name
be withheld because of his age.
   The child was held in a children's shelter after his arrest and
was moved to Little Flower on Feb. 27.
   Adrienne Carr, a spokeswoman for the home, said the boy is doing
well in school. ``He's so thrilled he can finally read,'' she said.
   Probation officers had recommended the maximum of 18 months at a
juvenile detention facility north of New York City.
   After the judge's ruling, the child turned to his mother and
said, ``I bet you're happy they're not sending me upstate.''
