<FIRST>r i PM-China-Politics     03-23 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Politics,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Won't Allow More Political Parties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese officials today ruled out the formation of
new political parties and said the eight parties that operate under
communist control will contine to be closely regulated.
   Leaders of China's eight so-called democratic parties also said
they expected more government officials to be appointed from their
ranks.
   On Tuesday, Communist Party authorities announced a plan to allow
the eight parties to participate in China's government.
   Yan Mingfu, who heads the Communist Party's office that deals
with other parties, said the plan will be ready by June or July.
   Cooperation among the eight parties, he said, will occur only
under the leadership of the Communist Party, which has ruled China
since 1949.
   The plan comes as a growing number of intellectuals are calling
for more political freedom and appears to be an attempt by the
Communist Party to silence critics without relinquishing power.
   Today's announcement, which came at a news conference on
multiparty cooperation, further emphasized this point. The news
conference was held by the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, a prestigious but powerless advisory body currently
meeting in Beijing.
   ``The Communist Party of China and the eight democratic parties
share the same goals. We are in the same boat,'' said Wan Guoquan,
vice chairman of the China Democratic National Committee. ``Just
like a symphony, a country needs a conductor. The Communist Party is
our conductor.''
   Zhao Weizhi, secretary general of the Jiusan Society, said China
would not allow new parties to form.
   ``The eight democratic parties already represent a wide part of
society,'' he said. ``So no new parties are needed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
