<FIRST>r a PM-BrideOverboard     03-23 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bride Overboard,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newlywed Convicted of Killing Bride</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claimed Israeli agents killed his
bride during a honeymoon cruise and framed him for the crime has
been convicted of throwing her overboard to her death.
   A federal jury Wednesday found Scott Robin Roston guilty of
murder after three days of deliberation.
   The prosecution said Roston, 36, of Santa Monica, had argued with
Karen Waltz Roston, 26, and choked her and tossed her over the
railing as the ship headed toward Southern California in 1988 at the
end of a three-day cruise to Mexico.
   Roston's defense was that Israeli agents on board drugged him and
killed his wife for writing the book ``Nightmare in Israel,'' in
which he claimed he was brutalized in an Israeli mental hospital
after his arrest on a robbery charge.
   ``The defense was absurd. His claim was absurd,'' U.S. Attorney
Robert C. Bonner said at a news conference.
   The defense called no witnesses. The prosecution offered
testimony from one of two Israelis, a Jerusalem photographer, who
had been aboard the ship. The man denied he was a government agent.
   ``He's disappointed,'' defense attorney David Kenner said of
Roston. ``Scott feels that it's incomprehensible for anyone to
believe that he would have killed his wife that he loved very
dearly.''
   Kenner said he will appeal on the ground that U.S. courts lacked
jurisdiction because the ship was registered in the Bahamas and the
crime took place on the high seas.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Kendra McNally said the ship was partly
owned by Americans, conferring jurisdiction here.
   Federal guidelines call for 11 to 14 years in prison, but the
judge could sentence Roston to up to life. Sentencing was set for
June 5.
   Jury forewoman Theresa Mattaddocon said jurors immediately
rejected the claim about Israeli agents.
   ``Why on a honeymoon cruise would a man take his bride's life?
That bothered all of us,'' said another juror, Patricia Kellogg.
``We couldn't get into his mind. We could only surmise it was a fit
of anger.''
   Mrs. Roston's body was found 30 miles off San Diego. An autopsy
revealed she died of strangulation associated with drowning.
</TEXT>
