<FIRST>r a PM-Dallas-DrugTests 1stLd-Writethru a0470 03-23 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dallas-Drug Tests, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0470,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Approves Drug Testing of City Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to recast, adding background on council member
who acknowledged drug use and on Tuesday's Supreme Court decision. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council approved mandatory drug tests for
city employees but did not extend the policy to itself, even after
one member said he had abused ``just about everything.''
   Instead, the council on Wednesday approved a measure asking
members to take voluntary drug tests.
   ``I have smoked, snorted, sneezed, drank _ just about
everything,'' said Councilman Al Lipscomb, 64. ``I have abused
drugs, alcohol, et al. Let's show some leadership and be the first
to take the test.''
   But after an hour's debate, his amendment proposing that council
members be tested for drugs before city employees was defeated 8-3.
   Lipscomb, an independent councilman known for his outspokenness,
said today that he used drugs in the 1940s and the 1950s but quit
when ``I found the Lord.''
   ``I took drugs in the days I was sowing my oats,'' he said. ``We
called it reefer back then. I haven't been 64 always.''
   The drug policy for city employees takes effect Oct. 1 and
stipulates that all people applying for ``safety sensitive''
positions _ such as driver, mechanic and maintenance worker _ must
take drug and alcohol tests to be hired. About two-thirds of city
jobs fall under the policy.
   In addition, an employee would be asked to take drug or alcohol
tests if two supervisors determined there was ``reasonable
suspicion'' that the employee was using drugs or alcohol.
   An employee who refused testing could face disciplinary action.
   City Attorney Analeslie Muncy said she did not think Lipscomb's
proposed amendment would have withstood a legal challenge because
council members are not in ``safety sensitive'' positions and
because the test would be required without ``reasonable suspicion.''
   On Tuesday, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld drug testing for
railway workers involved in accidents, and, by a narrower margin,
for Customs Service workers seeking assignments as drug enforcement
agents or in jobs requiring them to carry firearms. Experts were
divided on whether the rulings mean the justices would be likely to
accept drug testing for many other types of workers.
   Nancy Burkett, business manager for the American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees, argued against the city drug
policy and said the council was yielding to ``hysteria sweeping out
of Washington.''
   ``There is no evidence that a drug problem exists among city
employees,'' said Ms. Burkett, whose organization represents 400 of
Dallas' 13,000 city workers.
</TEXT>
