<HEAD>Pope Celebrates Holy Thursday Mass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II led 1,200 clergymen in
renewing their priestly vows in a Holy Thursday Mass in St. Peter's
Basilica.
   Twenty-four cardinals, 50 bishops and 1,200 priests, all in white
and gold vestments, took part in the service before an audience of
10,000 people.
   ``Let us celebrate together the Eucharist morning of Holy
Thursday,'' John Paul said in his homily in Italian. ``We wish to
renew this gift which each of us received. ... Let us today renew
our priestly vows.''
   The pope also blessed the holy oils used at baptisms,
confirmations and the consecrations of bishops.
   Later in the day, he was going to Rome's Basilica of St. John
Lateran to wash the feet of 12 priests in a service re-enacting
Jesus Christ's Last Supper with his apostles.
   The pope is to carry a wooden cross in a Good Friday procession
near the Colosseum. He will celebrate Easter vigil Saturday night
and an open-air Mass in St. Peter's Square on Easter Sunday.
</TEXT>
