<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NoMen     03-23 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-No Men,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesting College Students Lock Administrators Out of Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50 students at Colby-Sawyer College
took over the administration building today to protest the possible
admission of men to the women's school.
   The students blocked entrances and locked out administrators
beginning about 6 a.m., said Gail Thacher, a vice president. She
called the demonstration ``enthusiastic but harmless.''
   The private liberal arts school, which has about 450 students and
has been a women's college since 1928, is considering becoming
coeducational in 1990 to maintain enrollment.
   Thacher said college President Peggy Stock was away today and the
school's provost met with students to hear their demands.
   ``We're concerned about the disruption of classes,'' Thacher
said. ``But the administration feels the students are doing about
what we expected them to do.''
   About 100 students staged a sit-in at the building March 16,
demanding a meeting on the issue and representation on the trustees'
task force considering the idea.
</TEXT>
