<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia     03-23 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Clash With Ethnic Albanian Demonstrators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legislature in a southern
province today approved constitutional amendments that would reduce
its autonomy, prompting clashes between police and thousands of
ethnic Albanians opposed to the change.
   The Tanjug news agency said the amendments were approved by 176
of the 188 Kosovo province lawmakers. They are designed to give the
country's largest republic of mainly Christian Serbia a greater
degree of control over the affairs of Kosovo, which has a mainly
Moslem ethnic Albanian majority.
   It was not immediately clear why the deputies, about 80 percent
of whom are ethnic Albanian, would vote for the measure. But there
was a report that some deputies may have been intimidated by state
security police.
   The decision prompted demontrations by about 3,000 people in the
town of Urosevac in Kosovo province. Hundreds of club-wielding
police dispersed the protesters, who were chanting slogans against
the changes, Tanjug said.
   Police also stopped about 200 ethnic Albanian women and children
who attempted to march in protest from Urosevac to Pristina,
witnesses said.
   Urosevac is 15 miles north of the provincial capital, Pristina.
   Ethnic Albanians, who make up about 85 percent of Kosovo's 1.8
million inhabitants, have in the past opposed the changes, claiming
they would restrict wide autonomy granted to the region by the
Yugoslavia's 1974 Constitution.
   More than 100,000 ethnic Albanians demonstrated in November in
Pristina, and thousands walked off their jobs in February to protest
the amendments.
   The protests prompted Yugoslavia's federal presidency to impose a
partial state of emergency in the province last month.
   Under today's changes, Serbia would no longer need the approval
of Kosovo's Parliament to approve amendments in the Serbian
Constitution that affect the province. Serbia would also get tighter
control over the judiciary and police.
   Serbian authorities have been pressing for the changes of the
constitution, claiming they are necessary to provide greater
security for Kosovo's mainly Serbian minority, which they claim is
being harassed and forced to emigrate from the region by the ethnic
Albanian majority.
   Ethnic Albanians have disputed this claim, contending that the
Serbians are emigrating from the province due to its severe economic
problems, which include a 30 percent unemployment rate and average
monthly incomes of less than $100.
   Ethnic Albanians say that if the Kosovo legislature's approval is
no longer necessary for future constitutional changes, such rights
as the use of the Albanian language in official matters and in
education could be restricted.
   The Mladina biweekly from Yugoslavia's northern republic of
Slovenia reported in its current issue that a considerable number of
the deputies in Kosovo's Parliament have been ``invited'' in the
past few days by the state security police ``for talks and
consultations'' on how they would vote.
   Several intellectuals from the country's other republics have
claimed that the vote in Kosovo's Parliament on the amendments ``was
undemocratic since it is conducted amid emergency measures in the
province.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
