<DOCNO> AP890323-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PhoneCosts     03-23 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Costs,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Orders Cut in Long-Distance Access Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
ordered the nation's local telephone companies to reduce their
interstate calling access charges by $705 million, which will
require American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. to cut its long-distance
rates again.
   The FCC on Wednesday directed local exchange carriers to file
revisions to their interstate access rates to be effective April 1.
   The local companies last Dec. 30 proposed reductions of $489
million in the charges they levy on AT&amp;T and other long-distance
carriers to connect with the local phone networks.
   The FCC said that based upon data collected since their December
filing, the local companies had understated expected demand and
costs.
   AT&amp;T last month proposed a $533 million reduction in rates
effective April 1 to reflect the anticipated lower charges it would
have to pay the local companies.
   The $533 million cut also reflected savings to AT&amp;T from the
scheduled April 1 increase in the so-called subscriber line charge
that residential and small business customers pay to maintain the
local phone system. That charge rises by 30 cents a month to $3.50
on April 1.
   With residential and business users paying more, AT&amp;T has to pay
less, and the FCC requires AT&amp;T to pass those savings along to its
customers. AT&amp;T's long-distance competitors generally have followed
suit.
   It was not immediately clear how much AT&amp;T would have to adjust
its proposed cuts on April 1.
   That reduction would be the eighth for AT&amp;T since 1984, when the
company shed its local operating companies.
   AT&amp;T's rates have dropped about 39 percent during that period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
