<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0513,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Hunger Striker Critical After 34 Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3 grafs for 5th pvs, ``He is...'' to UPDATE with prayer
service for detainee. Pickup 6th graf, ``Police say ...'' DELETES outdated
grafs 10-12.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black detainee in critical
condition after 34 days on a hunger strike vowed today to maintain
his fast until the government releases him.
   Sandile Thusi, a 26-year-old researcher at the University of
Natal, told a reporter who visited him that he has lost 57 pounds,
about one-third his weight, during his fast to protest his detention
without trial.
   ``Don't worry, I'm fine,'' said Thusi, who is at St. Aidans
Hospital in the port of Durban. He appeared in good spirits and said
he had no intention of eating until he was freed.
   Thusi had an intravenous tube attached to his arm that supplies
some nutrition. Doctors have described his condition as critical and
said he risks blindness and brain damage if he continues refusing
food.
   More than 3,000 students, academics and university officials
attended a prayer service today at the University of Natal in
Durban, where Thusi worked until he was detained nine months ago.
   At a campus demonstration earlier today, the Roman Catholic
archbishop of Durban, Denis Hurley, said Thusi had ``great
courage.'' Hurley said he was upset by the ``conscience of the South
African state, which claimed to uphold Christian standards.''
   The university's vice chancellor, P.D. Booysen, said he had
appealed to government officials ``to intervene on behalf of our
dying colleague.''
   Police say they are reviewing the status of all detainees, but
have not indicated if they plan to release Thusi soon.
   About 600 detainees have staged hunger strikes for varying
periods since January, demanding to be released or put on trial. The
detainees are being held without charge under terms of the state of
emergency in effect since 1986.
   The government says it has authorized the release of 580
detainees since mid-February, but human rights groups say at least
300 people remain in detention, including 60 hunger strikers.
   Four hunger strikers who escaped Monday from a Johannesburg
hospital and took refuge at the West German Embassy in Pretoria left
their refuge Wednesday after receiving assurances they would not be
jailed. The four called for Thusi's release.
</TEXT>
