<FIRST>u i PM-Paraguay     03-23 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Order Arrest Of Stroessner Son For ``Illegal Enrichment''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered the arrest of air
force Col. Gustavo Stroessner, son of deposed President Alfredo
Stroessner, for ``illegal enrichment'' through extortion and
influence peddling, officials said today.
   The younger Stroessner accompanied his father into exile in
neighboring Brazil on Feb. 5, two days after Gen. Andres Rodriguez
staged a violent coup and proclaimed himself provisonal president.
   Criminal Court Judge Dario Caballero Bracho ordered Col.
Stroessner's arrest late Wednesday after receiving a police report
describing how he ``illictly obtained copious amounts of money.''
   The report, published in part today's edition of the Asuncion
newspaper El Diario, describes the younger Stroessner as a
``fugitive.''
   Officials said the court has the option to seek an extradition
order following investigation of the charges against Stroessner.
   The police report noted Col. Stroessner received at least
$725,000 monthly from three Asuncion bingo houses between 1985 to
1988.
   ``He used psychological pressure, saying, `If you don't give me
my cut I can close the business or give it to someone else,'''
police spokesman Osvaldo Palacios told The Associated Press.
   ``Everyone knew this man (Stroessner) had the power to decide,''
he added.
   Gambling is legal in Paraguay and bingo houses and casinos
operate under concessions granted by the government.
   The police report also noted that the younger Stroessner was a
major stockholder in the insurance company Mundo S.A. which won
several contracts from builders of two hydroelectric projects:
Itaipu on the Brazilian border and Yacyreta on the border with
Argentina.
   Col. Stroessner received $21 million in insurance fees from
Itaipu alone, the police report added.
   ``Part of this money was ill-gotten, while another portion was a
legitimate result of the business,'' Palacios said.
   The police report also said Col. Stroessner ``used his influence
to obtain contracts for third parties...in exchange for cash award.''
   Interior Minister Orlando Machuca Vargas announced, meanwhile,
that four former Stroessner government officials had been sent to
the interior of the country ``for security reasons'' while charges
against them are studied.
</TEXT>
