<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland     03-23 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Ministers Named, Parliament Ends Two-Day Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today appointed two Communist
Party members as government ministers for labor affairs at the end
of a two-day session highlighted by introduction of political
reforms.
   Acting on a recommendation by Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F.
Rakowski, the Sejm, or parliament, named Michal Czarski, 40, to be
minister of labor and social policy. It also appointed Jozef Aleksy,
43, to the Council of Ministers as the member responsible for
cooperation with trade unions.
   Referring to Poland's frequent strikes, Rakowski said it was
clear that ``relations between the state ... administration and
trade unions need special attention and tactful and careful
supervision.''
   Rakowski kept the post vacant in an October Cabinet shuffle.
   He made an attempt to draw at least four opposition figures into
his government last fall, but they declined and said they wanted to
await the results of the negotiations between Solidarity and
authorities.
   The talks are nearing completion, and parliament on Wednesday
received a package of bills intended to put into law agreements
reached at the table.
   In addition to allowing the banned Solidarity union, the farmers
union Rural Solidarity and other indepedent associations to be
legalized, the bills would alter the structure of the Polish
government.
   A freely elected Senate would be created and an office of the
president. The parliament also would be opened up to the opposition,
which could contend for up to 35 percent of the seats.
   On Friday, the government spokesman, Jerzy Urban, begins an
official visit to the United States.
   Urban said he did not plan to meet officials in Washington to
discuss aid for Poland's struggling economy and its $38 billion
foreign debt, but the government makes no secret that it will gladly
accept foreign aid.
   Urban is to arrive in New York on Friday and then travel to
Washington, where he is to meet with State Department and White
House spokesmen, said Urban's assistant, Ryszard Straus.
</TEXT>
