<FIRST>u w PM-NorthTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 03-23 0955</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fawn Hall Dissolves In Tears On The Witness Stand</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts grafs 11-15, Sullivan led, with Ms. North leaving witness
stand after testifying shredding was ``no big deal.'' Subs pvs graf 12,
She began, for transitional purposes.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fawn Hall dissolved in tears today on the
witness stand as she described her former boss, Oliver North, as a
tireless worker at the National Security Council.
   Testifying at North's trial on 12 criminal charges, she said that
in many cases ``I would be almost falling asleep at the typewriter''
while North worked extraordinarily long hours at the NSC.
   ``He was an excellent man'' to work for, she said.
   She began to cry as she told North lawyer Brendan Sullivan that
she had met ``Colonel North, his wife, Betsy, and their four kids in
Easter of 1983.''
   When Sullivan asked her to describe the work pace, she responded
that ``it was pretty crazy'' and that North would work at the NSC
late into the night while ``everyone else would be at home with
their wife and family.''
   Sullivan asked for a break after Hall, starting to tell a story
about ``an American'' who ``was shot on the Honduran border,''
appeared unable to go on.
   It was the second interruption of the morning so that Ms. Hall
could compose herself.
   Earlier, she requested a break after questioning from prosecutor
John Keker, who kept referring to earlier testimony she had given to
Congress and a grand jury.
   She told Congress and a federal grand jury in 1987 that North had
specifically instructed her to retype memos detailing his deep
involvement with the Contras.
   In front of the North jury, she said she recalled that he asked
her to make changes. But she said ``I don't remember the exact''
word, that it's ``very hard'' to remember what happened three years
ago.
   Sullivan led her gently through the document-shredding episode
she had testified to before and asked her how long it took.
   ``I really don't know,'' she said. ``I was not looking at the
clock ... I was just doing my job.
   ``It wasn't, lock door, pull down windows, pull down the
shades,'' she added. It was no big deal.''
   When she learned on Nov. 25, 1986, that then-President Reagan had
fired North, she said, ``I was very upset ... it was very unfair.''
   Her testimony, which began in mid-afternoon Wednesday, was
completed before noon and Miss Hall left the stand appearing weary.
   At one point during her testimony, Ms. Hall began talking at the
same time as U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell, who told her:
``Please keep your mouth shut while I am talking.''
   Gesell then admonished Keker, saying Ms. Hall's earlier testimony
was ``wholly consistent'' with her later statements.
   When Keker resumed questioning, she asked: ``Could I take a
break?'' She stepped off the witness stand appearing distraught, and
returned five minutes later.
   In grand jury testimony in March 1987, she said she deleted
altered documents from her word processor. She told the North jury
she wasn't certain she did that.
   She testified in 1987 that she told North the day he was fired
that she was smuggling documents out of the NSC offices. She told
the North jury she simply asked him whether he could see anything in
her back.
   She testified in 1987 that she recalled North and lawyer Thomas
Green chuckling in the car after she pulled the smuggled documents
out of her boots and back of her skirt on Nov. 25, 1986. She told
the North jury that ``I don't really have a recollection of that''
but acknowledged her earlier grand jury testimony was accurate.
   She insisted there was no agreement among her, North and another
NSC staffer, Col. Robert Earl, ``to keep quiet'' about altered
documents, shredding and smuggling papers out of the NSC as the
Iran-Contra affair came unraveled.
   She said that when the Los Angeles Times ran a story on
Thanksgiving Day 1986 saying there had been shredding at the NSC
offices, she was contacted by then-White House counsel, now U.S.
attorney, Jay Stephens.
   ``I said that we shredded every day,'' said Ms. Hall.
   Asked whether she told Stephens there had been an unusually large
amount of shredding, she replied, ``I don't believe I did.''
   Asked whether she told Stephens she had altered documents and
smuggled some out of the NSC, she twice replied, ``No I didn't.''
   Asked why she didn't tell Stephens about the smuggled documents,
she said, ``I don't know. He may not have asked.''
   In testimony Wednesday, Ms. Hall acknowledged that North joked
about going to jail in 1985 when she typed false letters to Congress
denying that North was involved with the Contras. North now is
charged with lying to Congress.
   ``Colonel North made jokes and there were jokes made about''
going to jail, Hall testified. ``He is one to jest often. ... He had
a great sense of humor.''
   Hall described how at North's instructions on Nov. 21, 1986, the
day before the attorney general's aides began combing National
Security Council files for evidence of the Iran-Contra affair, she
altered several classified memos.
   The documents described North's recommendations to his superiors
on how to help the Contras, including providing aid to Guatemala
after military officials there supplied phony end-user certificates
for arms shipments to the Contras. The memos also referred to
third-country assistance to the Contras and the possibility of
seizing an arms shipment headed for Nicaragua.
   Former national security adviser Robert McFarlane had raised
questions about those memos with North in 1985, shortly before
McFarlane signed the letters to Congress containing denials of NSC
assistance to the Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
