<SECOND>PM-Switzerland-Drugs,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss Clear Way For U.S. To Request Extradition of Magharians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today granted a U.S. request
to detain two Lebanese brothers pending their extradition to the
United States on drug trafficking charges.
   The brothers, Barkev and Jean Magharian, are in custody in
Switzerland while prosecutors investigate allegations that the two
laundered illegal drug profits through Swiss banks and financial
institutions.
   Under terms of a U.S.-Swiss extradition treaty, U.S. authorities
have 60 days to present a formal request for their extradition, said
the Swiss Justice Ministry spokesman, Joerg Kistler.
   The two men were indicted in U.S. federal court in New York on
March 10 on charges of cocaine trafficking.
   They were also charged two days earlier in a federal court in Los
Angeles with money laundering and the illegal export of capital.
   Swiss investigators are checking allegations that $1.25 billion
transferred to Switzerland by the brothers included drug money.
   Prosecutors said the Magharians must have been aware that at
least $22.2 million was of criminal origin.
   The money laundering scandal, known as the Lebanon Connection,
has rocked Switzerland's political and financial community and
forced the resignation of Justice Minister Elisabeth Kopp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
