<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Millie'sBestFriend     03-23 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Millie's Best Friend,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Don Rhodes Walks Millie While George and Barbara Bush Are Traveling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When George and Barbara Bush are traveling, the
job of walking the first dog belongs to longtime family retainer Don
Rhodes, a shy, aw-shucks Texan who is known around the White House
as ``Millie's best friend.''
   Rhodes doesn't see much these days of his pal Millie, the Bushes'
2-year-old English springer spaniel, because she is busy nursing her
first litter of six puppies. They were born last weekend with Mrs.
Bush serving as midwife.
   When the Bushes are home, the first lady feeds Millie herself and
walks her around the White House South Lawn three or four times a
day, Rhodes says. The president occasionally takes the first pooch
along for an evening stroll around the South Lawn after dinner.
   But when they're away, Rhodes finds Millie in the second-floor
family quarters of the White House, pats her head, tosses an old
tennis ball for her to retrieve _ her favorite game _ and takes her
outside for some exercise.
   Rhodes, 51, is a lifelong bachelor who lives in a small apartment
on Capitol Hill. He's never owned a dog, yet he and Millie share
that special sort of chemistry that produces strong bonds of
affection and loyalty between man and dog.
   ``She always stops and wags her tail when she sees me coming,''
says Rhodes, his voice as soft and gentle as the wind whispering
through the piney woods of East Texas.
   ``She's a very friendly dog,'' he said. ``She's nice to
everybody, although she's sort of bashful with strangers. She likes
to please people, so to speak.
   ``She's not a rambunctious dog. Some people's dogs start running
and barking and jumping on you. She's just the opposite. She very
seldom barks, unless she's shut away in a room. She's a little
lady.''
   Millie's real name is Mildred Kerr Bush, named after a Houston
friend of Mrs. Bush. The dog was given to Mrs. Bush in February 1987
by William S. Farish, a wealthy Kentucky horse breeder and
Republican supporter, shortly after the death of her beloved cocker
spaniel, C. Fred Bush.
   Millie's first litter, five females and one male, was sired by
Tug Farish III, a year-old springer spaniel from the Farish farm at
Versailles, Ky., where Millie was born. The puppies, like their
parents, are white with liver-colored spots.
   Rhodes has been Bush's loyal personal assistant for the past
quarter-century. They met in 1964, when Rhodes was a student at
Texas A&amp;M University and Bush, campaigning unsuccessfully for the
U.S. Senate, gave a campus speech that Rhodes liked.
   Bush hired the young campaign volunteer from Houston as a file
clerk after Bush was elected to the House in 1966, and Rhodes has
been on the Bush payroll ever since.
   Nowadays, from a small office in the East Wing of the White
House, Rhodes handles the president's personal mail, pays his
incidental bills and runs errands for the Bushes.
   ``I'm just a waterboy,'' he says with a smile.
   The Bushes, however, consider him a close friend. Last year, they
invited Rhodes to join the family for Thanksgiving dinner at their
Kennebunkport, Maine, vacation home.
   Rhodes steadfastly refused to allow a photographer to take his
picture posing with Millie, or even alone.
   ``I'm bashful, too,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-JuryDuty     03-23 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jury Duty,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Runs Out Of Jurors, Sends Deputy To Round Some Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAYWARD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civic duty came as a shock to 12 people
who were minding their own business in a courthouse when a burly
deputy seized their driver's licenses and told them they were
prospective jurors.
   ``I don't mind jury duty, but the way it happened was rather
frightening,'' said Paul Croskrey, who with 11 other unhappy people
was pressed into service at the order of Superior Court Judge
Richard Bartalini last week.
   Bartalini took the unusual step after he ran out of potential
jurors in a murder case Thursday and he still needed two alternates
to complete the jury roster. Invoking a rarely used law, the judge
sent his deputy to go find some jury candidates.
   ``Let's say some were more understanding than others,'' said Sgt.
George Tarnow, who told the recruits they couldn't leave the
building by an order of the court.
   Tarnow picked the 12 from a line at a window where tickets for
traffic violations and other minor offenses are paid or assigned
court dates. They were threatened with jail if they didn't come with
him.
   Bartalini told them the case they might hear could take as long
as a month.
   ``They were not happy to be there,'' said Assistant Public
Defender Howard Bloom. ``You could hear the breath whistling out of
people.''
   But the two who were eventually chosen as alternate jurors, and
the other jurors who had been chosen earlier in the day, were
thanked and sent home when they showed up for the trial Monday. The
defendant had entered a last-minute plea of no contest to a lesser
charge of voluntary manslaughter.
</TEXT>
