<HEAD>American Jet Strikes Barricade on Takeoff, Lands Safely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jet took off from
the wrong runway in Houston today and struck a metal barricade, but
continued to a safe landing at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport, federal officials said.
   There were no injuries on Flight 508, which arrived on time at
Dallas, its intended destination, the airline said. The Federal
Aviation Administration said more than 90 people were on board.
   The MD-80 jet mistakenly took off from a runway undergoing
construction at Houston's Hobby Airport and marked for use by light
planes only, said Geraldine Cook, spokeswoman for the FAA's regional
office in Fort Worth.
   The plane struck a construction barricade at the end of the
shortened runway as it took off, damaging the plane's tail section,
Ms. Cook said.
   The pilot did not advise the tower he had struck anything and
continued on to Dallas-Fort Worth, she said.
   Ground crews noticed the downed barricade, some debris and marks
on the runway that indicated the tail was dragged, she said.
   She did not know if any action will be taken against the pilot,
who had twice been cleared to take off on a nearby runway.
   American Airlines officials would not confirm or deny that the
jet hit a barrier.
