<FIRST>r i AM-France-Chemicals     03-23 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Chemicals,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sonar Fails to Find Container of Insecticide In Channel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHERBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities searching the English
Channel for a container of deadly insecticide detected an object on
sonar, but it turned out to be a block of reinforced concrete, the
navy said Thursday.
   The container was lost when the Indonesian ship Perintis sank in
a storm March 13 northwest of the Channel Islands.
   Ecologists say that if the containeer spills its six tons of
toxic Lindane insecticide, it could cause an ecological disaster
with dire consequences for the next 30 years.
   Lindane is used widely by European farmers, and small amounts
routinely wash down the rivers to the sea. But large amounts of it
would kill fish.
   Two French navy mine sweepers have been searching for the
container in sometimes heavy seas, and their sonar detected an
object similar to the container Wednesday.
   But two mini-submarines determined the object lying in 400 feet
of water near a World War II ammunition dump was a block of concrete.
   Rhone-Poulenc, which manufactures Lindane in France, says it
would not dissolve easily in the cold waters of the channel. It is
also well packed in strong plastic sacks inside the reinforced
container, company officials said.
   The French government said small quantities of Lindane had been
traced in waters near the mouth of the Seine River but added that
these were normal and well below limits allowed in Europe.
   The container was originally retrieved with five others from the
wreck of the Perintis by the French navy, but the container was lost
again when tow ropes snapped as it was being hauled back to
Cherbourg port.
</TEXT>
