<FIRST>r a AM-OscarTraffic     03-23 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oscar Traffic,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Traffic Experts Say This Year Will Be Different</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AP Arts: Oscar-Auction, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Army in 4th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arriving at last year's Academy Awards was a
feature-length disaster starring some of Hollywood's biggest names.
This year, some of the biggest names in city traffic control say
there will be no sequel.
   Limousines making their way to the 1988 awards ceremony at the
Shrine Auditorium came to a dead stop in sweltering smog, many
blocks short of their destination. For hours they sat motionless in
a high-glamour gridlock as the clock ticked toward the televised
show's opening credits.
   Acting nominee and presenter Glenn Close, nine months pregnant,
finally emerged from her limo and hiked up Jefferson Boulevard to
make the ceremony on time. Others followed suit, among them Olivia
de Havilland and Meryl Streep.
   ``I saw quite a few gorgeous women holding their skirts with one
hand and high-heel shoes with the other, out of breath and trying to
get in on time,'' said official Oscar greeter Army Archerd.
   ``Hundreds of dollars in hairdressing and makeup were ruined
because they had to run in the broiling sun,'' he said.
   A tribute to Oscar's 60th birthday, presenting nominees from all
59 previous ceremonies, had to be scratched because so many
principals were late.
   ``It was a nightmare,'' said Dav-El Limousines chauffeur Rick
Cameron. ``We actually rehearsed the drive the day before, but we
had no idea it would be as bad as it was.'' He said he arrived with
moments to spare.
   Another celebrity who got stuck was Los Angeles Mayor Tom
Bradley. Needless to say, things will be done a little differently
this year.
   Within days of last year's debacle, a team of traffic experts
began work to assure a smooth street performance for the 61st
Academy Awards next Wednesday, said Timothy F. Crowder, a city
traffic engineer who handles special events.
   The team concluded there were several problems, including too
many vehicles trying to squeeze through narrow Royal Street at the
front of the auditorium to unload their passengers in a timely
fashion.
   Among the changes this year is a different celebrity arrival area
with five lanes to accommodate the big cars.
   The number of traffic officers will be nearly doubled from last
year, Crowder said, along with street engineers trained to rearrange
traffic patterns while an event is occurring.
   Officials also will use Automatic Traffic Surveillance and
Control, a system linked by fiber optics to a centralized computer
to adjust signal lights. The system was installed in the area for
the 1984 Summer Olympics.
   Crowder said officials expect 500 to 800 limousines for Oscar
night, along with 800 passenger cars. Inside the auditorium will be
5,700 guests, another 550 people devoted to production of the live 9
p.m. EST broadcast on ABC-TV, and about 150 Academy personnel.
   ``The city does not look good when things like this happen,''
Crowder said of last year's traffic jam. ``This is the home of the
film industry, and we don't want to lose something like the Oscars
to somewhere else.''
</TEXT>
