<HEAD>Three East Germans Escape To West Despite Warning Shots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two East German teen-agers fled to
West Germany from Czechoslovakia under a salvo of warning shots, and
a third East German man escaped by swimming the Werra River, West
German police said Thrusday.
   The two 18-year-old East Germans reported Wednesday to
authorities near the West German town of Tirchenreuth about 120
miles north of Munich, Bavarian border police said.
   Several warning shots were fired by Czechoslovak border guards
but the two were uninjured, police said.
   The third East German fled his communist homeland by swimming
Wednesday across the Werra River, which forms part of the border
with East Germany about 95 miles northeast of Frankfurt.
   Police said the 20-year-old electrician reached the West German
side of the river uninjured and apparently was not noticed by East
German border guards.
