<DOCNO> AP890323-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ArkansasDesegregation Bjt   03-23 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arkansas Desegregation, Bjt,0882</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arkansas Legislature Acts To Remove Vestiges of Segregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES JEFFERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than three decades after fighting
federally ordered integration, the Arkansas Legislature took a
series of landmark steps to shed the state's segregrationist past.
   The keystone of the legislative session concluded last week was
the approval of a $118 million settlement in a lingering civil
rights lawsuit stemming from state and local actions that the
plaintiffs said helped resegregate inner-city schools in Little Rock
and encourage ``white flight'' to the suburbs. The settlement
includes beefing up city schools and redrawing some school district
boundaries.
   ``A national statement for desegregation was made today,'' Little
Rock school board member Skip Rutherford said after the state House
of Representatives narrowly approved the settlement.
   ``It was a clear determination on the part of a majority of the
legislators to put the legacy of 1957 behind us forever,'' Gov. Bill
Clinton said in an interview this week.
   It was 1957 when then-Gov. Orval Faubus refused to allow nine
black students to enter the all-white Central High School. President
Dwight D. Eisenhower ordered federal troops to Central to keep the
peace and enforce court-ordered desegregation.
   In addition to approving the settlement, lawmakers this session
voted overwhelmingly to repeal more than a dozen laws passed during
the late 1950s and early 1960s to preserve segregated schools.
   One statute required local school officials to consider public
sentiment in making school assignments. Another provided for
jailhouse school board meetings in case board members were jailed
for disobeying integration orders.
   A co-sponsor of the legislation to repeal the segregation laws
was freshman Rep. Ben McGee, the first black since Reconstruction to
represent the largely black Mississippi River Delta region of
eastern Arkansas.
   ``What's historic about the whole thing was the commitment on the
part of people to wipe the slate clean,'' said McGee, who noted that
some of the votes to repeal the segregation laws came from lawmakers
who had helped adopt them years ago.
   Lawmakers also decided to put on the November ballot a measure
asking voters to repeal a 1956 amendment to the state constitution
that required the Legislature to pass laws and use all other means
necessary to circumvent federal desegregation rulings. Any state or
local official could be prosecuted for failure to enforce state laws
to preserve segregation.
   Faubus, now 79, said this week that repealing the old laws and
attempting to amend the constitution is commendable but unnecessary.
   ``All those things had been nullified by the federal court
rulings,'' he said. ``I'm not objecting to it, but I think it's
mostly posturing and for propaganda purposes.''
   Faubus does object to the settlement involving the Little Rock,
North Little Rock and Pulaski County Special school districts.
   ``It may turn out as one of the worse things that ever
happened,'' said Faubus, who served six terms as governor. ``This
could break the state government. There's no limit to what it could
cost, and there's no limit to how many lawsuits that can be filed.
These lawyers are making too much money to let it stop.''
   Clinton calls the agreement a model for other states grappling
with desegregation issues, and he and other proponents argue it
could buffer the state from liability in any future desegregation
litigation. At least two such lawsuits are pending.
   Lawmakers from outside Pulaski County _ Little Rock and the
surrounding area _ were angry that money earmarked for schools in
their districts will be funneled into the Pulaski schools, among the
state's wealthiest. Rep. Lloyd George called the settlement an
open-ended ``entitlement program'' that ultimately could cost the
state more than $260 million.
   In addition to the money the state agreed to pay in the
settlement, court orders in the case require the state to fund other
compensatory programs in the Little Rock district and pay $9.3
million a year for the operation of magnet schools designed to
attract white students back to the Little Rock district.
   Also approved were programs _ such as mandatory kindergarten and
college grants to entice more minority students into teaching _
drafted to benefit blacks.
   The state Senate easily approved the settlement, 31-2. But it
took four ballots in the House before the agreement finally passed,
54-42, just 30 minutes before the 68-day session ended Friday.
   Of the House members who changed their votes in the final ballot,
Clinton said: ``They concluded that the old tried-and-true Southern
strategy of whipping up on the federal courts had never worked for
anybody _ that it would generate a lot of votes but never show any
positive results in the civil rights area.''
   He complimented the legislators from outside Pulaski County for
voting for the settlement.
   ``We are trying to close the books on the Little Rock crisis and
essentially make a statement that we're committed to equal
opportunity, to giving all of our children a chance to learn, and
that we're committed to a progressive course in education, economic
development and race relations,'' Clinton said.
   ``We have to deal with all of those things if this state and its
people are ever going to fulfill their potential.''
</TEXT>
