<SECOND>PM-Teen Murder, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0558,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Man Arrested In Neighbor Girl's Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs on arraignment, bail hearing, police news
conference. PICKS UP 5th graf, `Kelly had ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man was charged today with murdering
a 13-year-old neighbor girl found stabbed and strangled three weeks
ago in the basement of the home he shares with his parents and
teen-age brother.
   Robert Golub, 21, surrendered to police and was ordered held
without bail.
   ``This defendant is charged with the vicious, savage killing of a
13-year-old girl,'' Assistant District Attorney Daniel Cotter argued
at the arraignment.
   Richard and Victoria Tinyes, whose daughter, Kelly, was slain,
stood quietly in a courtroom hallway.
   County Chief of Detectives Wayne Seay said Golub's arrest was
based on ``significant and substantial forensic evidence,'' which
Cotter said included a bloody palm print found at the murder scene
in Golub's basement.
   Golub, a muscular, 5-foot-3 weightlifter, maintains his
innocence, his attorney, John O'Grady, said.
   Neighbors and relatives of the girl, angry that police had not
made an arrest, had driven the Golubs from their house in Valley
Stream on Long Island earlier this week.
   Kelly had been seen entering the Golub house on March 3 after
reportedly receiving a phone call from John Jr., 14.
   Police had said the Golub brothers, both of whom were at home on
the afternoon of the killing, were the main focus of their
investigation.
   Police announced last week that they had enough evidence to make
an arrest, but District Attorney Denis Dillon said he wanted to
present the case to a grand jury to strengthen it. The grand jury
heard testimony Wednesday.
