<FIRST>u a PM-PoliceSting 3rdLd-Writethru a0577 03-23 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Sting, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0577,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Drops Charges Against Activist Featured In Televised Arrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS to car sted van in 7th graf pvs, `Police said ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges of resisting arrest have been
dropped against a black policeman whose head shattered a plate glass
window in a confrontation with a white officer that was videotaped
by a news crew.
   ``I'm very elated,'' Don Jackson, 30, said after the prosecutor
announced there was not enough evidence to bring him to trial
Wednesday.
   Jackson, a Hawthorne police sergeant who has accused white
officers of racism, set up his own ``sting'' by traveling into
nearby Long Beach on Jan. 14 in a car while an NBC news crew
followed.
   Jackson's vehicle was pulled over by police. In a scene later
televised on NBC, Jackson's head is seen apparently being smashed
into a store window. The city filed charges of resisting arrest.
   On Wednesday, Deputy City Prosecutor John Vander Lans told
Municipal Judge Gary Hahn there was insufficient evidence to obtain
a conviction.
   Vander Lans said he based his decision on the videotape; the
testimony by the arresting officer, Mark Dickey, during a state
Senate hearing, and interviews with witnesses.
   Police said Jackson's car had been weaving in traffic, and
officials had suggested Jackson instigated the confrontation through
his words and actions.
   But Dickey told the state Senate panel that Jackson had never
sworn at him as he had stated in his police report. The officer
attributed the discrepancy to a faulty memory.
   After the charge was dismissed, Jackson denounced Long Beach
authorities' attempt to prosecute him as ``a ridiculous spectacle.''
   Jackson is on disability leave from the Hawthorne department
because he contends he suffered stress as a result of racism there.
   Mike Minton, a spokesman for the Long Beach Police Officers'
Association, criticized the decision to drop the case.
   ``The Don Jacksons of the world are going to go out there and try
to intimidate police officers, and somebody is going to get hurt,''
he said.
   Jackson's lawyer, Thomas E. Beck, said he has filed a complaint
with the state bar against Vander Lans alleging malicious
prosecution and claimed city officials conspired against Jackson.
Vander Lans denied the charge.
</TEXT>
