<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1411EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-23 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CROOKS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This small eastern South Dakota town has done
without one of the more common trappings of the modern world for 113
years _ a paved Main Street.
   But Crooks residents voted Tuesday to cover up the past by
approving a $70,000 project that will put pavement on Main.
   Work to lay the asphalt carpet will begin this spring on the 2{
blocks made up of mud and gravel.
   ``You bet it's a big deal,'' Mayor Paul Anderson said Wednesday.
``One of the things we've found is when we go out and try to lure a
business into Crooks, a paved Main Street is a priority.''
   Crooks, located about 10 miles northwest of Sioux Falls, began as
a settlement called New Hope in 1876. The town changed its name in
1904 to honor the then-postmaster and banker D.O. Crooks.
   Although most of the town's 750 residents work in Sioux Falls,
there are about a dozen businesses and Anderson said he would like
to attract more.
   ``It seems to have an effect on the general feeling of the
community as a whole,'' he said. ``A lot of people come and drive
through and they won't stop.''
   Residents approved a $20,000 bond issue to help pay for the
project 100-47.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WOODBINE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What's an annual Crawfish Festival without a
crawfish mascot?
   Not much, decided Woodbine city officials, so they got a friend
of a resident to stitch up a costume.
   The Woodbine Citizens Steering Committee unveiled ``Crawford''
Tuesday night.
   ``I think it turned out very well,'' Fran Hewitt, the costume's
designer, said from her home in Marietta, Ohio.
   Mrs. Hewitt, a housewife who has been designing costumes for 20
years, said she has designed costumes resembling bears, rabbits,
ducks and geese to entertain children, but never a crawfish.
   Woodbine's deputy city clerk, Sandy Rayson, sent her a crawfish
in a box to help spur her creative juices, Mrs. Hewitt said. She
said she had seen crawfish before, but ``never that big.''
   Her biggest challenge with the costume was finding a place
through which its inhabitant could breathe and see. She settled on
the crawfish's mouth.
   ``Crawford'' will be featured in the fourth annual Crawfish
Festival parade April 29.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state senator says he has found the
appropriate time to hear testimony on a bill to make The Kingsmen's
classic recording of ``Louie Louie'' the official state rock song.
   ``My hunch is we'll get it in with the nut bills,'' said Sen.
Glenn Otto, a member of the Senate Government Operations and
Elections Committee.
   Otto hastened to add that he meant two bills to designate the
hazelnut and the chinquapin as official Oregon nuts.
   Otto earlier referred to the song as ``Lousy, Lousy.''
   The bill's author, Sen. Bill Bradbury, admits that the idea of
giving official state status to the world's most-recorded rock song
was a gimmick to get some free entertainment.
   ``Can I be honest with you?'' Bradbury said Tuesday. ``The
reality of the bill was to get The Kingsmen down here to play'' at a
legislative party last week.
   The lure was enough to persuade several members of The Kingsmen,
who recorded the original ``Louie, Louie'' in Portland in 1963, to
show up at the party and play music for free, Bradbury said.
   Bradbury plans to continue to push the bill even though an
identical measure died without a hearing in the 1987 Legislature.
</TEXT>
