<FIRST>r i AM-China-Deng     03-23 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Deng,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Xiaoping Says He Skipped Session Due to Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping said Thursday that he
skipped the opening session of China's legislature so he could
``conserve my health and live longer.
   In his first public appearance since the National People's
Congress opened Monday, he also acknowledged the government has made
mistakes, such as not paying enough attention to education and
forgetting its tradition of hard work and plain living.
   ``I seldom do the daily work (of government) now,'' Deng told
visiting Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni.
   Deng, 84, did not attend even though he is a delegate to the
congress from his home province, Sichuan. Government officials said
only that Deng had asked for leave.
   Deng confirmed to Museveni: ``I have asked for leave. I want to
conserve my health and live longer. What is more important is that I
should gradually withdraw from the stage and let others preside over
the work.''
   He noted new government and party leaders were chosen in 1987 and
1988. Deng retired from all his posts except that of chairman of the
Central Military Commission, which sets military policy.
   ``We should not let the new leaders feel that there is a kind of
force above them,'' Deng said.
   ``Yes, but young people need the guidance and leadership of the
older generation,'' Museveni responded.
   In a later report by the official Xinhua News Agency, Deng was
quoted as saying the government has made small mistakes in the last
10 years during which China has enacted a reform program to open its
economy to market forces.
   China is facing an inflation rate of 36 percent, the highest
since the communist victory in 1949. Corruption also is on the rise.
Deng said it would take the country two to four years to overcome
the problems.
   Deng said Premier Li Peng had referred to the mistakes in his
report Monday to the National People's Congress.
   ``Foreigners have commented that we have made self-criticisms
about these mistakes. We veterans, too have to take
responsibility,'' he said.
   Deng chain smokes despite doctors' advice to cut down. He wears a
hearing aid in one ear and moves more slowly than he did several
years ago, but is not known to have any major ailment.
   He has cut down sharply on his public appearances in the past
year, but is still believed to play a deciding role in policymaking
and apparently is the final voice when party leader Zhao Ziyang, Li
and other officials disagree.
   Some Western experts believe he is the only leader with the full
support of the military.
</TEXT>
