<SECOND>PM-Abortion Protests, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0575,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Protests Begin with Archbishop's Blessing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with numbers of arrests and protesters,
CORRECTS name of clinic; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Operation Rescue ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT JABLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested about 80 anti-abortion
protesters today at a clinic, the first target of an Easter season
offensive undertaken with a blessing from the head of the nation's
biggest Roman Catholic archdiocese.
   Some 400 members of Operation Rescue sang ``Jesus loves the
little children, all little children of the world,'' as the
protesters were dragged away from the Family Planning Associates
Medical Group clinic in Cypress, 20 miles from Los Angeles.
   The arrests brought cheers from about 150 counter-demonstrators,
who had chanted: ``Not the church, not the state, women will decide
our fate.''
   ``This is too big to ignore. We need to do something for our
voices to be heard,'' said Sue Otti, one of the pro-choice advocates.
   The anti-abortion protesters went limp as police in helmets and
face shields carried them away. Others crawled up to the clinic on
hands and knees to continue the blockades. They, too, were carried
off by police.
   Those arrested were taken on buses to the Orange County jail,
where they were to be issued misdemeanor citations for failing to
disperse, said sheriff's Lt. Dick Olson.
   Operation Rescue said it expected up to 2,500 people to protest
today at targeted clinics, with most willing to risk jail by
ignoring a federal court order against blocking entrances. The New
York-based group says 21,000 of its anti-abortion advocates have
been arrested in nationwide protests since 1987.
   Archbishop Roger Mahony lent his prayers to the demonstrators in
a statement issued Wednesday.
   ``I understand and respect the goals of Operation Rescue,
appreciate the manifestation by its participants of the value of
human life and the need to take active steps to safeguard each human
life from the moment of conception,'' he said. ``I offer my prayers
for those who choose to participate.''
   Pro-choice advocates, describing the demonstrators as bullies,
vowed the clinics would remain open throughout protests.
   Los Angeles officials, promising to enforce laws to keep the
clinics open, set up a command center four floors under City Hall,
just as they do to mobilize forces during earthquakes.
   Organizers of the protests Wednesday displayed what they said was
a human fetus in a small, white coffin at a news conference.
   ``This is `Baby Choice,''' said Randall Terry, founder of
Operation Rescue. ``She was killed at 19 weeks by a saline solution
abortion, and she will answer all your questions.'' Terry left
quickly, refusing to answer further questions.
   The archbishop ``has no comment on the tactics involved,'' said
Bill Rivera, a spokesman for the archdiocese, when asked about the
coffin display.
   One local anti-abortion group, the Right to Life League of
Southern California, declined to take part in the protests because
of the court order won March 13 by the American Civil Liberties
Union of Southern California.
   ``My heart is with these people, but I choose to operate within
the law,'' said president Susan Carpenter-McMillan.
</TEXT>
