<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     03-23 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Negotiators Hopeful of Accord When Talks Resume in April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budget talks between the White House and
Congress will continue into April as negotiators remain hopeful of
accord despite the slow pace of the talks, according to a statement
released Thursday.
   The secret sessions involving President Bush's aides and the
leaders of the House and Senate budget committees broke off
Wednesday until Congress returns next month from its Easter recess.
   The bargaining group released a letter Thursday, reporting to the
president and the congressional leadership that they believed their
talks may eventually bear fruit, a deficit-reduction plan for the
fiscal 1990 budget.
   The letter said the meetings have been ``cordial and
constructive'' and added: ``A number of budget options have been
discussed. We intend to continue to negotiate on the basis of these
and other options in an effort to reach a compromise.''
   The goal of the group is to agree on a plan for the $1.16
trillion budget that would meet the guidelines of the Gramm-Rudman
law, which calls for reducing the federal deficit to $100 billion in
fiscal 1990. The current year's deficit is expected to exceed $160
billion.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, one of the White House
negotiators, predicted Thursday a bipartisan agreement could be
negotiated which would not violate Bush's no-tax pledge.
   Bush proposed in his budget raising government revenues by about
$14 billion through a combination of tax increases, user fees, and
sales of government assets. However, the administration contends
none are ``new taxes.''
   In an appearance before the National Association of
Manufacturers, Brady also defended the economic assumptions
underlying the administration's budget. The forecast has been
attacked for using overly optimistic assumptions about economic
growth and interest rates.
   He said that a credible budget deficit reduction plan would lower
interest rates and the administration's growth forecast for 1989 and
1990 of 3.2 percent, as measured by the gross national product,
reflected the average growth rate of the economy over the past
several years.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, the chairman of the House Budget Committee,
said recent government reports indicating a possible return of
inflation ``haunt the negotiations'' and has helped spur the
negotiators toward creation of a substantive proposal.
   ``While it began with everybody thinking they really could slide
by'' with a minimal plan this year, the economic news has created
``a face-to-face confrontation with reality.''
   Panetta said Democrats were not going to propose raising taxes
any more than Bush. But he said one of his goals in the talks was to
make sure the $14 billion in revenue would actually be raised, and
that it was not a figure based on unrealistic expectations.
   A third of Bush's total is his estimate for revenue raised by
lowering the tax rate on capital gains, a proposal given little
chance on Capitol Hill.
   The talks are expected to resume April 3.
   Congress has an April 15 deadline for completing its annual
budget resolution, and it is unlikely a pact could be reached before
then. Congressional leaders have indicated the deadline could slip
somewhat.
</TEXT>
