<HEAD>Three Youths Board Unguarded British Airways Jumbo Jet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack Warning, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young men who boarded a jumbo jet at Heathrow
Airport and got into the cockpit said the caper proved the security
has not improved since a bomb brought down Pan Am Flight 103 over
Scotland.
   British Airways said it considered the breach to be extremely
serious, but stressed that the Boeing 747 was in a maintenance area
and was not operational.
   A videotape taken by three young men who said they boarded the
aircraft early Monday was shown Thursday by Independent Television
News.
   ``They say they are cracking down on security and they are
confident no-one else can do what happened at Lockerbie,'' said
Shoaib Khan, the only one of the three who was identified. ``It is
just not true.
   ``We want to prove the point and just want to tell the whole
world that they are not doing anything about it,'' he said. ``We did
break the law and we are ready to stand up and say it was us who did
it and this is the reason why we did it.''
   Airport security has been a sensitive issue since the bombing of
Pan Am Flight 103, which was blown apart Dec. 21 over Lockerbie,
Scotland, killing 270 people.
   The British Airways jet boarded by the young men reportedly was
at the airline's maintenance base adjoining Heathrow.
   The Transport Department said it was ``most concerned'' and had
asked British Airways for a report.
   ``It seems that the incident took place in the BA maintenance
area, which is BA's private property and outside the restricted area
of the airport on Monday morning,'' the department said.
   British Airways has its own security, but the young men said they
were not detected.
   John Prescott, the opposition Labor Party's transportation
spokesman, said the incident was a ``clear breach of security'' and
said in the House of Commons he wanted an explanation from Transport
Minister Paul Channon.
   ``He assured us in this House less than 70 hours ago that
security at Heathrow is OK,'' said Prescott. ``It is not, and the
traveling public are absolutely concerned about it.''
   Robert Adley, a lawmaker from the governing Conservative Party,
called for prosecution of the three.
   ``People who trespass, for whatever reason, are behaving as
irresponsibly as people who make hoax telephone calls, and should be
treated as such,'' Adley said.
   A spokesman for Scotland Yard said detectives would interview the
young men, but added there appeared to be no crime involved.
</TEXT>
