<FIRST>r a AM-CDC-Rubella     03-23 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC-Rubella,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rubella At All-time Low, But Risk In Childbearing-Age Women Still
A Worry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EST; Time set by source.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rubella has almost vanished in the United States
since a vaccine was licensed 20 years ago, but federal health
officials said Thursday they are concerned that a large number of
the remaining cases are occurring among adults.
   Preliminary figures released Thursday by the U.S. Centers for
Disease Control showed there were 221 cases of rubella, also known
as German measles, reported in 1988. A final count for 1987
indicated there were 306 cases of rubella, the CDC said.
   The 1988 figure amounted to about one case per 1 million people
and represented the lowest total since 1966, when the government
began compiling statistics on the disease. It was a 99 percent drop
from 1969, when the vaccine was licensed.
   The disease is fairly mild in most people, but it can cause
serious birth defects such as heart disease and mental retardation
in babies whose mothers are infected while pregnant. Because of
this, health officials are most worried about the risk of infection
to women of childbearing age.
   The CDC said its preliminary figures indicate there was just one
case reported last year of a baby born with signs of rubella
infection or related birth defects, down from three in 1987. But so
far this year, there have been three more cases reported of babies
with rubella or related problems.
   In 1980, the federal Public Health Service set a goal cutting the
number of overall cases to 1,000 by 1990, and the number of cases
among newborns to fewer than 10.
   Although both goals were reached years ahead of time,
``unacceptable morbidity is still occurring,'' the CDC said in its
weekly report.
   The CDC said people 15 and over accounted for 58.2 percent of all
U.S. rubella cases in 1985-87. Nationwide statistics from before the
rubella vaccine was licensed are not broken down by age group, the
CDC said, but data from areas that did count rubella cases by age
group during that time indicated that only about 23 percent of all
cases were in people 15 and over in 1966-68.
   ``The continued occurrence of rubella in childbearing-aged
populations suggests that potentially preventable cases of
congenital rubella syndrome may continue to occur during the next 10
to 30 years,'' the CDC said in its weekly report.
   Dr. Paul A. Stehr-Green, an epidemiologist with the Atlanta-based
CDC, said that during the last major rubella epidemic, in 1962-64,
there were 12.5 million cases reported in the United States,
including 20,000 babies born with the disease and 11,000 fetal
deaths.
   Stehr-Green said most of the rubella cases occurring now stem
from people failing to get vaccinated, though there are some cases
of the vaccine failing to work.
   ``This is more an issue of failure to vaccinate rather than a
failure of the vaccine,'' he said.
   The government recommends that children get rubella vaccine when
they are 15 months old. Stehr-Green said adults who have not had the
disease and are not sure if they've been vaccinated are advised to
get the shot again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0136 </DOCNO>
