<FIRST>u a PM-CatholicBingo 1stLd-Writethru a0530 03-23 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Catholic Bingo, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0530,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bishop Outlaws Bingo Games As Fund-Raisers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead to clarify.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Carolina's Roman Catholic bishop
has banned bingo in his diocese because he considers the game an
unseemly way of raising money.
   ``This is an evil in the country,'' Bishop Ernest Unterkoefler
said Wednesday. ``People think they are getting something for
nothing ... and we are aiding and abetting something that is not
good for society.
   ``I'm not saying gambling is sinful, but I am saying that under
state and church auspices, it is no way to raise money,'' he said.
   Instead, money should be raised by ``sacrificial giving'' by
churchgoers, the bishop said.
   The diocese, which covers the entire state, has 100,000
parishioners in about 100 parishes and missions. The directive
issued last week is one of the first such measures in the country,
said John Conick, a permanent deacon.
   The diocese could not say how many institutions would be affected
and how much revenue they would lose, but Cardinal Newman High
School in Columbia raises $70,000 through bingo games it must end by
July 1990.
   Bingo is legal in South Carolina if it is for the benefit of
charitable, religious or fraternal organizations. But state records
show that big-time promoters have found ways to get around the law
and keep most of the proceeds.
</TEXT>
