<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1824EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     03-23 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.-South Korean Forces End Team Spirit Exercises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200,000 U.S. and South Korean
troops ended joint military exercises Thursday, and a senior U.S.
commander said the annual maneuvers would help discourage aggression
by North Korea.
   Gen. Louis C. Menetrey said ``Team Spirit'' exercises were held
``solely to test and improve the capability of Korean and U.S.
military forces to deter war or defeat aggression on the Korean
peninsula.''
   Also Thursday, 13 U.S. Marines who were seriously injured in a
helicopter crash during the maneuvers left for the United States for
further medical treatment, a U.S. military spokesman said.
   Nineteen Marines were killed in the crash of a Sikorsky CH-53D
Sea Stallion helicopter on Monday near Pohang on the southeast
coast. Four others died in a separate crash March 17.
   Communist North Korea repeatedly demanded the exercises _ in
their 14th year _ be called off and claimed Team Spirit was a front
for U.S. war prepartions. Radical South Korean students have
protested the exercises, and opinion polls indicate many ordinary
South Koreans have a growing doubts about it.
   Menetrey said the exercises were necessary because North Korea
poses a major military threat to the south. He said the exercises
were purely defensive and North Korea's annual protests proved their
worth.
   ``The exercise threatens no one, North Korea or anyone else,''
Menetrey said. ``In fact, as an effective means to ensure our
defense readiness, Team Spirit is a major factor for peace.''
   The general expressed regret that North Korea had rejected an
invitation to send observers to Team Spirit to reassure the
Pyongyang government they posed no threat to the north.
   About 43,000 U.S. troops are based in the South under a mutual
defense treaty, and they were joined during the exercises by 27,000
from Okinawa, Hawaii and the U.S. mainland.
   U.S. forces have been based in the South since Washington
intervened in 1950 to aid the Seoul government against the North
Korean invasion that started the Korean War. The two Koreas are
still technically at war.
   A U.S. military spokesman said two C-141 transport planes
carrying 13 injured Marines left a military base near Seoul to carry
the burn victims to Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio, Texas.
   Two burn victims remained in good or fair condition at a Seoul
military hospital and were not evacuated to the United States, the
spokesman said.
   Monday's helicopter accident was still under investigation.
</TEXT>
