<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Press     03-23 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Press,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalists Protest Killing of Newsmen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Federation of
Journalists has protested the killing of three reporters in El
Salvador, urging a full investigation and measures to protect the
press.
   Salvadoran journalists Mauricio Pineda and Francisco Roberto
Navas and Dutch journalist Cornel Lagrouw were killed by Salvadoran
soldiers as they were covering the nation's elections Sunday.
   ``The people of your country will never be free, and your
democracy will never have substance until journalists can walk the
streets without fear,'' said Aidan White, secretary-general of the
federation. His the letter was released Thursday by the
Brussels-based organization.
   ``The killing of these journalists during a democratic election
is an outrage, not only to the profession of journalism but also to
democracy itself,'' White wrote to Salvadoran President Napoleon
Duarte and President-elect Alfredo Cristiani.
   ``We urge you to ensure that there is the fullest possible
investigation into each of the incidents,'' White added. ``This
inquiry should be immediate, should be thorough and should be
public.''
   ``The deaths come at a time when the democratic process is
gathering pace in your country and in other parts of Central
America,'' he added. ``But there is no democracy without human
rights and freedom of expression.
   ``Journalists, whose first duty is to serve the public interest,
are constantly under threat in the world today,'' White wrote.
``There are taken hostage in Beirut, they are detained without trial
in South Africa, they are brutally murdered in political struggles
in Peru or in the Philippines.
   ``I urge you to take urgent action to protect journalists in El
Salvador from further attacks,'' White told Duarte and Christiani.
   The federation represents more than 150,000 journalists worldwide.
</TEXT>
