<FIRST>r a AM-HolyHumor     03-23 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holy Humor,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merry Christians Celebrate Religion With Good Humor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As serious and solemn as religious
holidays can be, there is plenty of room for humor. Just ask Cal
Samra on ``Easter Monday.''
   That's the first day of the Holy Humor Season, a monthlong
celebration created by Samra's Fellowship of Merry Christians, a
Kalamazoo-based ecumenical group that believes there's a serious
lack of humor in faith.
   Between 100 and 200 churches in 24 states are expected to
celebrate Monday in their own funny way. Festivities, built around
the resurrection, will include sing-alongs and joke-tellings
sessions. The Merry Christians say raising Jesus from the dead was
the ultimate in practical jokes that God played on Satan.
   Samra, who says his 3-year-old group has 10,000 members, believes
humor and Christianity often are thought of as mutually exclusive.
   ``There are two traditions in Christianity: there's a lot of joy
and humor and there's also a tradition of solemnity. We felt things
had gotten out of balance and we thought we should focus on
Christian humor, Christian wit, Christian joy,'' Samra said.
   In his bimonthly publication ``The Joyful Noiseletter,'' Samra
relays references of joy from the New Testament as well as
religious-oriented anecdotes and jokes from the famous and
not-so-famous:
   ``The good Lord didn't create anything without a purpose, but the
fly comes close'' _ Mark Twain.
   ``Question: What do you get if you cross a praying mantis with a
termite? Answer: An insect that says grace before he eats your
house.''
   Samra figures that if he can bring an occasional chuckle _ or
even a grin _ to those he touches, he has served his purpose.
   His theory, which is shared by scholars and scientists, is that
humor is healing.
   Samra, who began collecting rare drawings that depict Jesus with
a smile, described his theory in a book, ``The Joyful Christ,''
published in 1986 by Harper &amp; Row.
   Herb True, an adjunct professor at the University of Notre Dame,
applauds Samra's work. He believes most members of the clergy would
be receptive to it.
   ``Comedy is meant to get laughs _ usually at someone else's
expense. But humor is a form of love. It's purpose is to lift the
load,'' said True, a psychologist who claims to have the nation's
only humor database.
   Samra said about half the fellowship's subscribers are members of
the clergy with nearly every denomination represented. Other members
are health professionals and humorists. Even clowns.
   But not everyone agrees that religion should be presented in a
lighthearted manner.
   ``There is a tiny minority out there who have difficulty with the
concept of the joyful Christ,'' Samra said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0142 </DOCNO>
