<FIRST>r w AM-InsuranceAntitrust     03-23 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insurance Antitrust,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Urged to Narrow Insurance Industry's Exemptions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankers and consumer-advocacy groups urged
Congress on Thursday to narrow the insurance industry's exemptions
from antitrust laws.
   ``Consumers suspect they're not getting their money's worth from
insurers,'' said Philip S. Corwin of the American Bankers
Association.
   ``How could they,'' he said, ``when price collusion at the
wholesale level is permitted by the antitrust exemption; competition
at the retail level is inhibited by (state) anti-rebate laws; and
the potential market entrant with the greatest ability to provide
new underwriting capacity and more efficient distribution, the
banking industry, is barred at the door?''
   In testimony to the commerce, consumer protection and
competitiveness subcommittee of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee, Corwin endorsed in general terms a bill by the
subcommittee chairman, Rep. James J. Florio, D-N.J., to forbid some
collective activities that insurance companies may engage in under
their antitrust exemptions.
   Several insurance companies and trade groups argued against
Florio's bill, contending it would lead to a reduction in the number
of companies offering property and casualty insurance.
   Rep. Don Ritter, R-Pa., said he would ``not stand idly by'' if he
thought Congress would jeopardize the existence of any companies in
his home state.
   ``Evidence has not been forthcoming'' to justify a need to change
the present system, Ritter said.
   Peggy Miller of the Consumer Federation of America said ``this
legislation will not cure'' problems of high premium costs and
limited availability of auto, health and life insurance, but only
provide ``one critically needed step.''
   There is no federal regulation of insurance, which is left to the
states under a 1945 law.
   Florio's bill would forbid the sharing of information to
determine premiums or coverage areas, bar ``tie-in'' sales such as
requirements that motorists buy a homeowner's policy with their auto
policy, and ban ``any action to impair the availability or
affordability of insurance.'' Companies could still share loss and
reserve data.
   Craig A. Berrington, a lawyer for the American Insurance
Association representing member casualty and property insurers, said
the tie-in prohibition appeared so strict ``it would have prevented
the marketing of today's standard homeowner's policy ... (and) the
marketing of commercial multiperil policies. And it would prevent
innovation in the future.''
   However, Linda A. Lipsen, representing Consumers Union, said such
purchase requirements currently ``leave virtually no avenues for
redress.''
   ``If the only butcher in town conditioned the sale of deluxe
boneless chicken breasts on the purchase of soup bones, such conduct
might be subject to a substantial fine,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
