<FIRST>r a AM-SovietBread     03-23 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Bread,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet `Peace Bread' Comes to America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A millionaire with a hankering for Russian
pumpernickel has struck a deal with the Soviet Union to fly 2,000
loaves a week to New York consumers.
   ``I thought it was an interesting metaphor _ breaking bread with
the Russians; I call it peace bread,'' said Fred Kayden, 58, of
Harrison, who describes himself as a ``retired multimillionaire.''
   Kayden grew to love Russian bread during his business travels,
and always brought home a few loaves. ``It's like old-fashioned
bread, with no preservatives,'' he said.
   Two months ago, he began talks with Valery Saikin, chairman of
the Moscow city council, who arranged the venture with help from
Aeroflot and the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Trade and Economic Council.
   The bread will be served at the Waldorf-Astoria and New York
Hilton hotels, and sold at 15 Zaro's Bread Basket stores in the
metropolitan area at a price of $4 to $5 for a 2-pound loaf.
   ``The Russian bread has a slightly sour taste that you would find
in a traditional Jewish rye bread, but with even more flavor and
taste,'' said Stuart Zaro, president of Zaro's.
   ``It has a very good shelf life because it's very dense and
moist,'' said John Doherty, executive chef of the Waldorf.
   The officials sampled four varieties during a Waldorf taste-test
Wednesday: regular rye, Unzhensky, Darnitzky and Borodino _ the
latter a dark, slightly sweet bread, lightly laced with caraway
seeds, anise and coriander.
   They ordered 500 loaves of each, and will let the public decide
what kind to import in the future.
</TEXT>
