<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     03-23 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Washes Feet of Young Priests in Holy Thursday Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II knelt before 12 young priests and
washed their feet Thursday evening in a re-enactment of the Jesus
Christ's Last Supper with his apostles.
   Thousands of worshipers packed the vast, marble-columned Basilica
of St. John Lateran, which is considered the pope's special church
as bishop of Rome, for the solemn Holy Thursday ceremony.
   Earlier in the day, the pope led 1,200 clergymen in renewing
their priestly vows in a Mass in St. Peter's Basilica.
   The services marked the beginning of four of the most important
days in the Roman Catholic calendar, marking the crucifixion of
Jesus Christ and his resurrection on Easter Sunday.
   John Paul, wearing white robes trimmed with gold, washed the feet
of a dozen priests from different countries who are studying in
Rome, in a ritual symbolizing Jesus' humility before he was
crucified on Good Friday.
   The pope poured water from a golden urn onto the foot of each of
the priests, who were seated on a platform beneath the altar and
wore gold robes. The pope then wiped each foot with a white cloth
and gently kissed it.
   Three of the priests were from Taiwan, two were from Nigeria and
two from Zaire. The others were from Uganda, the Philippines, South
Korea, Vietnam and Italy.
   The pope then celebrated Mass and delivered a homily on the
subject of Christian unity and reconciliation between people of
different countries and classes.
   ``All of us, who share the bread of the Eucharist, open ourselves
toward our brothers in the exercise of an authentic charity that
finds its realization in the family, in the professional world, in
schools, in the community and in society,'' he said.
   Catholics mark the Last Supper as the gathering at which Christ
instituted the Mass, the sacrament of the priesthood, and the
Eucharist _ the transformation of bread and wine into his body and
blood.
   On Friday, the pope will carry a wooden cross in a Good Friday
procession near the Colosseum. He will celebrate the Easter vigil on
Saturday night followed on Easter Sunday by a Mass in St. Peter's
Square.
   During the Mass on Thursday, the John Paul blessed the holy oils
used at baptisms, confirmations and the consecrations of bishops.
   Twenty-four cardinals, 50 bishops and 1,200 priests took part in
the service before about 10,000 people.
</TEXT>
