<FIRST>r i AM-Priestess     03-23 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Priestess,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uganda's Lakwena in Kenya, Not at Riotous Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ugandan warrior-priestess Alice Lakwena did
not flee a rioting refugee camp in central Kenya earlier this week
because she was never there, a U.N. official said Thursday.
   ``She has been in Kenya, but she wasn't in a camp,'' said Ernest
Allison, a U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees official in Nairobi.
``After her release from prison, she was placed in what was
considered a safe hideout. The government of Kenya knew where she
was and we knew where she was.''
   Allison would not say where that ``hideout'' was, whether Ms.
Lakwena still was there, or what she was doing. He said she had not
been placed in a group.
   Allison said that since early 1988 when Ms. Lakwena finished a
four-month jail sentence for entering Kenya illegally, she has been
under U.N. auspices while her application for asylum is under
consideration.
   ``The application is still being processed,'' said Allison. ``It
has neither been approved nor rejected.''
   A local newspaper Tuesday reported Ms. Lakwena was among more
than 100 refugees who fled from a U.N. camp in Thika, 27 miles north
of Nairobi, on Monday after rioting refugees damaged a car, broke
doors and beat up a storekeeper.
   Ms. Lakwena, 28, who called herself a medium of God, fled to
Kenya in December 1987 after Ugandan government forces defeated her
yearlong suicidal crusade to wrest power from President Yoweri
Museveni.
   Her forces were battalions of believers she inspired to go into
battle singing hymns, their chests smeared with oil they believed
would repel bullets and armed with stones she said would explode
like grenades.
   Thousands of her followers died before Museveni's army crushed
her campaign.
   Museveni's government has not asked for Ms. Lakwena's
extradition, according to O. Adala, head of the Africa division in
Kenya's Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
   However, Allison said he could not elaborate in detail on Ms.
Lakwena's circumstances because of the ``nature of the case'' and
Uganda's interest in it.
</TEXT>
