<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls     03-23 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress May Cut Proposed $1 Million-a-Day Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress will consider reducing the $1
million-a-day fines proposed by President Bush as part of a
crackdown on fraud in the savings and loan industry, a House
subcommittee chairman said Thursday.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., chairman of the Judiciary
subcommittee on criminal justice, said in an interview that he
supported stiffer fines, but added, ``We have to discuss how much to
raise them.''
   Bush is proposing an increase from $1,000 to $25,000 a day for
most violations of banking regulations but up to $1 million daily if
the violation was made with reckless disregard for the safety of the
institution.
   Edward L. Yingling, executive director of government relations
for the American Bankers Association, in testimony to Schumer's
panel, said such ``extraordinarily harsh penalties'' could prevent
banks and S&amp;Ls from attracting qualified managers and directors.
   ``Increasing civil money penalties to such a substantial amount
sets a dangerous precedent giving regulators the power to assess
penalties that could threaten the stability of an institution,'' he
said.
   Yingling also objected to provisions of the Bush proposal
permitting regulators to decide when a violation was committed with
reckless disregard, triggering the $1 million penalty. He said fines
should be capped at $2,500 a day.
   Schumer, during a break in the hearing, said, ``I think that's
too low, but I think you could find a happy medium.''
   After the House Banking Committee acts on legislation next month,
other panels, including Schumer's, likely will amend sections coming
within their jurisdiction.
   Officials of the General Accounting Office, a congressional
investigative agency, told the subcommittee earlier that most of the
money lost by failed thrifts is attributable to fraud rather than
adverse economic conditions or deregulation. They said the GAO
examined 26 insolvent savings and loans in eight states and found
evidence of fraud or abusive insider dealing in each.
   As part of a broader bill to bail out the insurance fund backing
S&amp;L deposits, Bush is proposing spending $50 million a year on
discovering and prosecuting fraud at banks and S&amp;Ls.
   Schumer suggested that more spending might enable the Justice
Department to prosecute a greater proportion of the 4,000 pending
fraud cases involving losses of $100,000 or more.
   But the acting associate attorney general, Joe Whitely, declined
to ask for an appropriation larger than recommended by the president.
   Meanwhile, David Lewis, a New York attorney representing the
National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, said the Bush bill
represents ``a permanent threat to the rights of the people of this
nation'' and a ``blatant attempt to avoid the Constitution in
exchange for a quick economic score for the government coffers.''
   He specifically criticized provisions that would give financial
institution investigators greater access to grand jury testimony,
which is normally considered secret, and that would extend the
statute of limitations for bank fraud from five years to 10 years.
   The ABA's Yingling complained that a proposal to pay rewards of
up to $100,000 for information leading to bank fraud convictions
could ``lead to widespread abuse by disgruntled employees or
disappointed customers.'' He predicted that overworked authorities
``would be inundated with tidbits or hunches.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
