<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Soviet     03-23 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Soviet,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Welcomes Soviet Agreement on More Talks on Territory Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the Soviet position remains ``very rigid''
against returning a group of northern islands to Japan, Tokyo
welcomes Moscow's willingness to continue talks, a Foreign Ministry
official said Thursday.
   The nations concluded three days of working-level meetings on
Tuesday without reaching any agreement on the territorial dispute
over the Kuril islands that blocks a peace treaty to formally end
World War II hostilities.
   ``It is noteworthy that this session has taken place and both
sides agreed to have another round of talks on this issue,''
ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe said at a briefing.
   ``This is something we welcome. I think we do share the common
recognition about the need to continue dialogue of this kind,'' he
added.
   The Soviet Union long has balked at even talking about the
islands off northern Japan that the Soviets seized at the end of
World War II. About 10,000 Soviet troops are stationed there.
   This time, Watanabe said, they decided to spell out their views
on the issue, ``almost for the first time.''
   The Japanese contend there never had been any question about the
islands being under Japanese rule until after World War II.
   Rather than discussing the legal points of the issue, the Soviets
insisted they had taken the lead in discovery and exploration of the
islands, Watanabe said.
   ``This is a working group discussion rather than a kind of pure
negotiations and the purpose of this is ... to deepen understanding
of the positions of each party,'' Watanabe said. ``We have found out
the Russian position is very rigid on this territory issue.''
   Asked how the talks had affected a possible visit to Japan by
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Watanabe said, ``Having
studied the position of the Japanese government, if the Soviet
leader decides to come, that is welcome. ... It is up to them
whether they would decide to come.''
   Japanese Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno will visit Moscow in May.
   The working-level talks were headed by Vice Foreign Ministers
Igor Rogachev of the Soviet Union and Takakazu Kuriyama of Japan.
   They also took up Soviet-China relations, tensions in Korea and
Vietnam's withdrawal of troops from Cambodia, Foreign Ministry
officials said.
</TEXT>
