<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     03-23 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stroessner Son Ordered Arrested for `Illegal Enrichment'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered the arrest of
deposed dictator Alfredo Stroessner's son, Gustavo, for receiving
millions of dollars in ``illegal enrichment,'' officials said
Thursday.
   The younger Stroessner, an air force colonel, accompanied his
father into exile in neighboring Brazil on Feb. 5, two days fter
Gen. Andres Rodriguez seized power in a coup.
   Judge Dario Caballero Bracho ordered Gustavo Stroessner's arrest
late Wednesday after receiving a police report describing how he
``illictly obtained copious amounts of money.''
   The report, published in part Thursday by the newspaper El
Diario, describes the colonel as a ``fugitive.'' Officials said the
court could seek an extradition order after an investigation of the
charges.
   According to the police report, Col. Stroessner received at least
$725,000 a month from three Asuncion bingo houses in 1985-88.
   ``He used psychological pressure, saying `If you don't give me my
cut I can close the business or give it to someone else,''' said
police spokesman Osvaldo Palacios. ``Everyone knew this man had the
power to decide.''
   Gambling is legal in Paraguay. Bingo houses and casinos are
licensed by the government.
   The police report also said Gustavo Stroessner was a major
stockholder in the insurance company Mundo S.A., which won several
contracts from builders of two hydroelectric projects: Itaipu on the
Brazilian border and Yacyreta on the border with Argentina.
   It said he received $21 million in insurance fees from Itaipu
alone.
   ``Part of this money was ill-gotten while another portion was a
legitimate result of the business,'' Palacios said.
   Col. Stroessner ``used his influence to obtain contracts for
third parties ... in exchange for cash award,'' the report said.
   Interior Minister Orlando Machuca Vargas said four officials of
Alfredo Stroessner's government had been sent to the interior of the
country ``for security reasons'' during the investigation of charges
against them.
   He identified them as Pastor Coronel, former chief of police
investigations; Delfin Ugarte Centurion, who was industry and
commerce minister; Gen. Gaspar Martinez, former defense minister,
and Roberto Velazquez Excobar, a former legislative leader.
   Charges against them include corruption and illegal enrichment,
Machuca said.
   Police deported Alejandro Mella Latorre, 39, a Chilean who served
six years for participating in the 1980 assassination in Asuncion of
deposed President Anastasio Somoza of Nicaragua. Mella Latorre was
put on a Thursday morning flight to Santiago, Chile.
</TEXT>
