<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     03-23 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discovery Takes Off on Piggyback Ride Back to Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The shuttle Discovery,
which flew a successful five-day space mission last week, began its
return flight to Florida on Thursday atop a Boeing 747 transport.
   The modified jumbo jet took off shortly after 11 a.m., bound for
Kelly Air Force Base, Texas, where it was to remain overnight and
continue the ferry flight to Kennedy Space Center on Friday, said
NASA spokeswoman Nancy Lovato.
   Discovery was launched March 13 on a 79-orbit mission that
deployed that last of three Tracking and Data Relay Satellites to
complete the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's shuttle
communications system.
   The orbiter landed at dawn Saturday in the California desert. It
was originally scheduled to begin a one-day flight to Florida at
dawn Friday but preparations went smoothly and the journey began a
day early.
   The flight had to be broken into two days, however, because the
takeoff was delayed by a problem with a mechanical lift used to
hoist technicians up to the plane-mounted shuttle.
</TEXT>
