<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Press     03-23 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Press,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Warning Issued to Newspaper Before First Edition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is threatening
punitive action against an anti-apartheid newspaper even before it
publishes its first regular edition, a spokesman for the newspaper
said Thursday.
   The newspaper, The New African, could be required to pay a
registration fee of about $16,000 to begin publishing as planned on
April 3, said spokesman Ricky Naidoo.
   The weekly, intended to serve readers in Natal Province, received
a letter last week from the Justice Ministry saying a registration
fee was under consideration.
   The government does not automatically charge a fee for a new
publication, but may do so if it rules that the publication may
later be banned for violating security regulations.
   The letter said Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee had received
information that The New African's staff was ``committed to the
South African liberation sturggle.''
   ``Information at the minister's disposal indicates that The New
African will probably operate on similar lines as the New Nation,''
said the letter, referring to a Johannesburg-based weekly newspaper
shut down by the government for three months last year for allegedly
publishing subversive material.
   Naidoo said The New African's lawyers would talk to the
government in hopes of avoiding or minimizing any fee, and expected
to get a final ruling next week.
   In a response to Coetsee, The New African protested ``the way in
which a small publication like our own is placed in jeopardy in
advance of publication.''
   The Association of Democratic Journalists, which often criticizes
government censorship, said the threat against The New African shows
the government ``has so little legitimacy that it cannot afford to
allow even a single new critical voice to be raised against it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
