<FIRST>r i AM-Gavroche     03-23 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gavroche,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three-Star Restaurant Beats Health Rap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Le Gavroche:
   ``Three stars'' _ Michelin guide.
   ``Two stars'' _ Egon Ronay.
   ``Not guilty'' _ Wells Street Magistrates Court.
   Magistrate Terence English on Thursday exonerated restaurateur
Albert Roux, who had been charged with 15 counts of health and
safety violations after inspectors reported ``disgusting''
conditions in his kitchen in 1986.
   English said he was not convinced by the evidence of the health
inspector, Alexander Parker-Brown, who admitted in court he had
never read the regulations governing his job. He also conceded he
had asked Roux to autograph a book for his wife.
   ``I have been referred to in the foreign press as a `reborn
Napoleon' _ but he met his Waterloo. I have not met mine,'' Roux
said before taking his wife Monique away for a celebratory glass of
champagne.
   ``I am a fighter. I like a fight. When you have worked all your
life from the age of 14 building up a reputation and suddenly a Mr.
Parker-Brown comes into your life and tries to destroy everything
you have worked for, you have to fight.''
   Roux had been charged with 11 counts under the food hygiene rules
and four under the industrial health and safety regulations. The
city will reimburse him for the cost of his defense, which Roux said
was about $170,000.
   Health inspectors had reported finding flies, grease and dirt in
the restaurant's kitchen, and pigeon droppings and cigarette butts
covering refrigerators outdoors.
   Prosecution witnesses included an entomologist who brought a
foot-high model of a fly to help explain how flies eat.
   Parker-Brown has said that in a follow-up inspection, the
restaurant's kitchens were among the cleanest he had ever seen.
   The Michelin guide had reaffirmed the restaurant's three-star
rating while the trial was being held. The only other Michelin
three-star restaurant in Britain, the Waterside Inn at Bray, is
owned by Roux's brother, Michel. The restaurant earned two stars in
Egon Ronay's guide book.
   The Roux brothers are famous in Britain because of their cooking
show on BBC-TV.
</TEXT>
