<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1631EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-ThinBlueLine 2ndLd-Writethru a0623 03-23 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thin Blue Line, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0623,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Thin Blue Line' Defendant Leaves Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with prosecutors dropping case;
Picks up 7th graf, `Adams originally ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors today decided not to retry Randall
Dale Adams for the 1976 slaying of a policeman, as Adams left the
state that imprisoned him for 12 years for a murder to which another
man has all but confessed.
   Dallas County District Attorney John Vance said the case has been
dropped because there is not enough evidence to try Adams again.
   Adams, who was freed on bail Tuesday after an appeals court March
1 overturned his 1977 conviction for killing a Dallas policeman,
boarded a plane this morning for Ohio, where his family lives, said
his attorney's office.
   ``I'll be glad to get back to Ohio,'' he said Wednesday. ``No
offense, but I hate Texas.''
   Adams, whose conviction was questioned in the 1988 documentary
film ``The Thin Blue Line,'' was headed for Grove City, outside
Columbus, where his mother, Mildred, had decorated her trailer with
yellow ribbons.
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals overturned Adams' conviction
for killing Patrolman Robert Wood, saying prosecutors withheld
evidence and used perjured testimony.
   Adams originally was sentenced to death and at one point was
three days from being executed, but his sentence was commuted to
life in prison in 1980.
   Despite his experience, the 40-year-old Adams said the state's
judicial system ``in my case worked. Texas did not execute me.''
   Adams has called Dallas County ``hell on earth'' but said he
holds no grudge against Texans.
   ``I do not blame the people of Dallas or the people of Texas for
the actions of a few,'' he said.
   He also reiterated that he would welcome the chance to come back
and clear his name in a retrial.
   ``Of course I would love to have a jury release me in Dallas,''
he said. ``I did not kill Robert Wood.''
   ``I believe that if the retrial happens, we may be able to
receive some answers as to why all of this happened, and I would
like that,'' Adams said.
   His case gained international attention after the release of
``The Thin Blue Line.'' The documentary questioned the testimony of
then-16-year-old David Harris of Vidor, Texas, who had picked up
Adams the day of the shooting after Adams' car ran out of gas.
   Wood was killed after stopping a car for a traffic violation.
Adams has said Harris dropped him off before the shooting occurred.
   During the trial, Harris was the state's key witness, saying he
saw Adams kill Wood. But the film showed Harris recanting his
accusations, as well as other witnesses reporting information that
conflicted with their testimony. Harris all but confessed to the
shooting, and is on death row for another slaying.
   Adams said he has received a few job offers but has no specific
plans. He said he hasn't quite grasped the fact that he is finally
free.
   ``I just want to go home. I will see where I stand at that
point,'' he said.
</TEXT>
