<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Trials     03-23 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Trials,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Opens For Cultural Activist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a cultural activist
facing charges that could jail her for up to five years adjourned
Thursday after a preliminary hearing, a leading dissident said.
   The trial of Eva Vidlarova on charges of obstruction of execution
of a state decision opened in the Moravian capital of Brno, said
Charter 77 activist Anna Sabatova.
   Vidlarova, a leading theater worker in the city, was detained
Dec. 19 for allegedly obstructing an investigation against another
independent cultural activist in Brno last fall.
   Sabatova said Vidlarova, who was in detention until two or three
weeks ago, denies the charge.
   About 60 people were in the courtroom for Thursday's hearing,
Sabatova said. The next hearing in the case is set for April 5, she
said.
   The trial of Dusan Skala, an independent publisher detained last
fall, opens Friday in a town near Brno, Sabatova said. He faces
charges of preparation to incitement that could jail him for up to
five years.
   The trials are the latest in a widespread crackdown on dissent
that has jailed at least seven leading activists, including the
dissident playwright Vaclav Havel, and has led to suspended
sentences and fines for dozens of other activists and sympathizers.
</TEXT>
