<DOCNO> AP890323-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Nitze     03-23 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nitze,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Denies Nitze Forced Out of Arms Control Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, stepping into a State
Department spat, worked out a compromise with Paul H. Nitze that
keeps the veteran arms control specialist working for Secretary of
State James A. Baker III on a part-time basis, U.S. officials said
Thursday.
   Nitze, who at 82 can look back on nearly a half-century in
government life, wanted to stay on the job full-time as the Bush
administration prepares to resume negotiations with the Soviet Union
on nuclear weapons reductions.
   But, the officials said, he initially was offered only the role
of ambassador-emeritus, meaning he would be on occasional call, and
turned it down.
   ``There was no major spat,'' an official told The Associated
Press. ``It was all handled in a gentlemanly way.''
   But still, the officials said on condition of anonymity, Nitze
had freed his staff to take other jobs and was prepared to leave
himself until Bush invited him to the White House a few weeks ago to
discuss the situation.
   The session, the officials said, produced the compromise that he
would be a part-time consultant to the president and to Baker. His
resignation as a full-time adviser, effective May 1, still stands.
   Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, rejected
published accounts that linked Nitze's departure to disagreements
with Baker over what Nitze's job would be in the Bush
administration, saying the reports were ``unfortunate because they
are inaccurate.''
   ``Having talked to both sides I feel confident in assuring you
that there was not that kind of atmosphere involved in this
particular case,'' Redman said.
   Nitze, under former Secretary of State George P. Shultz, played a
key role in the U.S.-Soviet treaty signed in 1987 to abolish
intermediate-range nuclear missiles. His government service began
nearly 50 years ago.
   ``Having talked to both sides I feel confident in assuring you
that there was not that kind of atmosphere involved in this
particular case,'' Redman said.
   Nitze, under former Secretary of State George P. Shultz, played a
key role in the U.S.-Soviet treaty signed in 1987 to abolish
intermediate-range nuclear missiles. His government service began
nearly 50 years ago.
   Meanwhile, Nitze's office said Thursday that he is in a hospital
here recovering from surgery for a broken pelvis suffered when his
horse fell during a riding jaunt two weeks ago.
