<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-WomenPolice     03-23 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Women Police,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women Police Officers Wind Up International Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOORDWIJKERHOUT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 women police
officers from 39 countries called for better career opportunities
Thursday as they ended a conference on issues ranging from child
care at the police station to sexual harassment in the patrol car.
   ``Although more and more women are now pursuing a career in law
enforcement, the top slots in police organizations worldwide remain
in the hands of men,'' said Maj. Marian de Labije, one of the Dutch
organizers of the four-day meet.
   ``And that means that it also remains very difficult to draw the
attention of the higher echelons to the problems facing female
police personnel,'' Ms. De Labije said.
   She noted only a handful of about 100 male Dutch police
commanders and other law enforcement dignitaries invited to the
conference's opening Monday showed up.
   The conference, the first of its kind to be held outside North
America, where women police officers founded their organization as
early as in 1915, was attended by women police officers from nations
ranging from Bahrain to the United States to Zimbabwe.
   ``What we ought to do is change the minds of men, their dinosaur
mentality,'' said Kathy Burke, a detective in the Narcotics Division
of the New York City police department and the president of the
International Association of Women Police Officers, an organization
with members in the United States and Canada.
   ``Men and women must train side by side to convince the men that
we're not just the captain's girl,'' Ms. Burke said in an interview
in this western Dutch town 20 miles southwest of Amsterdam.
   In the Netherlands, 7 percent of the nation's 30,000-member
police force is female, a figure that reflects the situation in many
parts of the world, said Ms. De Labije. In New York, 3,000 of the
city's 28,000 police officers are women.
   The Dutch want to increase the women's share to 25 percent by
1995, but Ms. De Labije said it's unlikely that goal will be met.
   One of the problems facing women in law enforcement is proper
child care, said Ms. Burke, who brought her two children to the
conference.
   ``In New York, they're trying to develop a child care system, but
so far, only civil personnel is benefiting from it because it's a
9-to-5 scheme,'' Ms. Burke said. ``It's worthless to people who're
working in shifts.''
   The only area where proper child care facilities are less of a
roadblock is Africa, where such care traditionally has been part of
the extended family, said Ms. de Labije, an officer in the Juvenile
Department of the Dutch National Police.
   One of the conference's workshops dealt with sexual behavior in a
mixed police force, but the problem of harassment seems to be on the
wane, according to Superintendant Phyllis Nolan of the Police
Community Relations Department in Dublin, Ireland.
   ``It is easier now for female officers now that there is total
integration, now all sections are open to women,'' said Ms. Nolan.
   ``The acceptance is good, and we have women in all departments,
from motorcycle patrol people to special branch detectives,'' said
Ms. Nolan, who noted that until 1974, women police officers were
forced to resign from the Irish Garda when they married.
   At the meeting, participants from Western Europe founded the
European Network for Policewomen, which plans another conference in
two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
