<DOCNO> AP890323-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1652EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     03-23 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>15 Killed, 11 Wounded in Artillery Duels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian army gunners and allied Druse
militiamen fought artillery duels with Christian army units
Thursday, and police said 15 people were killed and 42 wounded.
   Most of the casualties were civilians in Christian east Beiruts,
where rockets sometimes landed at the rate of 40 a minute.
   A police spokesman said the dead included an 80-year-old woman
who was crossing the street in east Beirut's Saloumeh residential
district. A Lebanese soldier also was wounded, police said.
   The new casualities brought the toll to 81 killed and 253 wounded
since fighting began March 8 between Gen. Michel Aoun, who commands
the 20,000 Christians in the Lebanese army, and the Druse militia
led by Walid Jumblatt.
   Other Moslem militias and the 22,000 Moslem soldiers led by Maj.
Gen. Sami Khatib appear to have stayed out of the dispute. The
fighting threatens Arab League efforts to mediate a political crisis
that split the army on sectarian lines and created competing
Christian and Moslem governments.
   Aoun heads the Christian government in addition to commanding the
army's Christian units.
   More than 5,000 shells and rockets landed overnight in both
sectors of the capital, in the Christian region to the north and
east, and Druse-held territory to the southeast.
   Residents of Aramoun, seven miles south of Beirut, said Syrian
gunners operated rocket launchers overnight from the hill on which
the village sits. It was the first independent confirmation of
Syrian involvement.
   Aoun has accused Syria of firing on the 310-square-mile Christian
region, where 1 million Christians live in a crescent-shaped enclave
with the Mediterranean at their backs.
   One witness in Aramoun said Syrian rocket launchers were
``pouring fire all night at the Christian sector.''
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon and has become the country's
main power broker during a 14-year civil war. Aoun has declared a
``war of liberation'' against the Syrian forces.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said all
foreign troops except for peacekeepers of the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon should leave the country.
   Asked if that included Syria, Redman said: ``That would be all
those non-Lebanese armed elements and organizations currently on
Lebanese soil, with the exception of UNIFIL.''
   The thuds of exploding shells echoed across Beirut and the
surrounding wooded mountains. Residents huddled in basements and
bomb shelters.
   The latest violence began two days after Aoun blockaded private
ports militias use to finance their operations, which skim the
government otherwise would collect at the five legal harbors on
Lebanon's 130-mile coastline.
   Lebanon's government has been divided since Sept. 22, when
Parliament could not agree on a successor to President Amin Gemayel
and he appointed Aoun to lead an interim military cabinet.
   Moslems rejected the appointment and swore allegiance to Salim
Hoss, the Sunni Moslem premier who served during Gemayel's term.
   Under an unwritten national covenant dating to independence from
France in 1943, Lebanon's president is a Christian, the premier a
Sunni and the parliament speaker a Shiite Moslem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
