<FIRST>r w AM-EggOutput     03-23 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egg Output,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>It Breaks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egg production is down about 6 percent from a
year ago, mostly reflecting a sharp cutback by producers, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Total production during the first three months of the marketing
year that began Dec. 1 was estimated at 16.7 billion eggs, down from
17.7 billion a year earlier, the department said in a report.
   As of March 1, laying hens totaled 271 million, down from 282
million a year ago. The March 1 flock included about 232 million
hens producing eggs for consumer use, and 38.9 million producers of
hatching-type eggs.
   The department's Economic Research Service says 1989 egg
production is expected to be down around 2 percent fromf last year
because of the reduction in laying hens.
   Producers cut back flocks in response to the lowest net returns
since USDA began estimating those figures in 1972, the agency said.
</TEXT>
