<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Rights     03-23 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Rights,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Lawyer Dies One Day After Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A human rights lawyer died of his
injuries one day after being shot by an unidentified gunman, a human
rights organization said Thursday.
   Oscar Tonog, 37, was the sixth human rights lawyer slain during
the administration of President Corazon Aquino.
   He died Wednesday from bullet wounds to the head and chest
suffered in Tuesday's attack in Catarman, capital of Northern Samar
province, about 300 miles southeast of Manila, according to the Free
Legal Assistance Group.
   Word of his death reached Manila on Thursday shortly after the
group sent a chartered plane to transfer Tonog to Manila for
surgery, said Milabel Cristobal, a member of the group.
   The group on Wednesday blamed the attack on the military, which
has also been accused of involvement in the previous killings of
lawyers. The military has denied most of the charges.
   A member of a government-organized militia was convicted of
murder after admitting he was the gunman in the 1988 slaying of
human rights lawyer Alfonso Surigao last year, but charges were
dropped against a military major whom the gunman identified as the
mastermind. The other killings remain unsolved.
   All the victims were members of the legal assistance group or
other human rights organizations. They all acted as defense
attorneys for people accused of either being communist rebels or of
supporting the insurgents.
   ``These attacks against human rights lawyers also symbolize a
breakdown in the judicial machinery and the death of the rule of
law,'' the group said. ``While no lawyer is safe to fight for
people's rights in the courts, due process and other guarantees of
human rights enshrined in the constitution remain beautiful but
empty phrases.''
   The group said Wednesday that four gunmen attacked Tonog while he
and his wife, Merlita, were at a roadside shed waiting for a ride
home during a heavy rain. Mrs. Tonog was not hurt.
   On Thursday, it said only one gunman was involved and that he
shot Tonog from point-blank range in the head, chest and back. The
gunman fled aboard a motorcycle driven by an unidentified companion.
   Tonog had received many death threats recently, the group said.
He survived a knife attack in 1981 in his Catarman law office, and
the assailant, a policeman, was arrested, tried and convicted.
   Mrs. Aquino ordered investigations into the other killings after
human rights and lawyers' groups charged it was only since she took
over from deposed President Ferdinand Marcos three years ago that
lawyers were being killed for defending alleged subversives.
   During Marcos' 20-year rule, most forms of harassment of alleged
subversives' attorneys consisted only of telephone threats, bugged
telephone lines and military surveillance, lawyers have said.
</TEXT>
