<FIRST>u i AM-China     03-23 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Won't Allow More Political Parties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said Thursday that the nation's eight
so-called democratic political parties will continue to operate
under communist guidance and that new parties will not be allowed.
   On Tuesday, Communist Party authorities announced a plan to allow
the eight parties to participate in the government. Yan Mingfu, who
heads the Communist Party's office that deals with other parties,
said the plan will be ready by June or July.
   The parties will operate only under the leadership of the
Communist Party, which has ruled China since 1949, he said.
   The plan comes as a growing number of intellectuals are calling
for more political freedom and appears to be an attempt by the
Communist Party to silence critics without relinquishing power.
   Leaders of the eight parties said Thursday they expected more
government officials to be appointed from their ranks.
   ``The Communist Party of China and the eight democratic parties
share the same goals. We are in the same boat,'' Wan Guoquan, vice
chairman of the China Democratic National Committee, said at a news
conference.
   ``Just like a symphony, a country needs a conductor. The
Communist Party is our conductor.''
   The news conference was held by the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, a prestigious but powerless advisory body
currently meeting in Beijing.
   Members of the conference said new political parties are not
needed because the eight democratic parties represent a wide range
of China's people.
</TEXT>
