<FIRST>r a AM-ProblemTakeoff     03-23 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Problem Takeoff,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Strikes Barricade Taking Off From Wrong Runway, Lands Safely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jet took off from the wrong
runway Thursday, struck several construction barricades and damaged
the plane's underside before landing safely in Dallas.
   American Flight 508, carrying 92 passengers and a crew of six
from Houston's Hobby Airport, arrived on time at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport where passengers deplaned normally, American
officials said.
   Airport ground crews found three of 13 wooden barriers destroyed
in addition to a 4-by-4-foot plywood sign, said Sam Maloney, a
Federal Aviation Administration spokesman in Fort Worth.
   American spokesman Ed Stewart confirmed that the plane hit the
sign and a wooden sawhorse, adding that the plane sustained damage
to the bottom of the tail section and the wheel base.
   Tina Ceppi, spokeswoman for the Houston Aviation Department,
which operates Hobby, said barricades mark a runway section closed
because of construction.
   The pilot, whose name was not released, had been provided with
recorded information before the takeoff saying the last 2,200 feet
of the runway was closed because of construction, Maloney said.
   The pilot was in Washington late Thursday afternoon and was
``giving his side of the story'' to American officials, Stewart said.
   ``We have to ascertain what happened first before we can say what
action we will take,'' Stewart said.
   The FAA is continuing its invesigation and no immediate action
was taken.
   The pilot twice had been cleared to take off on a longer runway,
but turned down the wrong one, said Geraldine Cook, an FAA
spokeswoman.
   Shortly after the pilot began taxiing down the runway,
controllers noticed he was on the wrong runway and tried to radio
him but received no response, Maloney said.
   Once an aircraft is cleared for takeoff, a pilot can switch radio
frequencies, and that may have been the case with the American
pilot, he said.
   During the plane's ascent, the tower told the pilot he may have
hit a barricade, Maloney said. The pilot acknowledged that he
thought he hit it. The pilot thought it was safe to continue, Ms.
Cook said.
</TEXT>
