<DOCNO> AP890323-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0632 03-23 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0632,0789</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peres Backs Peace Plan; Palestinian Boy Killed, 18 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with 2 more wounded, parties agreeing
on funding of Jewish settlements. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Party leader Shimon Peres backed a
Palestinian ``entity'' Thursday as a key to peace in the occupied
lands, where hospital officials said soldiers killed a 14-year-old
boy and wounded 18 other people.
   He said he would urge Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, leader of
the conservative Likud bloc, to accept the peace plan before the
premier visits the United States next month. Peres is finance
minister in the ``national unity'' coalition of Likud and his
center-left party.
   Newspaper reports said the plan calls for a Palestinian state in
all but name, demilitarized and in confederation with Jordan and
Israel. Peres denied recommending a separate state in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured in the 1967 war.
   Arab hospital officials said soldiers in the occupied territories
shot the boy and wounded 18 other Palestinians. At least 405
Palestinians have been killed since an uprising began in the West
Bank and Gaza more than 15 months ago, and 18 Israelis also have
been slain.
   The army denied any troopers were in the West Bank village at the
time, but said it was investigating a report that civilian Israelis
in the area responded with gunfire when their car was stoned. A
spokesman said he had reports of six gunshot wounds.
   Also Wednesday, Labor and its rival, the right-wing Likud bloc
led by Shamir, agreed to allocate $19.4 million to fund Jewish
settlements in the occupied territories.
   Media reports said Likud demanded almost twice that sum, but
Peres' Finance Ministry refused.
   Haaretz, a Hebrew-language daily, said the Peres peace plan calls
for a one-year truce in the occupied lands, including a moratorium
on the uprising.
   ``In essence, we are talking about abandoning our control of the
territories, of Judea and Samaria. It's clear it would be handed
over to some form of Arab sovereignty,'' said Ephraim Sneh, a Labor
Party member who worked on the plan, using the biblical names for
the West Bank.
   Sneh said details have yet to be worked out but the plan has two
stages, with the problems of sovereignty and the link to Jordan to
be addressed in the second stage.
   On television Thursday, Peres said ``we are ready for territorial
compromise'' but vigorously denied calling for a Palestinian state,
a risky political concept in Israel, and gave no details.
   ``I have not proposed a Palestinian state,'' he said. ``I have
ruled out the Palestinian state. I will present my plan to Mr.
Shamir.''
   He used the phrases ``Palestinian entity'' and ``confederation,
according to the example of Benelux'' in describing his plan.
   The Haaretz report said Peres calls the plan ``the Benelux
model,'' a reference to the close cooperation between Belgium, the
Netherlands and Luxembourg.
   It said the Peres plan would create a three-state federation
involving Israel, Jordan and a Palestinian ``entity'' that would be
a nation in all ways except that it would have no army.
   Israeli troops would withdraw, but maintain a presence along the
strategic Jordan River valley.
   After an informal truce began, direct talks between Israel and a
Palestinian delegation elected from the occupied territories would
open in Geneva under international auspices.
   Representatives of the ``Palestinian diaspora,'' presumably the
Palestine Liberation Organization, would be brought in at a later
stage, Haaretz said.
   Peres said on television Thursday: ``The PLO has changed. You
can't deny it.''
   Israel still regards the PLO as a terrorist organization and
refuses to deal with it, but the United States began contacts in
December, after Yasser Arafat publicly renounced terrorism and
recognized Israel's right to exist. The second formal meeting was
held Wednesday.
   Avraham Burg, a Labor Party dove, said the plan published in
Haaretz was a rough version of a proposal that has been developed
further. ``It's in the right general direction,'' he said of the
newspaper report.
   Soldiers shot six Palestinians Thursday in the Gaza Strip and
wounded 12 in the West Bank, hospital officials said.
   At Ousarin village, near Nablus in the West Bank, 14-year-old
Maher Shakid Said was shot in the chest and killed, according to
officials of Ittihad Hospital in Nablus.
   A military court sentenced four Palestinian guerrillas to life
imprisonment Thursday for trying to enter Israel from Lebanon last
year. The Palestinians confessed to the attempt and said they
belonged to the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a
radical Syrian-based faction of the PLO.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
