<FIRST>u w AM-Gingrich-Democrats     03-23 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich-Democrats,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Gird for Gingrich Battle, Release Letter about his `Questionable
Activities'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats, girding for expected partisan
warfare following Rep. Newt Gingrich's selection as House minority
whip, circulated a letter Thursday raising ``unanswered questions''
about Gingrich's activities.
   ``Where I come from, you don't look for a fight. But you don't
run from one either,'' said Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark. ``If you
don't fight back, you lose.''
   Alexander said Democrats needed an organized campaign to combat
Gingrich, who rose to prominence within House GOP ranks largely on
the basis of his ethics campaign against Speaker Jim Wright and two
dozen other prominent Democrats.
   Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, sent all House Democrats a letter
Thursday listing a ``summary of some of the unanswered questions''
about Gingrich's activities.
   ``Gingrich's penchant for slinging mud is surprising, since his
own career is checkered with a string of questionable activities,''
Anthony said in the letter. ``In light of these developments, I
though it would be useful to familiarize yourself with some examples
of the Gingrich style.''
   The letter summarized questions raised previously by the DCCC
about an unusual promotional deal for Gingrich's book, ``Window of
Opportunity,'' about $13,000 Gingrich received in 1977 to write a
novel that never was published, and about a political action
committee chaired by Gingrich which raised $217,868 in direct-mail
solicitations for conservative candidates but spent only $900 on
political campaigns.
   Reporters' repeated telephone calls to Gingrich's office seeking
comment on the letter were not immediately returned. Gingrich has
said previously that he has committed no improprieties.
   Anthony said Gingrich has been ``a bomb thrower for 10 years'' in
the House and the fact that he is now being rewarded by his GOP
colleagues means that Democrats can use him as ammunition against
all of them.
   ``That's a gold mine of campaign issues,'' he said.
   If Gingrich intends to be a successful whip, however, Anthony
said, he might have to change his tactics.
   ``He's been the kind of guy who wants to burn the building down,
and he doesn't care if some of his own members get burned in the
fire,'' Anthony said. But in the GOP leadership, there is ``the
potential to defang him.''
   Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., compared Gingrich to a famous figure
of plains, Gen. George Armstrong Custer.
   ``Custer was a hard charger and everybody got excited about him
too,'' he said. ``That didn't work out so well.''
</TEXT>
