<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AIDS-HomeTests     03-23 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Home Tests,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA: Yellow Light on AIDS Home Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration remains
cautious about the safety, accuracy and privacy of home AIDS-test
kits as currently proposed, FDA Commissioner Frank Young told a
congressional panel Thursday.
   Young told members of House subcommittee on regulation, business
opportunities and energy that ``caution at this time is prudent''
because of concerns about technical feasibility as well as privacy
and counseling.
   ``In this disease ... there is a death sentence given with a
positive test and without the appropriate interpretation and
counseling, the Food and Drug Administration is apprehensive that
some individuals might not only have major psychological concerns
but might do themselves harm,'' Young said.
   More than a dozen companies indicated interest to the FDA last
year in developing home AIDS-testing kits, all requiring users to
collect blood samples at home and send them to laboratories for
testing. The results would be supplied by mail or telephone.
   The FDA has not approved any such home-testing kits for AIDS, and
has restricted market research on such tests to hospitals, clinics,
doctors' offices and other traditional health-care settings.
   Young said the FDA still has concerns about whether test
suppliers can assure that blood samples can be collected properly
and remain unchanged by temperature extremes in transit to
laboratories. Also, he said, he questions whether tests used will be
as accurate as those available used by health-care practitioners and
whether results will remain confidential.
   The agency will hold a public hearing April 6 to further explore
the issue, he said.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., subcommittee chairman, said he also has
concerns about home AIDS-testing. He said he is ``convinced that in
the hands of the untrained, the unscrupulous and the insensitive,
home AIDS testing can inflict considerable human damage.''
   AIDS advocates share the FDA's concerns, especially about the
need for adequate counseling of people who test positive for the
virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   ``We are deeply concerned that making a home-test available with
a relatively high false positive rate might well be irresponsible in
playing with the emotions of already frightened and concerned
individuals,'' Jeffrey Levi, executive director of the National Gay
&amp; Lesbian Task Force, told the panel.
   He added that testing is only part of the key to controlling
AIDS. Counseling about risk in spreading the disease is also
integral, he said.
   ``Testing does not occur in a vacuum. It is most effective when
accompanied by quality counseling _ counseling that is best provided
and assured in person,'' he said.
   However, Elliot J. Millenson of Rockville, Md., who founded a
company that developed an AIDS home-test, said potential benefits of
such a test far outweigh the potential risks.
   He said experience has shown that people can safely obtain a
small amount of blood for testing and the sample can be safely
packaged and withstand unusual and adverse shipping conditions.
   He also maintained that telephone counseling is as effective as
in-person counseling, and that in fact doctors already provide AIDS
test results and results of tests for other fatal diseases such as
cancer over the phone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
