<FIRST>r a AM-BoardHistory     03-23 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Board History,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Powerful Board's Future Questionable</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Estimate Board, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 92 years, the city Board of Estimate has
wielded immense power over the metropolis, giving approval to
landmarks like Rockefeller Center, the Empire State Building and the
World Trade Center.
   But that power has been jeopardized by the U.S. Supreme Court
decision declaring the eight-member body unconstitutional under the
one-person, one-vote principle.
   Borough presidents from each of the city's five boroughs are
given one vote, while the mayor, comptroller and City Council
president get two each.
   The board's duties including awarding franchises, negotiating
contracts with municipal unions, leasing property, and making zoning
and tax abatement decisions.
   The board was conceived in 1864 for the sole purpose of raising
and spending money for a regional police force. It's modern
composition came with the consolidation of New York City in 1898.
</TEXT>
