<FIRST>r i AM-Botha 1stLd-Writethru   03-23 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botha, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0585,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Botha Agrees to Retire This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with comments from television report.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The power struggle between
President P.W. Botha and the new leader of the National Party, F.W.
de Klerk, has been resolved, and Botha will retire after an election
later this year, news reports said Thursday.
   ``The fight is over,'' an unidentified government source told The
Star, South Africa's largest-selling daily.
   A compromise was reached in a meeting Tuesday calling for Botha
to step down after a general election in the second half of 1989,
the newspaper and government-run television reported.
   Neither de Klerk nor Botha has commented on the reported meeting.
   Botha, 73, suffered a stroke Jan. 18 and spent eight weeks
recuperating. He resigned as leader of the governing National Party
on Feb. 2 and was replaced by de Klerk, the minister of national
education.
   The party's parliamentary caucus later announced it wanted de
Klerk to become president to reunify the two positions. But Botha,
resisting pressure to retire after a decade in power, declared he
would serve until the next general election and said there would be
no early election this year.
   The deadline for the next election is March 1990.
   ``The mood in the National Party is cautious relief and
optimism,'' government-run television reported in an evening
broadcast.
   It said the compromise was reached after ``senior Cabinet members
played mediating roles.''
   The Star said Botha reluctantly agreed to the compromise ``after
finally accepting that the Natonal Party no longer wants him,
something reported to have hurt him deeply.''
   The newspaper said an announcement about an early election date
might be made in April. A meeting of the Nationalist caucus is
scheduled for April 8.
   The television report said an announcement was expected after
Easter weekend.
   De Klerk, 53, has yet to break with any of Botha's major
policies, but he is widely viewed as more flexible and pragmatic
than Botha.
</TEXT>
