<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-EstimateBoard Bjt   03-23 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Estimate Board, Bjt,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Scrambles To Revamp Governing Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day after the U.S. Supreme Court signed a death
warrant for the city's powerful Board of Estimate, officials were
unsure Thursday whether the unusual governing body would linger, be
reincarnated, leave a respectable heir or bequeath confusion upon
voters.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch said he believes the board can go about its
business until a replacement emerges.
   ``Based on normal constitutional law and actions by the Supreme
Court on prior matters ... I believe the Board of Estimate, until
the change occurs, is legal,'' he said.
   The Supreme Court ruled that the board's make-up violates the one
person-one vote principle because each of the city's five boroughs
has one vote on the board although they range in population from
Staten Island's 377,600 to Brooklyn's 2.3 million.
   The Board of Estimate was set up 92 years ago and wields great
power in New York. It decides questions of land use, zoning,
franchises and city contracts, and shares budget-making power with
the City Council. The city has a $25 billion budget this year, and
has to adopt a new one by June 30.
   Peter Zimroth, the city's chief lawyer, said courts usually give
governments ``a reasonable period of time'' to make adjustments in
such cases so as not to disrupt normal activities.
   One possibility is that residents could vote in a referendum for
a new government structure in November, when the city has its next
major election scheduled.
   That scenario could force voters to cast ballots for candidates
without knowing what powers their offices would attain. All the
positions on the Board of Estimate _ mayor, city comptroller, City
Council president and five borough presidencies _ are up for
election.
   Koch said during a news conference with Gov. Mario Cuomo that he
was confident the city will restructure its government in a way that
will hold up in court.
   ``It's an easier problem to deal with than drugs and AIDS,'' he
remarked.
   And Cuomo said of the court ruling, ``I don't think it's a bad
thing at all.''
   He said the Charter Revision Commission, which was established in
anticipation of the ruling, must be careful in addressing Staten
Island's participation in government.
   Staten Island, the least typical borough with a higher proportion
of homeowners and open spaces, and always prickly about being
disregarded, risks the most in a revision.
   Borough President Ralph Lamberti already has spoken of secession
if the island is left with only a weak voice in how the city is run.
A spokesman for the governor of New Jersey joked Thursday that
Staten Island is welcome to become part of the Garden State.
   Koch said one way to conform to the Supreme Court ruling would be
to keep the board and give the borough presidents votes weighted by
population, but that would not give Staten Island the say it demands.
   Richard Ravitch, former chairman of the Charter Revision
Commission and now a candidate for mayor, said last year he favored
eliminating the board, which blends legislative with executive
functions.
   He suggested giving its budget powers to the City Council,
strengthening the role of the borough presidents in setting budget
priorities and reducing the mayor's. He would set up a land-use
review board, give zoning authority to the council and have mayoral
agencies approve contracts.
   That would leave the City Council as a unicameral legislature and
the borough presidents functioning more like other county executives
in the state.
   City Council Majority Leader Peter Vallone said he favors that
kind of separation of powers. He said the court's decision
``reaffirms my confidence that a balanced and fair government will
soon be in place in New York City.''
   Officials must also take into account that any changes must
conform to the federal Voting Rights Act by not diluting the voting
power of minority group members.
   Gretchen Dykstra, spokesman for the charter commission, said the
commission had set April 4 for public hearings on ideas for
reconstruction of the board, but that date was picked before the
court ruling and might change.
   She said it was expected that the commission would draw up its
recommendations in time to put on the ballot as a referendum in
November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
