<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0624 03-23 0997</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0624,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fawn Hall Cries on Stand, Says Shredding with North `No Big Deal'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Earl testimony, inserting 5 grafs after 17th graf,
She testified; trims at end</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weeping Fawn Hall praised former boss Oliver
North Thursday as an inspirational, tireless and selfless man and
said their wholesale shredding of Iran-Contra documents ``was no big
deal.''
   Alternately crying and spitting back sharp responses, Miss Hall
twice appeared unable to go on with her testimony at North's trial,
causing impromptu recesses. Her sympathies throughout were obviously
with North, though she hardly ever looked at him.
   ``It's tough when people portray you as a witness for the
prosecution when you are a witness for the truth,'' she said outside
the courthouse. ``Hopefully, the good guy will win.''
   She called North's firing by then-President Reagan on Nov. 25,
1986, unfair. ``I was very upset,'' she recalled. ``When I heard
about it, I was very angry.''
   Miss Hall, who was North's secretary at the National Security
Council for nearly four years, admitted that when attorney general's
investigators were closing in on Nov. 21, 1986, she altered
documents to soften recorded versions of North's involvement with
the Nicaraguan Contras. She also said she helped him in what has
been called ``a shredelease of American hostages held in Lebanon and that
profits were to be diverted to the Nicaraguan Contras. He said he
worked out a price sheet for 240 missile parts, tacking on a $2.70
profit for each $1 cost.
   Earl testified that he and North made arrangements that if North
were taken hostage in Iran, ``that I was to go into his safe ... and
destroy contents of the bottom drawer.'' He was not asked what was
in the drawer.
   The jurors were given a four-day weekend for Good Friday and
Easter and Earl is expected back on the stand Tuesday. Also next
week, former Attorney General Edwin Meese III is to be a witness,
before the prosecution rests its case.
   The slender, blonde Miss Hall, who became an instant celebrity
when she testified in the televised congressional hearings in 1987,
proved a magnet at the North trial as well. The public lines outside
the courtroom were longer for her appearance than at any previous
time during the trial which began on Jan. 31.
   She said many work days at the NSC offices in the White House
complex would begin at 8 a.m and go until 1 a.m., but North was
unflagging.
   ``He was tireless. I'm half his age at least,'' said the
29-year-old Hall at one point. ``I would be almost falling asleep at
the typewriter and he would still be going.''
   North is 45.
   Sullivan gently led her through her experiences, asking about the
``thousands and thousands and more thousands of questions'' she had
been asked.
   ``Do you always try to tell the truth?'' he asked.
   ``Absolutely yes,'' she replied.
   She said she was not positive which documents she altered and
which she smuggled out of the building.
   ``It wasn't lock door, pull down windows, pull down the shades,''
she said of the scene at the shredding. ``It was no big deal.''
</TEXT>
