<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     03-23 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0471</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Walesa Not Ruling Out Candidacy for Parliament ^By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said Thursday
he would rather not run for a seat in Poland's new parliament, but
he said he would if the people want him to.
   He also said his banned independent union movement will look for
answers ``in the streets and by strikes'' if no final agreement on
reforms is reached at historic talks between the opposition and
Communist leaders.
   Neither will Solidarity tolerate ``tricks'' by officials in
implementing an accord, he said.
   Walesa made the statements at a news conference in his home city
of Gdansk and in a subsequent telephone interview with The
Associated Press.
   At the talks in Warsaw, negotiators continued to discuss economic
and political topics separating the two sides.
   Walesa's comments cast doubt on whether a final agreement could
be signed April 3 as planned. He said he would need about a week to
study the document, which could be hundreds of pages long.
   ``I must familiarize myself with the entire material. ... Even if
it takes more time, it will be understood, because we must do it
well,'' Walesa said.
   A decision to run for the existing parliament or for a newly
created senate would depend ``on the wish of the voters,'' he said.
   ``I don't want to be a candidate. But there are situations when
one must do it,'' Walesa said later by telephone. ``But I really
would not like to, simply because there are many people better than
me.''
   Elections with opposition participation are part of the
far-reaching compromise authorities are seeking at the talks. In
exchange for legalization, Solidarity would agree to elections that
guarantee in advance that a Communist-led coalition would get 65
percent of the existing parliament seats.
   But the new senate would be fully democratic, with opposition
candidates running against Communist-approved candidates for the
first time in the East bloc.
   Although Solidarity has said it would support candidates in
elections to the existing parliament, tentatively planned for June,
most union officials have said they would prefer to concentrate on
union issues.
   Some Solidarity activists also have expressed concern privately
that the union might not be able to find candidates quickly enough
to run for the 35 percent of the 460 seats to be open to the
opposition, and for the 100 or so seats contemplated for the new
senate.
   ``There may be, for example, a situation when I'll have to agree
(to run) because other people refuse,'' Walesa said in the telephone
interview. ``But I really don't want to.''
   Solidarity, the first independent union in the Soviet bloc, was
born in 1980 and banned after martial law was imposed in 1981.
</TEXT>
