<FIRST>r a AM-TeenMurder     03-23 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Murder,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighbor Arrested, Held Without Bail in Teen's Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 21-year-old man was ordered held without
bail Thursday after surrendering to police in the ``vicious, savage
killing'' of a 13-year-old neighbor girl whose battered body was
found in his basement.
   Robert Golub was arraigned on the murder charge shortly after his
arrest in the slaying of Kelly Ann Tinyes in the quite suburban
neighborhood their families had shared for 11 years.
   ``We have forensic evidence at the scene that points to Robert
Golub. ... All of the evidence we do have points to him,'' Nassau
County Chief of Detectives Wayne Seay said Thursday.
   Seay said Robert's 14-year-old brother, John Jay Golub, a onetime
schoolmate of Kelly's, is still a suspect as well and the
investigation is continuing.
   Authorities did not speculate on a possible motive.
   Kelly, an eighth-grader, was last seen entering the Golub house,
a few doors down from her home, in Valley Stream on March 3. Her
body was found in the basement there a day later.
   She had been stabbed with a World War I bayonet, strangled,
slashed, kicked and punched by her killer, authorities said. The
bayonet was recovered, Seay said.
   The Golub family, which had been staying with friends since
shortly after the killing, were cursed at and forced to leave after
they tried to return home Saturday night. Among the crowd of about
40 who screamed ``Monsters!'' and ``Seed of the devil!'' at the
Golubs were some of Kelly's relatives.
   The family, described by neighbors as remote, had lived in the
home for 11 years, while the Tinyes family had lived on the street
for 13 years.
   The slain girl's parents, Richard and Victoria Tinyes, stood
quietly in a courtroom hallway as Golub was arraigned Thursday.
   ``This defendant is charged with the vicious, savage killing of a
13-year-old girl,'' said Assistant District Attorney Daniel Cotter.
   ``It may not be the worst in the county's history, but it ranks
right up there,'' Cotter said. Nassau County Court Judge Marvin
Goodman accepted Cotter's request that Golub be held without bail,
pending a court appearance next Wednesday.
   Golub, an unemployed onetime truck driver, entered an innocent
plea through his attorney, John O'Grady.
   Seay said a bloody palm print that was found on a doorway near
Kelly's body was tentitively identified as belonging to Golub. The
FBI was analyzing it to confirm the identification.
   In the three weeks since the slaying, police checked a variety of
leads but ``We kept coming back to him (Robert Golub),'' Seay said,
adding the story the murder suspect told them shortly after the
slaying didn't check out.
   O'Grady said Golub maintained his innocence in the slaying on
Wednesday night when they discussed his pending surrender.
   ``What are you going to do? I didn't do it,'' the attorney quoted
Golub as saying.
</TEXT>
