<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Haiti     03-23 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Haiti,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Consulting With Congress On Easing Aid Curbs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has asked Congress to
consider a partial lifting of the freeze on aid to Haiti, sources in
the State Department and on Capitol Hill said Thursday.
   The State Department is now consulting with Congress about the
timing of such a move in light of recent steps taken by Haiti's
military rulers to guarantee free elections, said the officials, all
of whom requested anonymity.
   The United States suspended $78 million in aid to the government
of the impoverished Caribbean nation in November 1987 to protest a
massacre that disrupted elections. The United States left in place
about $25 million in aid to private Haitian groups for health,
education and other humanitarian projects.
   The State Department's proposal would give the Haitian government
about $8 million worth of wheat that had been held up by the aid
suspension, said a congressional source. The government would be
allowed to sell the wheat and use the proceeds to create badly
needed jobs, he said.
   ``The sentiment here is to wait a while and see if President
(Prosper) Avril follows through on his promises for elections,''
said the source.
   ``We're not that far apart from the administration on this. It's
a question of timing,'' he added.
   Avril, who assumed power in a September 1988 coup, promised last
month to set up a nine-member electoral council to fix an election
date and set conditions for the balloting.
   A State Department source said that if Avril follows through on
his promise and names the commission in the coming days, Congress
may agree to ``reward him with a small amount of that aid.''
