<FIRST>r a AM-Steinberg     03-23 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Received Hundreds of Letters About Steinberg's Punishment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adoptive parents, childless couples and people
abused as children wrote hundreds of letters urging a judge to give
Joel Steinberg maximum punishment for beating his illegally adopted
daughter to death, sources said Thursday.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said people from
all over the country wrote to state Supreme Court Justice Harold
Rothwax, the judge who will sentence Steinberg on Friday.
   When asked to make the letters public, the judge said any letters
received in the case already had been destroyed.
   The sources said letters also came from child advocacy groups and
domestic violence projects, including a Georgia organization
responsible for a writing campaign of more than 100 letters.
   Not one of the letters recommended mercy for Steinberg, the
sources said, and some demanded the death penalty, which New York
does not have.
   Steinberg, 47, was convicted Jan. 30 of first-degree manslaughter
in the November 1987 beating death of 6-year-old Lisa.
   A disbarred lawyer, Steinberg got the child at birth from an
unwed teen-ager and raised her as his own rather than arranging for
the baby's adoption as he had promised.
   Steinberg was acquitted of a more serious charge of second-degree
murder. The maximum sentence he faces is eight and one-third to 25
years in prison.
   If Steinberg is sentenced to the maximum, he would be eligible
for parole in less than seven years because he already has been
jailed for nearly 17 months since his arrest.
   Steinberg's lawyer, Perry Reich, said Steinberg will address the
court before sentencing.
   ``Joel wants the judge to assess his humanity to see his sorrow
at Lisa's death and to feel he is worthy of redemption,'' Reich
said. ``He's simply going to express himself as a human being.''
</TEXT>
