<FIRST>r a AM-StatenIsland-NJ     03-23 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Staten Island-NJ,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Staten Island Looking To Secede; Is N.J. The Answer?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Estimate Board, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A potentially unfavorable court decision to
New York City's Staten Island has the borough threatening to secede,
and New Jersey officials joked Thursday they would welcome their
neighbors across the water. ``An awful lot of people think it's part
of New Jersey already,'' said Carl Golden, a spokesman for Gov.
Thomas H. Kean.
   But Bob Huber, a spokesman for Borough President Ralph J.
Lamberti, said any talk of secession by New York City's smallest
borough remains premature. If the borough's nearly 400,000 residents
did leave New York City, it would be to form their own county and
not to join New Jersey, Huber said.
   ``We wouldn't consider New Jersey,'' Huber said, adding that
Lamberti commissioned a study two years ago that showed Staten
Island could be a self-sufficient body.
   The U.S. Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that New York City's Board
of Estimate violated the Constitution's one-person, one-vote
principle. The court upheld a lower court ruling that required the
city to develop a plan giving greater voting weight to larger
boroughs. Staten Island is by far the city's smallest borough.
   The board, which rules on issues ranging from land-use to sewage
rates, is comprised of the five borough presidents and the mayor,
comptroller and City Council president. The latter three each have
two votes.
   Huber said the borough would await a decision by the Charter
Review Commission, appointed by Mayor Edward I. Koch to revise city
policy after the lower court decision.
   ``Do we want a board overwhelmingly made up of people who don't
live here?'' Huber asked. ``That wouldn't be fair.''
   Golden said with a laugh that he did not want New Jersey accused
of pirating an entire borough.
   ``It would be nice to get another member for the congressional
delegation,'' Golden said. ``If they want to join New Jersey,
they're more than welcome.''
   Just across a small body of water from Staten Island is the
township of Woodbridge, a popular place for the New York City
residents, according to Mayor Joseph DeMarino. Many Staten Islanders
work in Woodbridge and use the large mall there as a place to shop.
   But DeMarino said he doesn't expect the two groups to share the
same state name any time soon.
   ``I don't think anybody's talking about coming over to New
Jersey,'' he said. ``You know, secession's not as easy as it
sounds.''
</TEXT>
