<FIRST>r w AM-SpottedOwl     03-23 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spotted Owl,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smith Bill Would Protect Logging Even If Owl Listed As Endangered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation aimed at ensuring that logging in
the Northwest would not be interrupted for at least five years even
if the spotted owl was listed as an endangered species was
introduced Thursday.
   Rep. Bob Smith, R-Ore., said the five-year period would allow
time for wildlife biologists to determine whether the owl, believed
to inhabit only ancient forests, was really threatened with
extinction.
   ``There is not enough evidence, at this time, to say whether the
owl is endangered,'' Smith said at a news conference.
   He said the legislation would not prohibit the owl from being
listed as an endangered species either by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service or a federal court, but would keep such a listing from
effecting timber sales.
   ``This is the most moderate kind of an answer to a difficult
situation,'' said Smith.
   The owl has become the focal point of an increasingly bitter
debate in the Northwest over protecting old-growth timber.
   Environmentalists have sought to have the bird listed under the
federal Endangered Species Act, while the timber industry has
insisted that such a designation could halt logging in vast areas of
the Northwest and result in the loss of thousands of jobs.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service had previsouly refused to list the
owl for protection, but a federal court in Seattle has given the
agency until May 1 to review its decision.
   A General Accounting Office report released last month concluded
that the agency's decision not to protect the bird was based more on
politics than on scientific evidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
