<FIRST>r w AM-Skinner-Burnley     03-23 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinner-Burnley,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Rejects Pilots' Call To Reconsider Burnley Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
rejected Thursday an appeal by the Air Line Pilots Association to
reconsider a decision by former Secretary James Burnley affecting
Eastern Airlines.
   Skinner said the fact that Burnley was negotiating for employment
with a law firm that represented Eastern at the time was not reason
enough to overturn Burnley's refusal to conduct a continuing formal
fitness investigation of the airline.
   The matter arose before the current Machinists' union strike
against Eastern which the pilots union is supporting. The pilots
were, however, involved in own contract negotiations with still have
not been settled.
   Skinner signed an order that said the union had not presented any
information that would justify reconsidering Burnley's decision in
December, just before his resignation to join the Washington law
firm of Shaw, Pittman, Potts &amp; Trowbridge.
   The department concluded that since the firm had not represented
Eastern in the fitness investigation proceedings, ``there was no
reason for Secretary Burnley to have recused himself, and therefore
no reason to reconsider Secretary Burnley's decision in that case.''
   The department had said Burnley disclosed his negotiations for a
job with the law firm to the department's ethics office, and an
ethics official told him there would be no ethical or legal problem
with him deciding the Eastern matter.
</TEXT>
