<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Afghanistan     03-23 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Accuses Pakistan of Ignoring Geneva Accord</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze on Thursday
accused Pakistan of ignoring its commitment not to interfere in
Afghanistan and said the Soviet Union will take firm steps to
protect its citizens in Kabul.
   In an interview with the official Tass news agency, Shevardnadze
said Moscow signed the Geneva accords in April with the United
States, Pakistan and Afghanistan only because the Kremlin believed
that outside interference, mostly from Pakistan-supported rebels,
``would be completely discontinued.''
   Soviet military forces completed their withdrawal Feb. 15 under
the U.N.-mediated agreement after more than nine years of direct
involvement in a civil war that began with a communist coup in April
1978.
   Shevardnadze said that despite the Soviet pullout, the civil war
in Afghanistan continues to rage.
   ``In order to understand why, one should turn to the Geneva
agreements again. And then, one will see that the clause on ending
interference in Afghan domestic affairs has been completely ignored
by Pakistan,'' he told Tass.
   Shevardnadze said Pakistan had grossly violated the Geneva
agreement by allowing the creation of an interim government on its
territory, known as ``the Alliance of Seven.''
   He said the agreement also specifically prohibits arms being
delivered to Afghan rebels. Most of the weapons have come from the
United States via Pakistan.
   ``I shall note again that if weapons were delivered not via
Pakistan, then, speaking from the legal viewpoint, there would be no
violation of the Geneva accords,'' Shevardnadze said. ``But, the
matter is that practically all the armaments are supplied from
Pakistan.''
   Shevardnadze said the Soviet Union was fully prepared to
discontinue arms shipments to Afghanistan, ``but we will not agree
to unilateral steps.''
   He said fierce fighting was raging outside the city of Jalalabad
but said Afghan forces were repelling the rebels.
   Shevardnadze also said a large number of Soviet civilian
specialists remained in Kabul as well as the staff of a large
embassy. ``Any attempts to encroach upon their security will draw a
most resolute Soviet response,'' he said without elaboration.
</TEXT>
