<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Soviet     03-23 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Condemns NATO Plan to Modernize Missiles, Looks for New Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri V. Dubinin on Thursday
assailed NATO's plan to modernize its short-range nuclear missiles
as an unacceptable impediment to the improvement of East-West
relations.
   Dubinin, at a news conference, also said he hoped a date would be
set for the resumption of U.S.-Soviet negotiations to reduce
long-range nuclear missiles when Secretary of State James A. Baker
III visits Moscow in May.
   ``We are ready,'' Dubinin said.
   The NATO plan to extend the range of U.S. Lance missiles is
running into obstacles even within the ranks of the Western
alliance. West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, with support from some
other allied leaders, is seeking a delay.
   The United States is determined to go ahead but still has to
persuade Kohl,whose chance for re-election next year may hinge on
the missile issue in a country where disarmament forces are strong.
   Congress, meanwhile, is unlikely to fund the modernization with
West Germany on the fence.
   Asked about improving the Lances, Dubinin said: ``It's
unacceptable, at any rate, not for the Soviet Union but for the
process we are talking about. It's just something which is going
against the mainstream of peaceable development of the world. It's
something which goes against the process of disarmament.''
   Dubinin added: ``There's absolutely no need to do it, because we
have begun in Europe a historic process of reducing forces,
unilaterally by the Soviet Union and multilaterally in
negotiations.''
   In any event, he said, the Soviet Union will not modernize its
own battlefield nuclear weapons. ``We are strongly in favor of
beginning negotiations to eliminate this class of weapons, too.''
   Apart from the Lance missile issue, Dubinin fielded questions
about U.S.-Soviet relations in a way that reflected a warming trend
in Moscow under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   He said the Soviet leader probably would see Baker when he goes
to Moscow in the first half of May to hold a second meeting with
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   Dubinin described Baker's first talk with Shevardnadze, which was
held March 7 in Vienna, as ``a successful one'' and ``the beginning
of a new, active period of Soviet-American relations.''
   U.S.-Soviet negotiations to reduce long-range nuclear missiles
were tentatively scheduled to resume in mid-February in Geneva. But
President Bush ordered a postponement and the administration is
reviewing U.S. policy.
   Asked if the delay set back prospects for a treaty, Dubinin said:
``The delay is a delay. It's absolutely clear. But we understand the
new administration needs some time to get things together. It's
understandable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
