<FIRST>u i AM-NATO-USAmbassador     03-23 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO-US Ambassador,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taft Expected To Be Named NATO Ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is expected soon to name
William H. Taft IV, the deputy defense secretary, as the American
ambassador to NATO, a source said Thursday.
   Taft will replace Alton G. Keel Jr., who is leaving the post at
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization to return to the United
States and a job in the private sector, the source said on condition
of anonymity.
   Keel will stay on the job through the summit to be attended by
Bush and other leaders of the 16 alliance nations May 29-30 at NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
   Taft, the great-grandson of President William Howard Taft, has
been deputy defense secretary since February 1984. In that job, he
has visited the NATO countries for discussions on
``burden-sharing,'' the sensitive issue of how much the allies are
contributing to the common defense.
   Before being named to his current job, Taft, a lawyer, was the
Pentagon's general counsel.
   In the 1970s, he held positions in the Federal Trade Commission,
the Office of Management and Budget and the Department of Health,
Education and Welfare.
   Keel was sworn in as the United States representative to NATO on
March 13, 1987. He had been acting assistant for national security
affairs under President Reagan.
   In 1981, Keel was named assistant secretary of the Air Force for
research, development and logistics. A year later, he was chosen
associate director for national security and international affairs
in the Office of Management and Budget.
   In 1986, he was executive director of the presidential commission
investigating the accident of the space shuttle Challenger.
</TEXT>
