<FIRST>u w AM-Warning-RighttoKnow 2ndLd-Writethru a0715 03-23 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warning-Right to Know, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0715,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Criticize British Press; Victims' Relatives Want Warnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf, The Daily, to CORRECT that FAA order was March
16, not March 15.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-ijack Warning Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials criticized the British press Thursday
for disclosing a secret Federal Aviation Administration warning of a
potential hijacking in Europe, but relatives of air terrorism
victims said passengers have a right to know of such threats.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said release of the
warning compromises intelligence-gathering activities and
jeopardizes airline passengers' safety. ``Hopefully no one will lose
their life over this, but it is a very serious matter,'' he said.
   Skinner ordered the FAA and a team of top aides now in London to
investigate who leaked the warning to British news media.
   The Daily Express in London quoted from a copy of a March 16 FAA
security bulletin which warned of a possible hijacking of a U.S.
airliner during the upcoming Easter weekend.
   The FAA, which acknowledged issuing the bulletin after reports
about it appeared in the Express and other British media, said,
``The release of this information by unauthorized persons can be
counterproductive to the civil aviation community's efforts to
provide a totally effective security system.''
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said it is necessary to
keep such bulletins secret to protect intelligence sources and,
ultimately, the public.
   Redman and other U.S. officials denied a Daily Express report
that it warned government employees against flying in Europe during
the Easter weekend.
   But several relatives of victims of the Dec. 21 bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 over Scotland said they believe the way the government
handles terrorism bulletins has the effect of warning diplomatic and
military personnel while keeping other potential passengers
uninformed about risks.
   The relatives, in telephone interviews, criticized government
reluctance to provide the public with information about terrorist
warnings. British investigators have concluded that a terrorist bomb
concealed in a radio-casettee player blew up Flight 103, killing all
259 people aboard and 11 others on the ground in Lockerbie, Scotland.
   ``We don't think they should use the American public as live
bait,'' said Colleen Hermann, of Huntington, N.Y., whose brother
John Michael Ahern was killed on Flight 103.
   Bert Ammerman, a spokesman for the relatives of Lockerbie
victims, said the group is not calling for general public
announcements everytime there is a terrorist threat.
   But he said until ``prudent security measures'' can be taken to
protect American carriers, a number should be set up for travellers
to call to get information on any threat against a flight they plan
to take.
   ``I don't think that's going to paralyze the aviation industry,''
said Ammerman, of Demarest, N.J., whose brother, Tom, was killed in
the Pan Am bombing.
   Another victim's relative, Paul Hodson, an Albany, N.Y., lawyer
who lost his 16-year-old daughter, Melina, said the present security
system amounts to a selective warning system.
   ``This whole thing gives us a feeling of deja vu,'' he said,
referring to the secret warnings passed around among government and
aviation officials before the Lockerbie explosion.
   ``What happens when this information is kept secret and yet is
passed around to literally thousands of security people is that it
is bound to leak out and hurt the credibility of security. It then
tends to sow panic even among those not directly threatened,''
Hudson said.
   Tim Cole, a Washington aviation consultant, said if all threats
were made public, they might become so commonplace that people would
simply ignore them. ``With 600 or so threats a year, you'd be crying
wolf all the time,'' he said.
   Officials say all but a handful of threats are hoaxes.
   Sherry Price, a consultant at the National Victims Center in New
York City, which works with victims of violent crimes, said fears
that warnings may disrupt commercial aviation are unfounded.
   ``They're not giving the American public the credit it
deserves,'' she said. ``People are still going to go on airplanes,
but I need to have the right to cancel my plans rather than cancel
my life.''
</TEXT>
