<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia     03-23 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Armenian Nationalists Sent to Prison for Airport Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Armenian nationlists were sentenced Thursday to
18 months in prison for leading a strike that closed the Caucasus
republic's main airport in July, the official news agency Tass
reported.
   It said A. Gevoyan and A. Pogosyan, both unemployed, were charged
with inducing unlawful actions that closed Zvartnots airport for
three days.
   Evidence was given during the two-month trial that the men, in
Civil Aviation uniforms, urged people at a mass meeting of the
banned Karabakh Committee to march on the airport and force the
staff to strike.
   ``The demonstrators, arriving at Zvartnots airport, blocked the
approaches to the airport and the buildings of the air terminal,''
Tass said. ``Takeoffs were prevented and the airport's functions
were paralyzed, jeopardizing the safety of numerous airliners.''
   An Ilyushin-86 airbus carrying 300 people was able to land safely
``only by a lucky chance,'' the agency reported.
   According to the evidence, the defendants directed the three-day
demonstration and strike. Tass said they ``ignored all the efforts
of airport authorities, of representatives of party and government
bodies to persuade them to end the blockage of Zvartnots airport.''
   ``Instead of that, the demonstrators' leaders continued to make
absurd demands and threatened to take hostages,'' the news agency
said. ``It is only due to the intervention of forces protecting law
and order that the dangerous developments were disrupted.
   ``The defendants have been sentenced to the deprivation of
freedom for 18 months and are to serve the term in a correctional
labor colony with a general regime.''
   Tass said the sentence cannot be appealed.
   The Karabakh Committee began a campaign in February 1988 to annex
Nagorno Karabakh, a predominantly Armenian enclave in neighboring
Azerbaijan. At least 87 people died in ethnic riots and efforts by
Soviet troops to quell violence between the Christian Armenians and
the Moslem Azerbaijanis.
</TEXT>
