<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Sudan     03-23 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Sudan,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Officials Say Rebels Agree To Safe Passage For Famine Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels in Sudan have promised a U.N. famine
relief effort safe passage to rebel-controlled areas where hundreds
of thousands of people face starvation, a U.N. official said
Thursday.
   ``Operation Lifeline,'' the biggest effort of its kind in any
developing nation, aims to deliver more than 100,000 tons of food to
more than 1 million people in April, which has been designated a
month of tranquillity in Sudan's civil conflict.
   The object of the operation is to deliver the food by train,
truck, barge and air to remote areas in the south before seasonal
rains and floods make transport routes impassable.
   The cost of the project is $132 million, $55 million of which
still must be raised.
   U.N. officials have said more than 600,000 of the 2 million to 3
million people displaced by the civil war could die of starvation
during the April-December rainy season unless they get help.
   James P. Grant, director of the U.N. Children's Fund, said at a
news conference that the Sudan People's Liberation Army has promised
safe passage to rebel-controlled areas in the south.
   He said both sides agreed to the presence of U.N. staff to assure
international donors that the supplies are being used for the
purposes intended.
   Also Thursday, Grant was appointed personal representative of
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar for relief in Sudan.
   Grant held talks in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, with Sudanese rebel
officials on allowing the relief convoys and airlifts, which already
have started.
   He said they had indicated their acceptance of ``corridors of
peace'' to allow transport of relief supplies.
   The rebels are fighting for more autonomy for the Christian and
animist south from the Moslem-controlled government.
</TEXT>
