<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1926EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ThinBlueLine 2ndLd-Writethru a0718 03-23 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thin Blue Line, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0718,0862</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Dropping Case Against Adams</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with quotes from Adams and others,
details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randall Dale Adams went home a free man Thursday,
meeting his family minutes after a prosecutor announced he will not
retry the man who was once three days away from execution for the
1976 killing of a Dallas policeman.
   ``I've been standing a twilight zone for the past 12{ years,''
Adams said after hearing the news. ``I was in that twilight zone
until the door opened. Thank God it did.''
   Dallas County District Attorney John Vance said the case was
dropped because there is not enough evidence to retry Adams, who has
served 12{ years in prison. A judge ordered his release two days ago
on grounds his first trial was unfair.
   ``It's almost impossible to find sufficient, credible evidence to
try a case that is 13 years old,'' Vance said.
   Adams was convicted and sentenced to die in 1977 for the murder
of Dallas police officer Robert Wood, a crime to which another man
has virtually confessed.
   The one-time drifter has unstintingly maintained his innocence.
His case drew national attention after it was portrayed in the movie
documentary ``The Thin Blue Line.''
   Vance announced his decision as Adams was en route to Ohio to
rejoin his family. He is free on a $50,000 personal recognizance
bond.
   In Columbus, Ohio, Adams walked off an airplane and kissed his
mother, Mildred Adams. Both broke into tears. About 100 friends and
well-wishers were at the airport to greet him.
   ``You're supposed to have a resurrection around Easter,'' Mrs.
Adams said. ``I guess this is it.''
   Errol Morris, director of ``The Thin Blue Line,'' had to battle a
contingent of reporters and photographers to get close to Adams. He
and Adams then embraced.
   Adams, who appeared red-faced and grimacing as he got off the
plane before hearing the news, was given an Ohio State University
cap and a lei made of daffodils. He then was taken to a private room
in the airport.
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals in March threw the conviction
out, saying Adams hadn't gotten a fair trial because prosecutors
suppressed evidence and witnesses lied on the stand.
   Adams, who was three days away from execution before his sentence
was commuted in 1980 to life in prison, has repeatedly said he'd
welcome a second trial.
   His attorney, Randy Schaffer of Houston, said Vance's action
served the purpose.
   ``I think he (Adams) would probably agree with me that his name
has been cleared, that he's been vindicated in the court
proceedings,'' Schaffer said.
   He said he believes the national spotlight on the case probably
forced Vance to drop it. But Vance defended prosecutors' actions,
including a legal fight that temporarily held up Adams' release
earlier this week.
   ``The easy route would have been to release Mr. Adams
immediately. However, my obligation is not to the media or to play
the part of the hero. My responsibility in every case is to the
victim, his family, Dallas County citizens and the state of Texas,''
Vance said.
   ``I think Mr. Adams would be the first to admit to you that the
justice system works. If it didn't he would be on death row.''
   Vance said a motion to dismiss the capital murder charge has been
filed with state District Judge Larry Baraka, who initially
recommended that Adams be retried.
   Pressure to re-examine the case grew after ``The Thin Blue Line''
raised doubts about the testimony of the state's key witness, David
Harris.
   Harris had picked up Adams the day of the shooting after Adams'
car ran out of gas. In the first trial, Harris said Wood had pulled
over Harris' car and Adams shot the officer.
   In the documentary, however, Harris changed his story. And in
December he told Baraka that Adams did not shoot Wood. Harris
provided so many details of the crime that the judge said he
considered Harris' testimony a virtual confession.
   Harris is on death row for another slaying but wasn't charged in
the Wood case.
   The district attorney previously said his decision on whether to
retry would hinge on prosecutors' ability to find two key witnesses
_ a woman investigators had not spoken with in 13 years and a man
who identified Adams, but later claimed he had forgotten his
original testimony.
   Vance said Thursday he doesn't believe Harris confessed, and he
doesn't expect him to be tried for the Woods killing.
   Detective J. Copeland of the Dallas Police Crimes Against Persons
Division said the case probably will not be reopened. Most of the
officers who worked on the 1976 shooting have retired or left the
force, he said.
   ``It's just too bad they can let a guy out because somebody makes
a movie that isn't right,'' Copeland said. ``They (prosecutors) know
best if they have a triable case or not. In this business you have
to roll with the punches.''
</TEXT>
