<DOCNO> AP890323-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FSX 610   03-23 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FSX, 610</SECOND>
<HEAD>FSX Questions Still Unanswered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior Bush administration and Japanese
officials met Thursday to discuss the controversial FSX fighter
after the chief White House spokesman declared that the joint
production arrangement is ``not a done deal.''
   ``The president still has to make the basic decisions,'' press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said.
   President Bush had said he wants to proceed with the deal, but
with modifications to help safeguard U.S. technology and to assure
that American industry has a share in the plane's production.
   ``We've pretty much finished our deliberations here inside the
administration. I've made my decision to go forward, with certain
clarifications,'' Bush said at that time.
   Fitzwater announced that Japanese officials would be meeting
later with Secretary of State James A. Baker III, Commerce Secretary
Robert Mosbacher and national security adviser Brent Scowcroft to
present their views on revisions being proposed by the
administration.
   The Japanese government has called for U.S. approval of the
original plan negotiated by the Reagan administration with as few
changes as possible.
   Japanese officials in the meeting at the State Department
included Vice Minister Seiki Nishihiro of the Japanese Defense
Agency and Nobuo Matsunaga, the Japanese ambassador to Washington.
   After the talks, Matsunaga brushed past reporters to a waiting
limousine, saying only: ``We agreed to continue meeting. I have
nothing else to say.''
   A State Department official, who spoke on condition he not be
identified, said the talks woill resume Friday.
   ``There is no conclusion, but there is no breakdown either,'' he
said.
   The FSX deal is expected to be sent to Capitol Hill within the
next few days. It could be blocked if both the Senate and the House
pass resolutions of disapproval within 30 days of being formally
notified of the agreement.
   The president, however, could then veto the congressional action,
with a two-thirds majority required to override the veto.
   Under the agreement signed late last year, St. Louis-based
General Dynamics would join with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries
to co-develop and co-produce the FSX as an advanced version of the
U.S. F-16 fighter.
   Proponents argue the agreement represents the best deal the
United States could negotiate in the face of Japanese opposition to
buying F-16s directly from this country. They say the deal will
promote exchanges of technology while helping U.S. industry.
   Critics contend the arrangement amounts to a giveaway of advanced
technology that Japan may use to help propel its civilian aircraft
industry into head-to-head competition with the United States in the
world market. They say Tokyo should purchase American-made planes to
help offset the $50 billion U.S. trade deficit with Japan.
   On Capitol Hill, a group of seven House members led by Rep. Mel
Levine, D-Calif., circulated a ``dear colleague'' letter saying they
continue to have ``serious reservations'' about the FSX deal.
   ``If the Japanese were serious about improving the defense of the
northern Pacific, increasing their share of the defense burden and
reducing their massive trade surplus with the United States, they
would buy these planes directly from us.
   ``Instead, they are getting U.S. technology on the cheap to
develop their own aerospace industry _ an industry which could
someday become a major competitor of its U.S. counterpart in
advanced commercial aviation and space launch vehicles,'' the letter
said.
   Also signing the letter were Reps. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., House
majority whip; Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., chairman of the House Ways and
Means subcommittee on trade; Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., chairman of
the House Trade and Competitiveness Taskforce; Robert T. Matsui,
D-Calif.; Norman Mineta, D-Calif., and Marvin Leath, D-Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
