<FIRST>u i AM-Europe-Warning     03-23 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Warning,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Stepped Up At Some Airports, Others Report Business As Usual</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack Warning, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some European airports stepped up security after
receiving a U.S. warning of a possible hijacking, but others
reported business as usual on a busy Thursday.
   Authorities in London, Frankfurt, Rome and Brussels said security
had been tightened at airports because of the alert, but no
additional precautions were reported in Paris, Amsterdam, Athens or
Madrid.
   The U.S. Embassy in London confirmed the Federal Aviation
Administration had issued an alert about a possible attempt by
radical Palestinians to hijack a U.S. airliner in Europe this
weekend.
   In West Germany, officials said the Interior Ministry and U.S.
government offices were notified of the threat but had issued no
warnings to the public.
   Interior Ministry spokesman Roland Bachmeier said Bonn
authorities received ``a vague warning'' but declined to give
details. He said his ministry regularly receives indications or
warnings of planned terrorist attacks and that security officials
routinely investigate them.
   In Washington, the White House played down the warning, saying it
was similar to many other terrorist alerts and travelers ``should be
confident that all reasonable precautions are being taken.''
   The alert was disclosed in several London newspapers, including
the Daily Express, which published a photocopy of part of the
warning it said had been received by International Aviation
Security, a subsidiary of Trans World Airlines.
   ``The public has been super. They understand the situation and
are very cooperative,'' said Barry Buttenshaw, assistant public
relations manager at London's Gatwick Airport, through which a
quarter-million passengers were expected to pass during the four-day
Easter weekend.
   Buttenshaw reported no flight delays because of stepped-up
security, and spokeswoman Roz Clark at London's Heathrow airport
also reported traffic moving smoothly Thursday afternoon.
   On Thursday morning, however, passengers waiting to board stood
in long lines waiting to be checked through security.
   Security staff ``were very thorough and searched everything we
were taking thorough, which we were pleased to see,'' said Alan Dean
of Boston, who was waiting for a flight at Heathrow.
   Authorities in Rome said security was tighter, but no special
precautions were reported in Paris, Madrid or Amsterdam.
   U.S. airline offices in Rome reported few cancellations.
   ``In fact, we are keeping tabs on this, but there have been no
unusual cancellations,'' said Daniela Travaglini of TWA's Rome
office.
   Rik Hirs, a Dutch national police spokesman, said the agency was
``looking into whether we can increase certain aspects of the
security situation here based on the alert we got.''
   In Athens, a police spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity
said ``security at the airport is always at a high state of alert.''
   The French government said it had received the warning but had
done nothing special about it. ``We do not wait for an FAA
communique to take measures,'' said an Interior Ministry spokesman.
   Nine people who work for Marshall Field's, the U.S. department
store, changed their Paris-to-Chicago bookings for Friday from
American Airlines to a foreign carrier, a Marshall Field's executive
said. They were in Paris for the ready-to-wear fashion shows that
just ended.
   Marshall Field's chairman Philip Miller made the decision, said
Ted Marlowe, merchandising vice president.
</TEXT>
