<FIRST>u i AM-Australia-Hawke     03-23 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Hawke,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says No Early Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke said Thursday
he will not call elections early, as the opposition and some others
have predicted.
   ``I am ruling out a July election,'' he said in a radio interview.
   Hawke has said he would let the government run its three-year
term until May 1990, but critics said his tearful admission on
television Tuesday that he had cheated on his wife of 33 years may
have been a bid for sympathy and votes.
   The 59-year-old Labor Party leader has won an unprecedented three
terms as prime minister and, in the past, has called elections early
despite asserting he would not.
   John Howard, leader of the opposition Liberal Party, suggested
last weekend that Hawke might call elections in July, 10 months
early.
   In the radio interview, his first public comment since the
television confession, Hawke said: ``The people that meet me are as
enthusiastic as they've ever been.''
   His approval rating has fallen to 48 percent, however, and a poll
published Wednesday indicated the Labor Party would have lost if
national elections had been held earlier this month.
   The tabloid Daily Mirror of Sydney speculated that the promise of
large tax reductions beginning July 1 indicate an election is coming.
   ``Political tacticians on both sides agree boosting the average
pay packet by at least $30 ($25 U.S.) a week will be electorally
advantageous,'' it said.
   Hawke is a former trade union leader who once was a heavy
drinker. His public admission of infidelity and his promise to stay
faithful were unexpected.
   Barry Cassidy, his press secretary, tried to counter the talk of
electioneering, and Clive Robertson, who interviewed Hawke on
television, said he thought the remarks were made off the cuff.
</TEXT>
