<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Peru     03-23 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvians Hope For End To Mail Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A postal strike that has held up millions of
letters from tax forms to love notes entered its 50th day Thursday,
but officials said it could end next week.
   ``For two months I have not received the check that my son sent
me from the United States. ... I am living on loans. I don't know
what else to do,'' said an elderly man waiting outside Lima's
central post office.
   He and dozens of others lined up in hopes that their mail somehow
got through.
   Jorge Perez, national mail director, told The Associated Press
that workers tentatively agreed to end their strike Monday, but the
National Federation of Postal Workers had not publicly agreed to a
settlement.
   Courier services such as DHL Worldwide Express said business has
surged since the strike began. Some people have gone into business
for themselves by placing newspaper ads offering to carry letters
for mailing in Miami for a $2 to $3 charge.
   Postal officials in Lima said there has been no home delivery
since the city's 570 letter carriers struck. A small number of other
postal workers remain on the job, but the mail flow, especially
arriving letters, has been reduced dramatically.
   Still, officials said, more than 10 million letters are piling up
in post offices in the city. Four storerooms in the central office
are filled to the ceiling with swollen mail pouches.
   The postal workers union struck Feb. 2 for higher wages to
counter inflation, which hit 110 percent during the first two months
of this year.
   The government decreed a 30 percent wage increase for public
employees earlier this month, but the union said the raise was
insufficient and continued the strike.
   Eugenio Medina, a 25-year postal veteran, said his current salary
_ equivalent to about $31 a month _ is barely enough to ``change the
soles of my shoes.''
   The inflation has combined with a 9 percent shrinkage of Peru's
economy last year to plunge the nation into its worst recession of
the century.
   There have been dozens of strikes, including walkouts by
telephone workers, bank employees, social security personnel and
Lima's morgue staff. Mine workers announced a tentative strike for
Monday.
   The government has argued that the wage increases demanded by
workers will only cause higher inflation and do little to boost
their spending power.
   Analysts say the weak economy and a relentless eight-year
insurgency by leftist guerrillas have undermined government
stability.
   President Alan Garcia began his five-year term in July 1985. His
center-left government cut inflation and sparked two years of growth
in 1986 and 1987 by using government dollar reserves to subsidize
imports of food and consumer and industrial goods.
   The economy began to falter late in 1987 when the reserves were
gone and the government continued its program despite a growing
budget deficit, considered the major cause of inflation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
