<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-23 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wet Weather in the Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was widespread over the south Atlantic coastal states
Thursday and heavy thunderstorms developed over the Florida
peninsula.
   Much of the Carolinas and Georgia had cold and rainy weather,
with temperatures ranging from 35 to 40 degrees at Atlanta,
Charlotte, N.C., and Raleigh, N.C.
   Freezing rain fell throughout much of the day at greensboro nc.
Ice accumulated on trees over the northern mountains and foothills
of North Carolina. Freezing rain was also reported at hot springs va.
   In the Greenville-Spartanburg region of South Carolina, moderate
rain, winds gusting to 43 mph and temperatures at 36 degrees
produced a wind chill of about 5 degrees above zero.
   High pressure near Nova Scotia, Canada, and low pressure over
Florida whipped up gales along the North Carolina coast.
   A few showers also developed across Minnesota as southerly winds
brought relatively mild and moist conditions to the upper
Mississippi Valley.
   Scattered rain and snow showers were reported over Wyoming and
western Montana, with an inch of snow reported at Missoula, Mont.,
Rawlins, Wyo., and International Falls, Minn.
   Sunshine and seasonably mild temperatures prevailed across most
of the nation.
   Rather cold temperatures prevailed over northern New England with
some the lows below zero in northern Maine. Caribou, Maine, set a
record for the date of 5 degrees below zero.
   The low in the nation this morning was 9 below zero at Houlton,
Maine. Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 25
degrees at Minot, N.D., to 85 degrees at Melbourne and Bartow, Fla.
   The national weather forecast for Friday, called for rain
widespread from the Carolinas across the mid Atlantic coastal states
to southern New England. Rainshowers will be scattered across
portions of the upper Mississippi Valley into Upper Michigan, and
from Oregon and Northern California into the northern and central
Intermountain.
   High temperatures will be in the 40s from New England to the mid
Atlantic Coast; in the 30s and 40s from the Dakotas across Minnesota
to northern Michigan; in the 70s and 80s from interior Southern
California across the desert Southwest, New Mexico, the southern
Plains and the Gulf coastal states to Florida. Elsewhere, highs will
be in the 50s and 60s.
</TEXT>
