<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AbortionProtests     03-23 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Protests,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 200 Anti-Abortion Protesters Blockading Clinic</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LA4, LA3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two hundred anti-abortion activists waving
pictures of aborted fetuses were arrested as they blockaded a health
clinic Thursday in the first of a series of Holy Week protests that
have put police on alert.
   The arrests of the protesters and their 29-year-old leader,
Randall Terry, who was carried away in a fetal position, brought
cheers and applause from 150 pro-choice advocates outside the clinic
20 miles east of Los Angeles.
   The anti-abortion protesters organized by Operation Rescue, many
from out of state, clutched rosary beads, sang hymns and prayed as
they were arrested by police at the Family Planning Associates
Medical Clinic in suburban Cypress.
   Counterdemonstrators chanted ``Not the church, not the state,
women will decide our fate'' and hoisted ``Freedom of Choice'' and
``Keep Abortion Legal'' signs.
   The pro-choice people began gathering at 7:15 a.m. to counter
what New York-based Operation Rescue billed as its biggest
anti-abortion protest since undertaking blockades of clinics that
perform abortions two years ago.
   ``I just think somebody has got to do this. This is too big to
ignore. We need to do something for our voices to be heard,'' said
Sue Otti, one of those who tried to block Operation Rescue members.
   Southern California was targeted for the pre-Easter ``National
Week of Rescue,'' organizers said, because of its high abortion rate
and many clinics.
   The 400 anti-abortionists participating in the Cypress protest
sang the ``Battle Hymn of the Republic'' and ``Jesus Loves the
Little Children.''
   The anti-abortion advocates refused comment. Terry, who had
displayed what he said was an aborted 19-week-old fetus in a small
white coffin at a Wednesday news conference, said he wouldn't make a
statement until the media shows pictures of aborted fetuses which
the activists usually display on posters.
   ``We do have a certain sense that media are not being fair with
this issue because a lot of the media has not explained adequately
the moral dilemma'' of equating a woman's right to have an abortion
to a fetus' right to live, said Lou Sheldon of Traditional Values, a
group representing 6,000 churches.
   The arrested were booked for investigation of failing to
disperse, a misdemeanor. Under Terry's order, they went limp during
arrests, requiring four police officers to drag each one to a bus
that took them to Cypress City Hall.
   At one point the pro-choice advocates tried to block
anti-abortion protesters who crawled to the clinic on hands and
knees to replace comrades who had been arrested.
   Later, the police used pro-choice advocates to help them escort
about 25 workers and abortion patients into the clinic as Operation
Rescue members shouted to one teen-age girl entering, ``Reconsider.
Keep your baby.''
   Calls to the clinic were referred to a Los Angeles office, where
a secretary said there would be no comment from management. However,
anti-abortion activists said the clinic's owner was Dr. Edward C.
Allred, a frequent target because he owns a number of clinics in the
area.
   Los Angeles officials who had expected protests by 2,500 people,
were on alert in a city command center four floors under City Hall.
   Police, fire and sheriff's officials kept tabs on activity at
clinics throughout Los Angeles County, including the Her Medical
Clinic near downtown, where 50 pro-choice advocates gathered.
   Operation Rescue members had vowed to risk arrest and defy a
federal court order obtained by the ACLU that forbid protesters from
blocking entrances or gathering within 15 feet of the clinic.
   In suburban Inglewood, police expecting protests there set up
Hollywood Park race track as a temporary jail site, but it wasn't
needed.
   The Operation Rescue protest was supported by Archbishop Roger
Mahony, head of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles.
   Pro-choice groups gathered as the Coalition for Safe and Legal
Abortion included the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern
California, the California Abortion Rights Action League, the
National Organization for Women and Hollywood celebrities, including
Christina Pickles of ``St. Elsewhere,'' who attended the Cypress
rally.
   Blockades were expected to continue through Saturday. Pro-choice
advocates vowed area clinics would remain open.
   The national Operation Rescue organization began its blockades
outside women's clinics in 1987 and since then, more than 21,000 of
its anti-abortion protesters have been arrested nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
