<DOCNO> AP890323-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MarcosCabinent-Arrests     03-23 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos Cabinent-Arrests,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arrest Warrants Issued for Marcos Cabinet Ministers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents who arrested an ex-cabinet minister of
Ferdinand Marcos have warrants to arrest five other ex-aides to the
ousted Philippines leader, but aren't expecting them to visit, a
federal agent said Thursday.
   A list prepared by Marcos aides for security guards at St.
Francis Medical Center showed that 11 former cabinet members were
expected to visit the ailing Marcos, who has been hospitalized since
Jan. 15 with heart and lung ailments.
   ``After what happened yesterday, we don't have any information
that they're still coming,'' said Ralph Girardi, assistant FBI
agent-in-charge in Honolulu. ``We don't have any absolute word that
they're not, but we're really not expecting them anymore.''
   Marcos aides said the former ministers' trips may be canceled.
   The arrested aide, Jaime Laya, who was head of the Philippines
Central Bank and later minister of education, was taken into custody
on a material witness warrant Wednesday at Honolulu International
Airport. He was ordered to appear May 8 in U.S. District Court in
New York.
   Girardi said material witness arrest warrants or subpoenas were
also issued for at least five others, including five of the six
former cabinet ministers scheduled to arrive in Honolulu Thursday or
Friday.
   Those who had been expected to visit Marcos were C.E.A. Virata,
former prime minister and finance minister; Manual Alba, former
budget director; Jesus Azurin, former health minister, Placido Mapa
Jr., former secretary general; and Geronimo Velasco, former energy
minister, Girardi said.
   The only scheduled guest who was not on the FBI's list was Ted
Pena, former director of Natural Resources, Girardi said.
   ``We may have just overlooked him,'' he said.
   Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad said Jose Rono, former minister
of local governments, visited Marcos Thursday, but U.S. authorities
didn't approach him.
   Rono came from Los Angeles, Trinidad said, and ``they probably
didn't know he was coming so they didn't get him.''
   ``Everyone who cleared their trip with (Philippine President
Corazon) Aquino was told `sure, go ahead,' then when they get here
they're greeted by the FBI,'' Trinidad said. ``It seems like there
is an intimate cooperation between the two governments when Mrs.
Aquino has said her government wouldn't interfere in the U.S.
matters.''
   Meanwhile, former Philippine First Lady Imelda Marcos called Laya
``a poor guy (who) doesn't know anything about our business.''
   ``This is really something to happen in the United States, the
land of democracy,'' Mrs. Marcos told the Honolulu Star-Bulletin.
``He was only coming here to pay his respects to a dying man.
President Marcos' relationship with him was always very official.
   ``How very sad that a dying man can no longer have visitors,''
she said.
   Laya paid a $10,000 cash deposit on $100,000 bail Wednesday and
was forced to surrender his passport. He was released pending a
second bail hearing Friday to decide whether he can leave the United
States before his scheduled New York appearance.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Charles LaBella, lead prosecutor in the
Marcos case, said Laya would not necessarily be held until May 8.
   ``He's important to the government's case and we want to make
sure he's here to testify at the government's main case,'' LaBella
said. ``It's calculated to make sure there's sufficient bail to
ensure his appearance at trial.''
   Laya was director of Marcos' budget office in the mid-1970s and
was later named Central Bank governor. He was forced to resign from
the Central Bank in 1984 after the discovery of an overstatement of
$600 million in the country's foreign exchange reserves.
   Despite criticism, Marcos then appointed Laya minister of
education, a post he held until Marcos was ousted in 1986.
   U.S. authorities said Laya earlier refused to talk to federal
prosecutors in New York and Manila.
   Marcos, accused of stealing more than $100 million from his
homeland and stashing much of it in the United States, remained in
guarded condition Thursday at St. Francis.
   Although Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent to the charges and was
freed on $5 million bail, her husband's ill health has prevented his
arraignment.
   Four other visiting former aides _ Blas Ople, former minister of
labor; Estelito Mendoza, former minster of justice; Conrado
Estrella, former minister of agrarian reform; and Sylvia Montes,
former minister of social services _ have already received subpoenas
and were ordered to appear in court with Layas.
</TEXT>
