<FIRST>u a AM-Chubb-DroughtInsurance     03-23 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chubb-Drought Insurance,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Paid in Drought Insurance Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than $18 million was mailed Thursday to
6,860 farmers in 10 states who settled a legal dispute with Chubb
Corp. over crop insurance applications rejected during the 1988
drought.
   Lawrence Kane Jr., a Cincinnati lawyer who was appointed by U.S.
District Judge Carl Rubin last fall to oversee the payments, said
the farmers should be mailed the remaining 50 percent of their
settlement payments by late April.
   Kane said he and his staff are still trying to resolve objections
by about 930 farmers who oppose the $36.6 million settlement with
Chubb Corp., based in Warren, N.J., and its insurance subsidiaries.
Also still pending are processing problems with the cases of some
other farmers, which remain to be worked out.
   The class-action case involves 7,484 farmers in Illinois, Iowa,
Ohio, Kentucky, Indiana, Tennessee, Minnesota, Michigan, Missouri
and Wisconsin. The first payments cover 6,860 of the claims.
   The farmers sued after Chubb began rejecting premiums and
applications for insurance against crop damage as the drought
worsened last year. Chubb lawyers said the company was prepared to
sell only about $40 million in coverage, but that its brokers sold
more than $200 million.
   Chubb and its insurance subsidiaries agreed in November to a
settlement in which the company set aside a fund of $48.1 million to
settle the farmers' claims. Kane said that not all of the fund may
have to be used to pay the claims.
   Chubb Corp. and the farmers since have teamed to sue Good Weather
International Corp., the agent that Chubb alleges violated its
contract with the company by selling more than the available number
of crop insurance policies. Rubin is to hear that lawsuit May 1.
   Good Weather has refused to comment on the case while it is under
litigation.
</TEXT>
