<FIRST>u a AM-ThinBlueLine-Homecoming 1stLd-Writethru   03-23 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thin Blue Line-Homecoming, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0758,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tears, Hugs Greet Adams in Hometown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Later, he ...' to to RESTORE dropped word ``in.''
Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Adams was ...' Tressa in 10th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randall Dale Adams, newly freed from the
charges that nearly led to his execution, arrived home Thursday to
tears and hugs from family members and friends who had waited more
than a decade for his release.
   ``You're supposed to have a resurrection around Easter,'' Adams'
mother, Mildred, said shortly after embracing her son as he stepped
off the plane at Port Columbus International Airport. ``I guess this
is it.''
   Adams arrived in his hometown just as the Dallas County, Texas,
district attorney announced Adams would not be retried for the 1976
slaying of a Dallas policeman.
   Told of the news as he arrived, Adams remained skeptical.
   ``I'll wait until I hear it from my attorney. I'm not supposed to
talk about the case,'' Adams told reporters.
   Later, he said, ``I've been standing in a twilight zone for the
past 12{ years. ... I was in that twilight zone until the door
opened. Thank God it did.''
   Adams was convicted and sentenced to die in 1977 for the murder
of Dallas police officer Robert Wood, a crime to which another man
has virtually confessed. Adams was three days away from exection
before his sentence was commuted in 1980 to life in prison.
   The case came under scrutiny in the documentary ``The Thin Blue
Line,'' which questioned the testimony of the state's key witness,
David Harris. Earlier this week, Adams was released from prison in
Texas on grounds his first trial was unfair.
   As he arrived in Columbus, Adams embraced his mother first, and
both broke into tears. Errol Morris, director of ``The Thin Blue
Line,'' had to battle a contingent of reporters and photographers to
get close to Adams. He and Adams then embraced.
   About 100 supporters, many of them wearing yellow lapel ribbons,
looked on. Among them was Tressa Lucas, a family friend.
   ``It feels great,'' Ms. Lucas said. ``It's the best I've felt in
40 years, almost. His mother and I are real good friends, and we
just stuck by each other. She's just really had a hard time.
   ``I told her all along that the Lord would have him released.''
   Mayor Dana Rinehart joined the merrymakers, offering a job to
Adams, who was unemployed before his arrest in Dallas. Rinehart said
he had no specific job in mind but would work that out with Adams.
   Adams told Rinehart jokingly, ``I didn't really want to be
mayor.''
   Asked if he expected such a reception, Adams said, ``I couldn't
have dreamed this. I knew I would be home, but not this way.''
   Adams, who appeared red-faced and said he did not feel well after
he got off the plane, was given an Ohio State University cap and a
lei made of daffodils.
   A few moments later, he held a news conference at the airport. As
he walked from the terminal gate toward the area where the news
conference was to be held, Adams' mother and his sister, Nancy,
stood on either side of him and appeared to be holding him up. He
was taken to a private room in the airport and appeared fully
recovered when he began speaking to reporters.
   While Adams was being reunited with his family here, District
Attorney John Vance announced in Dallas that a motion had been filed
with state District Judge Larry Baraka to dismiss the capital murder
charge against Adams.
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals in March set aside the
conviction, saying Adams hadn't gotten a fair trial because
prosecutors suppressed evidence and witnesses lied on the stand.
</TEXT>
