<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Immigration     03-23 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Immigration,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico: U.S. Immigration Officials Can't Be Based in Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Relations Department announced
Wednesday it has no agreement with the United States allowing U.S.
immigration officials to be based in Mexico.
   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service recently posted
teams of agents in Mexico to monitor the routes of Central Americans
passing through the country on their way to the United States,
mostly to southern Texas.
   The operation, which began Feb. 21 and has been canceled, came
under criticism in Mexico. Mexican newspapers called it ``outrageous
intrusion on Mexican sovereignty.''
   The INS was quoted as saying its patrols were carried out with
the cooperation of the Mexican government.
   The Foreign Relations Department, in a dispatch sent to news
agencies Wednesday afternoon, said, ``There is no diplomatic accord
between Mexico and the United States that establishes the
collaboration of the Mexican police and the INS to avoid the flow of
undocumented immigrants to the United States.''
   The INS agents, traveling through Mexico, filed their daily
reports to Washington from the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City, news
reports said.
   The INS has denied that the operation was undercover, but
canceled it anyway.
   Central Americans have been emigrating to the United States in
ever-increasing numbers, U.S. officials say. Some officials estimate
that 100,000 Central Americans will try to enter the United States
this year.
   On Feb. 21, the U.S. government clamped down on the flow of
aliens asking for asylum in the United States by demanding proof of
persecution. Since then, the overwhelming number of asylum cases in
south Texas have been denied and the number of people seeking
amnesty has dropped.
</TEXT>
