<FIRST>r a AM-Vincennes-Bomb     03-23 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vincennes-Bomb,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Van Bombing Reenacted for Television Showing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-crime group blew up a van Wednesday to
dramatize the bombing of a vehicle driven by the wife of a Navy
captain, and authorities said the reenactment will be shown on local
television to draw out witnesses.
   The videotaped bombing is part of the investigation into a March
10 blast that destroyed a van driven by Sharon Rogers, wife of USS
Vincennes Capt. Will C. Rogers III.
   A van similar to the one driven by Mrs. Rogers was taken to a
deserted area near an airstrip and rigged for explosion and fire by
Fire Department bomb experts.
   The reenactment is intended ``to trigger something in the mind of
someone who may have seen something that day or in Mrs. Rogers'
neighborhood leading up to the time of the bombing,'' said Molly
Wilson Cartmill, executive director of the San Diego chapter of
Crime Stoppers.
   The national, non-profit organization, which staged the
reenactment in cooperation with local and federal authorities,
operates an anonymous tip hot line and raises reward money for those
who help authorities solve crimes.
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Rogers was interviewed on videotape at San Diego
police headquarters for the Crime Stoppers segment on the attack.
The tape will be distributed to local television stations Monday.
   ``My understanding is she was an excellent speaker,'' said
Cartmill. ``She did really well. She talks a lot about that morning,
the explosion itself, and she makes a plea for information'' from
the public.
   Mrs. Rogers escaped injury in the explosion, which occured when
she was stopped at an intersection near the La Jolla area of San
Diego.
   Authorities are investigating if the attack was terrorist
retaliation for the Vincennes' mistaken destruction of an Iranian
jetliner in the Persian Gulf last July. All 290 aboard were killed.
   A total of $27,000 is being offered for information in the case:
$25,000 from an anonymous San Diego developer, $1,000 from Crime
Stoppers and $1,000 from the Vincennes crew.
   The videotape is being created with the cooperation of the FBI,
the lead agency in the investigation, as well as Naval Investigative
Services and local authorities, Cartmill said.
   On Tuesday, the Rogerses made their first public statement since
the bombing, sending out a letter that calls on the nation to resist
bowing to terrorism.
   ``The image of a burning van in the middle of a street of our
community must not become a symbol of fear and unreasoned
reaction,'' they said.
   Mrs. Rogers reportedly is resentful over the loss of her teaching
job at La Jolla Country Day school following the bombing.
   Although the school has maintained that her leaving was a mutual
decision, sources told the Los Angeles Times that Mrs. Rogers was
fired after the possibility of terrorism was raised.
   Jim Stewart, the school's development director, said officials
are standing by their earlier statement that Mrs. Rogers' and school
officials decided she should leave her fourth-grade teaching
position ``to ensure the safety of the children.''
   Stewart also said the school will pay Mrs. Rogers her full salary
through August. He declined to say how much that is.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
