<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0830EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Portugal-Africa Adv29   03-23 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Portugal-Africa, Adv 29,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs March 29 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Portugal Wooing Former Colonies in Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portugal is trying to win the friendship
of the former African colonies where it fought bitter wars just 15
years ago.
   Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva's recent visit to
Guinea-Bissau, Portugal's former West African colony where the fight
for independence was the fiercest, was the latest in a series of
journeys that included the Atlantic island nations of Cape Verde and
Sao Tome e Principe and is likely to continue with Mozambique in
southeast Africa later this year.
   A package of nine accords signed in Bissau, including an
agreement to create the framework of an escudo zone, is seen as an
effort to regain influence in Africa and improve Portugal's
diplomatic standing worldwide. The escudo is Portugal's currency.
   A string of left-leaning governments that followed the Portuguese
military coup April 25, 1974, never seemed able to get close to the
then-Marxist revolutionary governments in the five African countries
where Portuguese is still the official language.
   The five nations _ known by the Portuguese acronym PALOPS, for
Portuguese-Speaking African Countries _ are Angola, Cape Verde,
Guinea-Bissau, Mozambique and Sao Tome e Principe. They embarked on
a Marxist-inspired path of development via industrialization and
centralized economies after gaining independence in the mid-1970s.
   According to Adelino Torres, lecturer on Africa at Lisbon's
Higher Institute for Economics, ``it was always a question of
values'' with Portugal's socialist governments.
   ``If (African) governments weren't democratic enough, there was
no deal. It was an obstacle to cooperation.''
   Torres said Cavaco Silva, a center-right Social Democrat Cavaco
Silva, ``puts business first.''
   ``The reinforcement of our relations with the PALOPS is a
priority of this government,'' says Jose Durao Barroso, secretary of
state for foreign affairs and cooperation, who is regarded as the
driving force behind Portugal's African policy.
   Since the Social Democrats under Cavaco Silva won Portugal's
first absolute parliamentary majority in July 1987, Portugal has
signed 78 cooperation accords with its former African colonies.
   In the beginning these involved agreements on sports, education,
farming and health, but recent agreements include military accords
with all PALOPS countries except Angola, which remains locked in
civil war.
   Nevertheless, Portugal will become the first Western nation to
have a military attache in Luanda, Angola's capital, following a
recent exchange agreement.
   The decision to guarantee the convertibility of Guinea-Bissau's
peso currency by linking it to Portugal's escudo, was a ``major,
qualitative step in cooperation,'' Durao Barroso said.
   Sao Tome and Cape Verde are likely to be interested in a similar
accord. Mozambique's membership in an escudo zone is expected to be
discussed before the end of the year.
   Up to now, Portugal's drive for closer links with the Africans
has concentrated mostly on the three smallest countries.
   Because Cape Verde, Sao Tome e Principe and Guinea-Bissau lack
the size and potential wealth of Angola and Mozambique, they have
retained close trading links with Portugal.
   The view in Lisbon is that increased influence in Mozambique and
Angola would lend Portugal greater political weight in the
international arena.
   Foreign Minister Joao de Deus Pinheiro has been drumming up
international support for a projected $600 million-economic
assistance plan for Angola, once fighting ends between the Marxist
government in Luanda and U.S.-backed rebels of UNITA, the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
   Portugal has pledged $50 million toward the rehabilitation of the
strategic east-west Benguela railway that before independence
provided a vital route for exports from nearby Zaire and Zambia to
the Atlantic.
   But competition for influence in Angola, potentially one of
sub-Saharan Africa's richest nations, is growing.
   Brazil, itself a former Portuguese territory, has already granted
Luanda a $1.2 billion-credit to be repaid in Angolan oil.
   Italy, France, Spain and other European Economic Community
nations are looking to increase trade with Angola, a country
Portugal regarded as the jewel in its colonial crown.
   As the poorest member of the 12-nation EEC, Portugal cannot
compete on economic terms with its European neighbors. But Durao
Barroso says the Portuguese should cash in on a competitive
advantage of experience and adaptability.
   ``The Portuguese have a good understanding of Africa and Africans
... and we cost less,'' he said. ``It's usually cheaper to employ a
Portuguese teacher, say, than one from a richer country.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs March 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
