<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-LateNight-PBS ADV24   03-23 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-LateNight-PBS, ADV 24,0854</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, March 24, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wholey Talking Again on PBS; Talented Cast in `Men'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid the rock 'em, sock 'em yocks of Saturday
night, viewers will soon have a saner alternative when a kinder kind
of talk-show host, Dennis Wholey, returns to PBS with ``LateNight
America.''
   ``I guess you could say we're going to be the Saturday
alternative to wrestling and the Church Lady,'' Wholey said,
referring to the popular character on NBC's ``Saturday Night Live.''
   Wholey's two-hour weekly talk show will feature in-studio guests
_ newsmakers, authors and celebrities _ responding to telephone
queries and comments. It premieres Saturday on about 100 public
television stations nationwide.
   Wholey, a former Detroit radio talk-show host, was host of the
critically praised ``LateNight America'' on PBS from 1982 until he
ended the run in 1985.
   ``I made a decision to leave, because I wanted to take a look at
my own background,'' he said in a telephone interview from
Washington, where the show will originate. ``I grew up in an
alcoholic home, and as a recovering alcoholic myself, I just wanted
to get out of the public eye.''
   Wholey went through private therapy, started some Adult Children
of Alcoholics groups and wrote books: ``The Courage of Change:
Personal Conversations About Alcoholism,'' ``Are You Happy?'' and
the most recent ``Becoming Your Own Parent: The Solution for Adult
Children of Alcoholics.''
   After all that, he said, ``I felt very good, and all of a sudden
it came time to go back on the air again.''
   Part of the talk show will revolve around self-help issues, but
mostly it will be a discussion of an eclectic collection of subjects
_ for instance, upcoming topics include gun control and the Academy
Awards.
   Viewers who flee the confrontational styles of many current talk
shows can relax with Wholey.
   ``I think that people trust me,'' he said. ``I don't think that
television is church. I make mistakes. I probably mispronounce
words. I'm up there, I'm one of them, and I think the audience
perceives that I'm part of who they are.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In ABC's new ``Men,'' four high-school buddies, a surgeon, a
lawyer, a newspaper columnist and a cop, now in their 30s, still
meet weekly over poker to crack wise. Just like a million guys in
America.
   Despite the unlikely premise, ``Men,'' set in Baltimore and
filmed in Toronto, comes darn close to succeeding, thanks mainly to
the fine cast: Ted Wass (``Soap''), Saul Rubinek, Ving Rhames and
Tom O'Brien.
   It premieres Saturday.
   The look of the show, directed by Peter Werner, will contribute
to the already unavoidable comparison to ``thirtysomething.''
``Men'' isn't ``thirtysomething,'' even though it is about 30-ish
folks who spend a lot of time trying to figure out why they're not
happy. It's not nearly as well-written.
   Rubinek, the only Canadian among the regulars, plays Paul, a
columnist for the Baltimore Sun who rhapsodizes about his ex-wife,
before finding out she plans not to get back with him but to marry
an investment banker who saves Paul's ego by turning out to be bald.
   Wass is surgeon Steven, who spends most of his time picking up
new women, then finding something wrong with them and dumping them
before things get serious. Rhames is lawyer Charlie, the black
member of group and its resident, well-adjusted family man.
   O'Brien is Danny, a quick-tempered young cop, whose older brother
Tom, also a cop, was a founding member of the group.
   In the pilot, Tom is killed chasing down a purse-snatcher in an
incongruously violent sequence. His death prompts soul-searching
among the others. Too often the pilot wanders into sentimentality
when it isn't being awfully convenient.
   Steven is the surgeon who operates on Tom. What are there, four
people in all of Baltimore? Paul works at a newspaper, but doesn't
seem to write anything. Would Jimmy Breslin not write about the
death of a cop who was one of his best friends?
   After Tom's funeral, Paul goes off to the old high-school
football field. Steven shows up there, too, just by chance. The two
run across the field reliving that touchdown run that won the big
game.
   Steven chides that the game-winner occurred ``only once.'' ``Once
was immortal,'' declares Paul. ``Once gives me bragging rights
forever.''
   So it's been lifted from innumerable buddy movies. It's still a
nice scene.
   By the end of the episode, Danny has won his place in the group
and we're back at the poker table.
   ``Men'' is worth dealing in, at least for a few hands.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   COS MEETS BIG BIRD _ Bill Cosby will be the host of a ``Sesame
Street'' 20th anniversary special on NBC April 7. Guests will
include Ray Charles and Placido Domingo. Domingo, incidentally, will
be the guest star on ``The Cosby Show'' this coming Thursday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, March 24</NOTE>
