<DOCNO> AP890323-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0646EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-BirminghamRevival Adv29   03-23 0879</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Birmingham Revival, Adv 29,0902</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, March 29, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>England's Second City Celebrates a Birthday and Economic Recovery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now England's second largest city,
Birmingham has been around for at least 900 years, but this year it
is celebrating a centennial and a new beginning.
   It is marking its recovery from a severe recession and hopes
people will forget what they thought about it before and take note
of what's good about it now.
   It was in 1889 that Queen Victoria, who had her own misgivings
about the place, granted Birmingham its city charter. That's the
reason for the centennial. But it is using the occasion to bury a
recession that wiped out more than 200,000 jobs and ravaged its
traditional metals industry.
   The city of 1.05 million, 100 miles northwest of London, is
hoping the year-long celebration, with more than 600 individual
events, also will clear away its image as a cultural wasteland and
sterile, concrete jungle.
   Birmingham-bashing is as old as the city itself.
   History books tell of Victoria drawing the shades of her royal
carriage to block out its industrial soot, gloom and grime when she
came here on her travels through the English midlands.
   In her 1816 novel ``Emma'' Jane Austen wrote: ``One has no great
hopes for Birmingham. I always say there is something direful in the
sound.''
   ``Manufacturing used to be a very dirty industry,'' explained
Andrew Fretter, City Hall's principal marketing officer. ``It's not
anymore. People haven't yet adjusted to that new situation.''
   Birmingham has been a trading center for centuries, although the
Domesday Book of 1086 rated it one of the poorest in Warwickshire
County.
   It prospered during the 16th century as a finishing center and
marketing outlet for basic metal goods from the surrounding area and
is acknowledged to have been the birthplace of the Industrial
Revolution long before it became a city.
   As England's workshop, Birmingham attracted a rich diversity of
immigrants, primarily from Britain's farflung Empire, until the
recession struck in 1979. ``It hit hard,'' Fretter said. ``Vast
swathes in the city of Birmingham were left totally derelict.''
   ``The shakeout of the Birmingham economy was catastrophic, to say
the least,'' said Albert Bore, chairman of the economic development
committee of the Labor Party-controlled City Council.
   Birmingham's recovery was spurred by the council's sponsorship of
several megaprojects, including a modern science park and the
$215-million International Convention Center scheduled to open in
1991.
   It also spent the equivalent of $2.5 million on a bid to be the
host of the 1992 Summer Olympics. The bid failed _ Spain won out _
but it signified the new confidence of a city that only two years
ago came dead last in a survey of the quality of life in 38 British
cities.
   Besides its traditional prides and joys _ more canals than Venice
in Italy, Europe's largest public library, a rating as having the
best tap water of any big city in the world, even if it is piped
from Wales _ Birmingham is scheduling $2.5 billion for development.
   Manufacturing production has outstripped the previous record set
in 1979, 80 percent of manufacturers are working at more than 90
percent capacity and unemployment has fallen to 7.5 percent from
1982's peak of 16.8 percent.
   Herbert Austin set up his automobile works in the city's
Longbridge district in 1905 and pioneered the popular Austin 7.
Today, Birmingham holds Britain's only street-circuit car race, the
annual Super Prix, and the auto industry is once again the city's
largest employer, home to the Rover Group's modern robotic car plant
and the Austin Morris division of the British Leyland Motor Corp.
   Business travel to the city, streamlined by a modern
international airport, has helped create 73,000 jobs and has made
Birmingham the fifth most visited city in England. Visitors spent
the equivalent of $635 million here in 1987.
   ``Brummies,'' as Birmingham's residents are known, concede they
now must pay attention to how their city looks, as well as how it
works.
   In the 1960s, most of the city's Victorian heart was torn out and
replaced by featureless concrete and mirror glass buildings,
surrounded _ some say strangled _ by a beltway.
   It's architectural style is still symbolized by two of its best
known landmarks _ the Bull Ring, a covered shopping complex soon to
be replaced by a $688-million continental style arcade, and
Spaghetti Junction, a vast criss-crossing of roads, cloverleafs and
overpasses.
   The planners ``ripped the city apart in the '50s and '60s,'' Bore
said. ``The drive to clear the slums and to provide for the age of
the motor car lacked the sensitivity the planning community now
has.''
   The city has an eclectic mixture of performing arts: UB40, the
acclaimed multiracial rock group, comes from Birmingham; ``Spitting
Images,'' the wickedly satirical puppet show is produced here, and
Simon Rattle, the wunderkind of British conductors, has led the
Birmingham Symphony Orchestra since he was 25 years old.
   In a recent coup, the City Council lured the Sadler's Wells Royal
Ballet from London with a $10.3-million financing offer. The
traveling section of the Royal Ballet will move into the 1,950-seat
Hippodrome in August 1990.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed AMs March 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-JoblessinEgypt Adv30   03-23 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jobless in Egypt, Adv 30,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs AMs March 30 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>For College Grads, It's Tough Finding a Job in Egypt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nahid Samir went to college and earned an
engineering degree. Today, she's a housekeeper-nanny.
   Mohamed studied business administration at Cairo University. He
drives a taxi.
   They're lucky; they have jobs.
   Other college graduates _ roughly a million by one official
estimate _ can't find any work at all, a situation that is
potentially explosive.
   Egyptian universities turn out 100,000 graduates a year. Many
find their dreams brutally shattered by a twin headaches in this
overpopulated country of 54 million: unemployment and
underemployment.
   Official estimates put Egypt's jobless rate at around 10 percent.
But another 10 percent are in ``jobs'' supplied to graduates under a
30-year-old government policy that pays almost nothing in wages but
requires little more of the job-holder than signing a work register.
   ``It is a high percentage without doubt,'' said Mokhtar
Abdel-Hamid of the governing National Democratic Party, head of the
labor committee in the People's Assembly, the national parliament.
``We are a developing nation and need the efforts of every person.
This high percentage can affect development.''
   For the first time, President Hosni Mubarak's government is
ringing the alarm bell and testing a variety of remedies.
   ``We do not need more people,'' Mubarak said in a recent speech.
``What we need is better planning and development of the educational
system, and connecting it to the needs of development.
   ``We hope the government will be able to open new fields for
(graduates) so we can destroy this unemployment phenomenon.''
   Proposed solutions include small-business loans for graduates or
selling them cheap desert land for agricultural reclamation. Opening
retraining centers also has been suggested, in hopes of turning
unemployed graduates into skilled tradesmen, who are much in demand.
   The employment problem is the result of several factors. Very
important is the mushrooming population, increasing by a million
every nine months. Also, the world oil glut that hit the economies
of the Persian Gulf countries brought home to Egypt's labor pool
hundreds of thousands of Egyptians whose jobs abroad had disappeared.
   Part of the problem lies with two policies left over from Gamal
Abdel Nasser's socialist Egypt of the 1950s and 1960s: free higher
education, which has created a surplus of university graduates and a
shortage of skilled laborers, and the promise of a job to any
graduate who can't find one in private business.
   By January 1989, the government was looking to find jobs for
people who graduated in June 1983.
   Egypt's economy is stagnant, encumbered by a $44-billion foreign
debt and high inflation.
   The People's Assembly has been discussing unemployment and
Mubarak himself is meeting with senior politicians in search of a
solution.
   ``Lots of things combined and led to this unemployment problem,''
the assembly's Abdel-Hamid said. He enumerated the main ones as
population growth, the large number of graduates, the lack of money
for building new factories to create jobs and the return of the
workers from the Persian Gulf oil fields.
   ``There has to be a study to know what the Egyptian market needs,
and then (we should) set education policies accordingly,''
Abdel-Hamid said. ``There also has to be more work on institutes or
junior colleges to teach certain skills that are needed like
carpentry and plumbing.''
   The Engineers' Union says 20,000 new engineers are looking for
jobs. Fewer new doctors than that are out of work, but a physician's
starting salary in a government hospital is 60 pounds ($25) a month.
   And with the present rate of population growth, 6 million new
job-seekers will enter the market in the next decade.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, March 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-LearningInAmerica Adv26   03-23 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Learning In America, Adv 26,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>PBS Series Exposes Flaws in U.S. Education System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American education is laid bare in a landmark
television series virtually certain to leave viewers unsettled and
embarrassed.
   ``Learning In America,'' starting Monday night on PBS, is a
five-part, multimillion dollar look at what's happening in the
nation's classrooms, featuring Roger Mudd and three correspondents
from the MacNeil-Lehrer Newshour.
   The portrait is always revealing, sometimes chilling.
   ``I don't want to graduate, to tell you the truth. It's just fun.
I like it,'' says a California high school senior interested mainly
in sports.
   ``I think it's my senior year and I'm going to relax,'' says his
friend, explaining why he's taking nutrition and lifestyle courses
instead of the math he needs to become a computer repairman.
   And from Denver high school teacher Martha Nagel: ``This is a job
that breaks your heart every day.''
   The makers of ``Learning in America'' roved from California to
East Harlem, from Ireland to Japan, to paint a broad television
canvas unusual in the far-flung, locally controlled education field.
   ``The reason education doesn't get covered well on TV is that
it's so decentralized. Finding out about what's going on is very
time-consuming,'' said Joe Quinlan, executive producer of the series.
   Chrysler Corp. put up nearly $4 million for the series, equally
divided between production and promotion, and had nothing to do with
content. A number of other companies were also interested in
financing the project, Quinlan said.
   ``That's one indicator of the anxiety levels of American
business,'' he said. ``American business is in shock right now''
about the state of the education system.
   A shocker in the first section of the series is the revelation
that New York Life of Freehold, N.J. is shipping thousands of
medical claims to a rural Irish town to be processed. A personnel
officer of the company said she can't find enough competent,
motivated high school graduates close to home to fill her workforce.
   Mudd, who taught for a year at a private boys school before going
into journalism, said in an interview that the two students drifting
through high school ``are probably generally typical of that big
group of kids between the gifted and the slow. The top and the
bottom get all the attention. It's the middle group that's
worrisome.''
   Mudd noted the boys' plans to attend a free, open-admissions
junior college and remarked: ``In one year they'll try to learn the
stuff they didn't learn because they'd been playing for four years,
and of course the taxpayers will have to foot that bill.''
   In fairness to the boys, the series notes that U.S. schools don't
have clear goals and expectations for middle-range students. This is
contrasted with Japan, where all students are expected to be
serious, disciplined and solidly prepared for their futures.
   Another key point is that Japanese parents are totally involved
in their children's education, while U.S. parents are more likely to
be locked in a consuming struggle for economic survival.
   ``The main thing I noticed (in making the series) was how fast
the American family has changed and how far we all are behind in
responding to that, not just the schools but the whole society,''
Quinlan said. He cited women in the workplace, divorce rates and
single-parent families, latch-key kids and students working 30 hours
a week after school. ``It really hit home _ we're not in Kansas
anymore, Toto,'' Quinlan said.
   The most disturbing parts of the series examine inequities in
American schools and problems in the teaching profession. Nagel is
shown trying to call her gynecologist from a public phone; a 23-year
veteran doesn't have his own classroom; an incompetent teacher is
fired and then hired within hours by another principal who never
bothered to call for a reference.
   Mudd said he came away from the series ``agitated but not
depressed, because enough places are in fact doing something and
doing it well.'' But correspondent John Merrow, a former teacher who
holds a Harvard Ph.D. in education, said the successful formulas at
such schools most often are ignored elsewhere.
   ``All these terrific things that happen, they are not copied,''
Merrow said in an interview. ``There are some very hopeful signs.
The question is, is progress being made at a fast enough rate to
keep us from going into the dumpster?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 26</NOTE>
