<DOCNO> AP890323-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Wal-Mart-WaltonProfile Adv26   03-23 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wal-Mart-Walton Profile, Adv 26,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retail Empire Built By Bargain-Preaching Entrepreneur</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DE SOTO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The store manager of the Wal-Mart in this
community on the outskirts of Dallas tells a story that gives an
insight into the man considered responsible for a retailing
phenomenon.
   Manager Don Bost remembers one day last summer when a secretary
telephoned from Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s corporate headquarters in
Bentonville, Ark. Chairman Sam Walton was about to land at a nearby
airport and the secretary asked if someone could fetch him and bring
him to the De Soto store.
   Paying unexpected calls on stores is one way Walton has kept in
close touch with everyday goings-on. His example is followed by
other Wal-Mart executives and most make a point of spending a lot of
time in the field.
   Says Ed Nagy, district manager for 9 stores in the Dallas
metropolitan area, ``It's not like `Uh-oh, someone's coming,'
because they're always out.''
   By all accounts, Sam Walton's personality permeates operations
throughout the company.
   Everyone, from Wal-Mart President and Chief Operating Officer
David Glass down to an hourly store worker, can readily quote the
gospel according to Sam, as he is called.
   To paraphrase Sam's primary rules of retailing, ``Rule No.1 is
the customer is always right. Rule No.2 says just in case the
customer's wrong, revert to rule No.1.''
   If the principles sound old-fashioned and homespun, they are
because that's the way Sam is, people who know him say.
   He shuns the limelight that his company's success has shed on him
and has decided to refuse almost all press requests for interviews.
   He's happy to chat with folks in his stores, though.
   He also regularly reminds Wal-Mart ``associates'' that
hospitality to customers is crucial. He preaches it in person or via
high-tech satellite hookup with his stores.
   Wal-Mart employees became known as associates under a company
effort to prove it cared about employees, partly to thwart a union
organizing effort in the late 1960s.
   One of the most sensitive subjects for Walton is the fortune he's
amassed.
   A close associate says Sam would ``probably give anything'' not
to be named on Fortune magazine's list of the country's wealthiest
people. The magazine has estimated that his immediate family's stake
in Wal-Mart stock is worth about $6.8 billion.
   ``Sam Walton is more interested in his backhand than he is in his
bank account,'' says Don Shinkle, Wal-Mart spokesman.
   Samuel Moore Walton turns 71 on March 29. He was born in
Kingfisher, Okla., and grew up as the son of a farm-mortgage banker.
   He graduated from the University of Missouri with an economics
degree in 1940 and joined J.C. Penney Co. as a management trainee in
Des Moines, Iowa. After serving three years in the Army, he went to
Arkansas and opened a Ben Franklin five-and-dime store, eventually
becoming the company's biggest franchisee.
   The seeds of the Wal-Mart empire were sown when Sam and his
brother James L., or Bud, opened the first Wal-Mart Discount City in
1962. The rest will probably earn an entry in the history of U.S.
retail trade.
   Bud is a senior vice president and board member of Wal-Mart.
Three of the four grown children Sam and his wife Helen had are
involved with the company in various capacities.
   Sam hasn't slowed much, enjoying hunting and tennis as much as
ever, and is said not to suffer after effects from a bout with
leukemia, now in remission. He spends less time in the office since
handing over most responsiblities to David Glass. Sam is still
chairman of the board.
   Glass doesn't hesitate when asked if Wal-Mart can flourish
without Sam. The answer is an emphatic yes because, he says, ``We
have great people.'' The Walton family will always be involved, he
adds.
   Commenting on the future, Glass says: ``We'll be judged on what
we produce today. Tomorrow, what we've done in the past won't
matter.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:RingCycle Adv26   03-23 1252</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Ring Cycle, Adv 26,1300</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 26 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sustaining Wagner's Creative Imagination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1848, Richard Wagner had just completed the
scoring for ``Lohengrin'' when the idea for a work on the Nibelung _
dwarfs who owned a magic ring and a horde of gold _ began to
crystallize.
   Twenty-eight years later, he put the final touches on the score
of ``Der Ring des Nibelungen'' (``The Ring of the Nibelungen''). It
was a staggering accomplishment at the time and remains so today.
   Two major companies are about to meet the most difficult
challenge in the world of opera _ producing Wagner's Ring, 17 hours
of music originally intended by Wagner to be performed over four
days.
   The Metropolitan Opera will perform the entire epic about love
and greed and gods and goddesses three times in the next few weeks _
the first time it has presented it in so short a span in 90 years.
The Berlin Opera is bringing its version to Washington's Kennedy
Center in June.
   Wagner deliberately made his Ring inaccessible to most theaters
of the day, and he created an opera house in Bayreuth, Germany, in
1876 to show the work.
   ``I no longer gave a thought to the Dresden or any other court
theater in the world; my sole preoccupation was to produce something
that should free me, once and for all, from this irrational
subservience,'' the composer wrote in his autobiography.
   Few opera companies perform the four works _ ``Das Rheingold,''
``Die Walkure,'' ``Siegfried'' and ``Gotterdammerung'' _ in four
days. Usually, the operas are seen singularly, or if produced as a
ring cycle, are stretched out over weeks or months.
   ``Clearly Wagner knew what he was doing,'' said Speight Jenkins,
general director of the Seattle Opera. ``For the sake of the power
of it, it needs to go the way it was meant to go.''
   Seattle started an annual Ring cycle in 1975. It isn't performing
it this year because of the other two productions.
   Both productions are selling out, as Wagner buffs from around the
world scramble to attend one or both. At the Met, tickets for all
four operas range from $60 to $620. Tickets at the Kennedy Center
range from $120 to $380. The first cycle in Washington is June 2.
The first Met cycle starts April 1. All will be broadcast live on
radio.
   The Met's new production is the most traditional in the world.
The rocky mountain top where Brunnhilde, surrounded by a circle of
fire, is put into a deep sleep by her father, Wotan, resembles a
craggy peak. But the production departs from the very earliest
traditional stagings by eliminating her horse and not having the
Valkyries actually fly.
   Berlin's Ring, new in 1985, is set in a futuristic tunnel
designed by Peter Sykora. It was staged by Gotz Friedrich. Costumes
are contemporary with punk underpinnings. In ``Das Rheingold,'' for
example, Alberich is clothed in a diving suit with air hoses. And
Brunnhilde wears black leather and leather boots in the later operas.
   ``It's very modern. It is hot, especially with the lighting of
the stage. But it looks quite snazzy,'' said Dame Gwyneth Jones, who
sang Brunnhilde for Berlin in Japan last fall.
   ``It shows the personal, psychological relationships between the
persons in the Ring. It is a human Ring. It's not political at
all,'' said Jesus Lopez-Cobos, general director of the Berlin Opera.
   ``The idea is that every end is a new beginning. At the beginning
of the Ring you see a vision from the very end, and at the very end
you see once more the first picture of `Rheingold.' It is life,
going over and over.''
   At Bayreuth in 1976 to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the
opera house Wagner built, Pierre Boulez conducted and Patrice
Chereau staged the first Ring ever taped for television. The Chereau
Ring is a comment on corruption brought by industrialization.
Instead of three mermaids swimming around, ``Rheingold'' starts with
three prostitutes near a hydroelectric dam.
   In the Seattle production, Wotan is a stage director whose actors
get out of hand. ``It's the only untraditional cycle in America,''
Seattle's Jenkins said. ``We try to be as mythic as possible. I
think we follow very faithfully the words of the text and pay no
attention to the stage instructions of Wagner.'' The San Francisco
Opera is the only other American company performing a Ring.
   In 1985, when it was new, Seattle's unconventional Ring caused
fistfights at cocktail parties. By 1987, it was accepted and sold
out.
   Jenkins likes innovative approaches to staging the ``Ring.'' So
does Lopez-Cobos, who's conducting the first cycle in Washington.
   ``Sometimes they go too far,'' Lopez-Cobos said. ``I prefer to
take the risk. You are sometimes inspired by new and interesting
concepts on the stage.''
   Dame Gwyneth will sing Brunnhilde in the Met's third cycle. Next
fall she'll sing in a Ring at the San Francisco Opera and in a new
``Die Walkure'' at Covent Garden. The Welsh soprano has sung in a
lot of Rings, including the televised Bayreuth cycle.
   One problem with the Ring in the latter half of this century has
been that Hitler liked it and considered it a glorification of a
master race. Throughout its history it's story has been the subject
of differing and often bizarre interpretations. The music, though,
is another matter.
   In 1969, Milton Cross, the late commentator on the Met's Saturday
afternoon radio broadcasts, wrote that the music's greatness and
majesty present the ``conflicts, tenderness, grandeur, heroism,
passion and a tragedy that stirs us to the depths of our beings.''
   Wagner's grandson, Wieland Wagner, made a fresh start at Bayreuth
in 1951 _ the first postwar Ring. With an almost barren stage, he
stressed symbolism, thereby triggering the interpretive productions
which have followed.
   Both the Met's and Berlin's current Rings replaced productions
based on Wieland Wagner's. At the Met in 1975, the stage showed a
ring shape _ a giant, tilted, flat doughnut _ with singers in
costumes resembling dark choir robes. The lighting, mainly dark
blue, set the psychological moods.
   The shortest amount of time in which one could attend all four
operas in that 1975 Met Ring production was six weeks.
   The Met chose a traditional Ring, said artistic administrator
Jonathan Friend, because its audience prefers it. ``If you make a
mistake with the Ring, it is a very expensive mistake. The more
stylized a production is, the more difficult to get a larger
proportion of our public to accept it.
   ``In some of the stylized productions, the text and music are at
a complete opposite to what you're seeing on stage. Some would
rather see something unusual. Here, we would rather go the other
way.''
   James Levine, who conducts the Met's Ring, chose Otto Schenk to
create the production and suggested Gunther Schneider-Siemssen as
set designer.
   ``We knew Schenk would do something that was naturalistic,
romantic and warm without any particularly strong external idea
pushed onto the opera,'' Friend said.
   New York cast members include Toni Kraemer and William Johns as
Siegfried, Jessye Norman as Sieglinde, Gary Lakes as Siegmund,
Christa Ludwig as Fricka and Waltraute and Matti Salminen as Hagen.
   The two Brunnhildes in Washington will be Ute Vinzing and Anne
Evans. Rene Kollo will sing Siegfried and Peter Hofmann will sing
Siegmund. Wotan will be Robert Hale and Simon Estes, singing a cycle
each.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 2353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv26   03-23 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 26,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gingrich Choice by GOP May Crimp Bush's Bipartisanship</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was intramural politics, an election settled
by a bare majority of a chronic minority.
   But the leadership choice House Republicans made last Wednesday
may change the way both parties do business in Congress, and could
put a crimp in President Bush's new-look bipartisanship.
   The House GOP judgment seems to be that if they can't make laws,
at least they can make noise.
   Rep. Newt Gingrich of Georgia, newly elected as the assistant
Republican leader of the House, clearly intends to do just that.
Gingrich, loudly conservative, said he will build a more aggressive,
activist party.
   That is not the traditional task of the party whip, a job title
that traces to Parliament and was around before Congress was. The
whip's task is to line up votes, count heads, try to make sure his
party's supporters are on hand when the roll is called.
   The best of them deal in the favors and compromises that oil any
legislative machinery. It's a doubly difficult assignment when
undertaken for the programs of a Republican administration in an
overwhelmingly Democratic House.
   But compromise is not Gingrich's style. And he says the party
wanted a new job description when he was chosen whip, 87 to 85, over
Rep. Edward Madigan of Illinois. He also says that his primary
assignment is to work for House Republicans, not necessarily for
President Bush.
   Indeed, Rep. Robert Michel of Illinois, the minority leader, said
after Gingrich was chosen that he may have to take on some of the
vote-counting and other duties that normally go to the whip.
Michel's new deputy has no practice in those assignments.
   Gingrich and his conservative allies argue that the way toward a
Republican resurgence in the House is confrontation, not compromise.
They say that House GOP leaders have been too tractable and too
anxious to get along with the Democratic majority.
   By now it seems a permanent majority, especially to frustrated
political warriors like Gingrich. Republicans haven't controlled the
House in 34 years, going on 35. The House lineup _ now 258
Democrats, 174 Republicans, with three seats vacant _ is determined
in 435 separate elections every other year. National issues, trends
and tickets affect those contests. State and regional issues,
personalities and, above all, incumbency, affect them, too.
   The Gingrich game plan is based on the theory that the national
side of that political equation can become the base for a Republican
revival. That's in tune with the aggressive outlook of new leaders
at the Republican National Committee and the party's Congressional
Campaign Committee.
   It carries risks. Controlling Congress, Democrats also control
many of the perks, projects and federal favors that members of
Congress seek for their districts and their constituents. Those are
vital ingredients in the local side of a campaign for Congress. They
can be punishing weapons _ a House member needs to be able to
deliver for the voters back home.
   Former Speaker of the House Thomas P. O'Neill Jr., an old
Gingrich foe, always counseled that all politics is local. Gingrich
and company are on the opposite track, contending that the House can
be won back on the strength of national Republican issues.
   The proof, if there is any, will be a long time coming, with an
84-seat Democratic margin which actually widened by three seats
while Republicans were winning the presidency in 1988. The White
House party usually loses House seats in off-year elections like
those coming in 1990.
   Time and again during their minority decades, House Republicans
have looked to new leaders to change their lot. Rep. Charles A.
Halleck of Indiana ousted Rep. Joseph W. Martin Jr. as minority
leader in 1959, saying he offered new, vigorous leadership. Six
years later, in another uprising, Rep. Gerald R. Ford of Michigan
was elected leader, saying the party wanted new leadership, a new
image and positive programs to counter the Democrats. When Michel
was promoted from whip to leader in 1980, he said ``We're going to
take the offensive.''
   Now Gingrich says he'll do all that and more from the No. 2 job,
although he obviously has his eye on the leadership.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, March 26</NOTE>
