<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessMirror Bjt   03-23 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Bjt,0628</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Inflation Control, Another Import From Japan? ^By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the producer price index showed a big
increase the other day it was as if a million Americans had shouted
``fire.''
   Among those millions were investors, whose nervous systems had
been imprinted by years of inflation fears. Believing inflation is
ruinous for stocks, they nearly proved the thesis, knocking the
averages for a loop.
   Economists, many of whom had been waiting at least two years for
the inflation event, having prematurely forecast its onset, took
bows and sent overnight letters to their clients saying, ``I told
you so.''
   The media joined in the excitement, dutifully finding ``experts''
who could identify the causes of the inflation problem and explain
what damage might be expected _ that is, a recession, rising
unemployment and the like.
   Then the consumer price index was released.
   The numbers in this report were much lower or, as some headlines
stated, ``more modest'' than the bawdy producer prices. The
president said he was encouraged. An economist declared the
inflation numbers had returned to sanity.
   The departure from sanity was of course not in the brainless
numbers but in the interpretation by humans. And what that
interpretation showed is that when you expect inflation, almost any
sign is an inflation sign.
   Americans have been under great stress for at least two years
now, reminded almost daily that an expansion that lasts 77 months,
as this one has, is destined to be consumed at almost any time by
the fires of inflation.
   The explanations:
   You cannot work your production facilities at the very high rate
of 85 percent of capacity without adding to prices, because
increasingly you are bringing onto line the least efficient plants
and equipment.
   And you cannot drop the jobless rate to near 5 percent without
dipping into a labor pool of inexperienced and inefficient, and
therefore costly and unproductive, workers. Moreover, with labor in
short supply, wages must rise.
   Is that so? It might be. It might not.
   So many inflation-recession theories have been expounded that one
has to question them all. Most of them can be logically presented.
Many of them have merit, but a good many of them also leave
something unexplained.
   If the most popular explanation is correct _ the one that says
inflation is growing because of stress on job markets and plant
capacity _ how do you explain the Japanese experience?
   Japan's unemployment rate is about half the American rate, which
is somewhere just above 5 percent a year. And Japan's capacity
utilization rate is only a couple of percentage points below the
U.S. rate.
   In addition, its money supply growth rate often has exceeded the
U.S. money growth rate, the high level of which also has been named
as a factor in inflation. And its budget deficit has sometimes been
worse than America's.
   Those four factors _ high plant utilization, low jobless rate,
fast money supply growth and big budget deficits _ are probably the
four most popular explanations for present and future inflation.
   Many of the economists who use these factors to explain U.S.
inflation, and who forecast a recession for Americans this year,
have little to say of the Japanese anomaly. It is, it seems, another
impenetrable Oriental mystery.
   It is true that the Japanese have a high savings rate. And that
those savings help finance larger and more efficient production. And
that the Japanese are hard workers. But there is more to it than
that.
   The explanation could be the most beneficial Japanese import of
all, better than cars, cameras, TVs, VCRs and computers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GAF-Mistrial Bjt   03-23 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GAF-Mistrial, Bjt,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Mistrial Declared in Wall Street Stock Manipulation Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said it will try GAF Corp. and a
top executive for a third time on stock fraud charges despite a
mistrial that defense lawyers called a major setback in the pursuit
of Wall Street corruption.
   ``We still have a great deal of faith in our evidence in this
case,'' U.S. Attorney Benito Romano said Wednesday after a federal
judge declared her second mistrial. ``It's appropriate to try the
case again.''
   The GAF case was the first criminal trial stemming from the
insider trading scandals of the mid-1980s and considered a critical
test of information supplied by jailed stock speculator Ivan F.
Boesky.
   After 12 days and more than 90 hours of deliberations, the jury
of nine women and three men in federal court in Manhattan said they
were hopelessly deadlocked in a three-way split and U.S. District
Judge Mary Johnson Lowe declared the mistrial.
   On Jan. 10 Lowe declared a mistrial after determining prosecutors
unintentionally withheld an expert's report that a key piece of
evidence had been altered.
   GAF, two subsidiaries and Vice Chairman James T. Sherwin were
indicted last July for allegedly trying to boost Union Carbide
Corp.'s stock price in 1986 shortly before selling a large block of
Carbide shares. They also were charged with securities fraud, wire
fraud and conspiracy.
   GAF is a Wayne, N.J.-based chemical and building materials
manufacturer with operations worldwide. Its chairman, Samuel J.
Heyman, was named by prosecutors as an unindicted co-conspirator in
the case.
   Sherwin, 55, of Princeton, N.J., hugged his wife as the mistrial
was announced. Sweating profusely, he told reporters outside the
courtroom, ``My family and I are all just completely exhausted.''
   The government had made GAF its leadoff case in a series of
trials scheduled for this year that hinge on the confessions and
testimony of Wall Street figures who already have admitted
securities law violations.
   Defense lawyers said they would fight any move by the government
to retry the case.
   ``If a jury cannot agree despite 12 days of patient deliberations
I believe it's a waste of resources to continue to try this case,''
lead GAF attorney Arthur T. Liman said.
   Wall Street securities fraud lawyer Stanley Arkin said the
mistrial indicated the government was failing in its attempt to
bring criminal charges in what should be civil cases.
   ``I don't think this case demonstrated any harm,'' he said. ``It
never seemed to me like a criminal case and I don't think it is.''
   Romano denied that the mistrial marked a defeat for the Manhattan
U.S. attorney's office, which has brought charges in more than 50
securities fraud cases since 1983.
   All prior criminal frauds, including pending charges against the
investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., were settled through
plea bargains. Drexel agreed in December to settle securities fraud
charges unrelated to the GAF case by pleading guilty to six felonies
and paying a record $650 million.
   In a separate development, the government on Wednesday obtained
its first conviction in a Drexel-related case as a jury convicted
former Drexel assistant trader Lisa Jones of perjury and obstruction
of justice.
   The government's case against GAF was based largely on the
testimony of Los Angeles broker Boyd L. Jefferies, an admitted felon
expected to play a key role in other securities fraud cases as part
of a plea arrangement with the government.
   The purpose of the alleged stock manipulation was to maximize
GAF's profits from the planned sale of a large block of Union
Carbide stock after a failed takeover of the much larger chemical
concern earlier in 1986.
   Defense lawyers branded Jefferies a crook who had schemed
illegally with Boesky, who paid $100 million to settle insider
trading charges in late 1986. Boesky fingered Jefferies, 58, who
last year agreed to plead guilty to two securities law violations.
   Jefferies' testimony is seen as crucial to separate
Boesky-derived cases against speculator Salim B. Lewis and takeover
specialist Paul Bilzerian.
   On the ninth day of deliberations, the jury reported an 11-1
split but resumed discussions after the judge asked them to
reconsider their positions in the interests of reaching a verdict.
   It was not known whether the lone juror was for acquittal or
conviction, but some jurors clearly changed their minds, leading to
the three-way deadlock.
   GAF and the two subsidiaries faced maximum fines totaling $12
million, or $500,000 on each of eight counts against each of the
three. Sherwin faced 40 years in prison and a fine of up to $2
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-LisaJones Bjt   03-23 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Lisa Jones, Bjt,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Young Drexel Employee Guilty of Perjury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The perjury conviction of a young assistant bond
trader at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. will help the government's
ongoing investigation of the powerful Wall Street investment firm,
prosecutors said.
   A federal jury found Lisa Jones, 26, guilty of perjury and
obstruction of justice Wednesday in a case with links to the
government's most prominent target: multimillionaire Drexel bond
financier Michael Milken.
   Jones, a one-time runaway who climbed to a $100,000-a-year job at
the giant brokerage firm, faces a total of 35 years in jail and a
maximum fine of $1.75 million. Sentencing was set for May 22.
   It was the first trial of a Drexel employee after more than two
years of investigations.
   Defense lawyers alleged that the government overzealously
prosecuted Jones, who was charged with lying to a federal grand jury
about alleged shady stock deals involving Drexel and
Princeton-Newport LP, a now-defunct New Jersey securities firm whose
partners face racketeering charges.
   Jones, who made $117,000 last year and still is on Drexel's
payroll, worked for former Drexel trader Bruce Lee Newberg, one of
the Princeton-Newport defendants, who in turn reported directly to
Milken. Milken has been informed by the government to expect to be
indicted on fraud and racketeering charges.
   U.S. Attorney Benito Romano said the Jones conviction, which did
not involved securities law violations, would nonetheless help
future cases. ``I think perjury convictions help all law enforcement
investigations,'' he said.
   ``I think (this case) is a tragedy because this defendant didn't
or couldn't understand what was required of her and could have
avoided this but didn't,'' Romano added.
   Defense lawyer Brian O'Neill said he would appeal the verdict. He
equated Jones to a ``little person run down by a truck.''
   During the trial, Jones broke down repeatedly on the stand as she
was grilled about her life and the grand jury testimony on her work
as an assistant trader at Drexel's Beverly, Hills, Calif.,
high-yield junk bond department. Her job included placing orders and
writing up trading tickets.
   To help prove their case, prosecutors showed Jones lied about her
age, marital status, birthplace and education.
   Jones told a federal grand jury in January 1988 she didn't recall
any discussions about stock ``parking'' _ when one investor buys
stock for another to conceal its true ownership _ in her contacts
with Princeton-Newport.
   Parking isn't illegal, but the government is seeking to
demonstrate that such deals violate securities laws if conducted
with fraud in mind.
   Prosecutors showed Jones handled transactions in which
Princeton-Newport sold securities to Drexel and repurchased them at
a prearranged price 31 days later. They claim the deals were
designed so Princeton-Newport could retain ownership while claiming
losses for tax purposes.
   The government's star witness in the Jones trial, William Ward
Hale, a former junior trader at Princeton-Newport, testified that he
and Jones parked stocks in 1985 and knew it was illegal.
   The link is considered important. Hale is expected to testify
against Princeton-Newport and possibly Milken about the questionable
trades.
   Jones' lawyer maintained she didn't know what parking was,
couldn't remember every trade she executed during eight years at
Drexel and was bullied by government investigators who knocked on
her door in late 1987 in connection with the Princeton-Newport probe.
   Princeton-Newport defense attorneys said they doubt the Jones
case will have any direct impact on their trial, set for June 5,
other than showcasing Hale as a witness.
   They also chastised the government for its treatment of Jones,
who they said revealed little that would would help make
racketeering charges stick.
   ``For all practical purposes, her credibility has been so
destroyed that it is unlikely she will ever be used as a witness by
either side,'' said Ted Wells, who represents Princeton-Newport
partner James S. Regan. ``She is a tragic figure caught in the
middle.''
   The Jones case has no direct bearing on the government's
settlement with Drexel over complaints stemming from information
supplied by now-imprisoned speculator Ivan Boesky. The firm agreed
to pay $650 million and plead guilty to six felonies to settle
criminal fraud charges.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder said the firm had not decided
whether Jones will be fired. She was on a paid leave of absence from
Drexel, which paid her legal fees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AgingAircraft Bjt   03-23 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aging Aircraft, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Industry Engineers Say Humans Most Important Safety Factor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto DN8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eyes, not instruments, are the best detectors of
airplane structural problems, according to members of a task force
trying to determine how to ensure the safety of the nation's aging
aircraft fleet.
   ``The most important thing you can do today is to be around an
airplane and be alert,'' said Ben Cosgrove, engineering vice
president of Boeing Co., whose planes have been involved in some
widely publicized incidents involving structural failure.
   ``Eighty percent of all damage is found by eyeballs,'' he said.
   Cosgrove, and other members of the task force formed by the Air
Transport Association spoke Wednesday at an aircraft maintenance and
ground support trade show in Dallas.
   The task force was formed last year after a section of fuselage
ripped off a 19-year-old Aloha Airlines Boeing 737 over Hawaii. A
flight attendant was killed and 61 people were injured in the
incident, which focused public attention on the increasing age of
the nation's airplanes.
   There have been several other highly publicized incidents
recently, the most serious also occuring over Hawaii and involving a
Boeing plane.
   Last month, a section of the fuselage of a United Airlines Boeing
747 tore off just after the plane left Hawaii. Nine people died when
they were sucked out of the airliner.
   ``Current economic and market conditions have resulted in the use
of airplanes beyond their original economic design goal,'' said
Clyde Kizer, engineering and maintenance vice president of the Air
Transport Association.
   While the public has become aware of the age of the planes,
estimated to average 12.7 years, the United executive who chaired
the task force said age alone has little to do with an airplane's
airworthiness.
   The number of flights, the environment in which the planes
operate, and the attention paid to regular maintenance are more
important factors, said Bob Doll, United's vice president for
technical services.
   ``I don't see why there would be'' a limit to the operational age
of an aircraft, providing it is properly maintained, he said.
   Boeing's Cosgrove said the company has inspected 20-year-old
aircraft that look as if they just rolled off the assembly line, and
other, much younger aircraft in much worse shape.
   ``It's really down to the guts of an airline's organization,''
Cosgrove said. ``Inspection and maintainence of an aircraft, whether
it is one year or 20 years old, is important.''
   Whether closer visual inspection would have averted the Aloha
disaster is unclear, indicated Joseph Trippe Nall, the National
Transportation Safety Board member who is leading the investigation.
   Nall, in a separate speech Wednesday, said investigators found
stress fractures around screw holes near the damaged area of the
Boeing's fuselage.
   As a result, the NTSB _ although not ready to release its full
findings _ already has recommended some screw holes be redesigned on
the 737s to change their stress point.
   Nall said the NTSB's Aloha findings likely will be released May 9
when the board has its next regular meeting.
   Meanwhile, Doll said the task force was concerned about the
varied levels of maintenance practices it found throughout the
industry.
   Although he defended United's inspectors, Doll said the task
force was working on how to raise expertise industrywide.
   Doll balked at one questioner's suggestion that it would be
better to replace old aircraft rather than update them.
   ``If we pay $130 million (for a new plane) every time the
ashtrays get dirty, you're not going to be able to afford the
ticket,'' he said.
   Industry experts estimate that only about 15 jetliners have been
scrapped voluntarily by the airlines during the last decade.
   In the meantime, airlines are rapidly buying planes, but Doll
noted that most of the planes are being used for expansion and not
replacement of older aircraft.
   The NTSB's Nall stressed that training and following regulations
are the best ways to keep airplanes safe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
