<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Boeing Bjt   03-23 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Day Of Good News For Boeing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co., which has spent much of its time
lately fielding questions about aircraft quality, has plenty of good
news for a change: two major new aircraft orders and prospects of
record employment.
   American Airlines announced in New York Wednesday it was ordering
35 Boeing jetliners, along with up to 150 Fokker-100 short-haul
jets. Boeing's share of that order is worth an estimated $1.8
billion to $2.1 billion.
   Meanwhile, Boeing Canada's de Havilland Division said it received
its largest order ever, a $425 million deal from GPA Jetprop Ltd.
for 38 Dash 8 Series 300 turboprop planes.
   And Tuesday, Boeing said it planned to add 2,300 employees in the
first half of 1989, with mid-year employment in Washington state
reaching a company-record 102,000.
   Boeing currently employs 99,700 people in the state and 155,000
worldwide.
   The company has endured a rash of bad news recently, including
reports of miswiring in some jets, delays in its new 747-400 jumbo
jet, questions about the safety of older aircraft, and a series of
crashes and mishaps involving Boeing aircraft.
   But the tone at Boeing Commercial Airplanes was distinctively
upbeat Wednesday.
   ``I think that would be fair to say,'' chuckled spokesman Craig
Martin when asked if the company was heartened by the American order.
   So far this year, Boeing has announced orders for 102 jetliners
worth more than $8.2 billion. If that pace continued through 1989,
Boeing could set a record for order value for the fifth straight
year, breaking last year's mark of $29.7 billion. Boeing had orders
for 636 jets in 1988, an industry record.
   American ordered 25 Boeing 757-200s and 10 767-300ER aircraft,
bringing American's total orders of those aircraft to 85 firm and 85
options.
   Martin said a mid-sized 757 sells for $46 million to $52 million,
depending on configuration, while the wide-body, extended-range
767-300ER is priced at $72 million to $78 million. At those prices,
the Boeing share of American's order would be worth between $1.87
billion and $2.08 billion.
   ``American's been a good customer _ they are a good customer,''
Martin said. ``To see them buying what we call the 757-767 family is
very encouraging. It's another indication that last year's surge in
757 sales will continue.''
   Last May 26, American ordered 50 757s, valued at about $2
billion, and took options on 50 more. The next day, United Airlines
ordered 30 of the planes, worth about $1.3 billion and optioned the
same number. Those orders were seen as a strong vote of confidence
for the 757, a fuel-efficient, quiet aircraft that had been a slow
seller since its introduction in the early 1980s.
   To date, Boeing has announced orders for 447 757s and 372 767s.
   GPA Jetprop, a partnership between GPA Group Ltd. of Shannon,
Ireland, and PWA Corp. of Calgary, Alberta, is a major lessor of
turboprop aircraft. Tom Appleton, de Havilland vice president for
marketing and sales, said its order is probably the largest ever for
a single model of turboprop airliner.
   ``This order transforms us to a central role in the turboprop
acquisition business,'' said Naill Greene, GPA Jetprop managing
director. ``We have gone from being a boutique to being a department
store.''
   The twin-engine Dash 8 Series 300 carries 50 to 56 passengers and
is used primarily on commuter routes.
   With GPA Jetprop's order, de Havilland has firm orders and
options for 86 of the aircraft, valued at more than $1 billion. For
the entire Dash 8 family, de Havilland now has orders and options
for 297 aircraft from 34 customers.
   GPA Jetprop earlier ordered nine Dash 8 Series 100 aircraft,
which carry 37 to 40 passengers, and took options on another five.
   Boeing has been hiring about 900 workers per month, with
employment expected to level off by mid-1989. Most of the new hires
will be at Boeing's Everett, Wash. widebody jet plant, where the
company is hustling to get deliveries of the 747-400 back on
schedule, company spokesman Paul Binder said.
   In 1988, Boeing's total employment rose by nearly 11,000, or 7.7
percent, to 153,000. The company is predicting job growth will be at
about 5 percent this year.
   ``It's slowing somewhat, but if you look at the level of economic
activity generated by Boeing right now, it's just extraordinary,''
said Douglas Pedersen, vice president and economist with Security
Pacific Bank Washington.
</TEXT>
