<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GoldFields     03-23 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gold Fields,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Appeals Court Upholds Block to Consolidated Gold Fields Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has upheld a preliminary
injunction blocking Minorco SA's $5.7 billion hostile bid for
Consolidated Gold Fields PLC on antitrust grounds.
   A three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals also
said Wednesday Minorco's bid should be sent back to a lower court
for consideration of whether it violates U.S. securities laws.
   Minorco, which is largely controlled by two South African
corporations, Anglo American Corp. of South Africa and De Beers
Consolidated Mines Ltd., launched its bid for Gold Fields, a British
firm, last fall. Minorco, a Luxembourg corporation, already held
nearly 30 percent of Gold Fields' stock.
   Gold Fields has resisted the bid in Britain, and also filed an
antitrust action here.
   Minorco ``is the largest producer of gold in the non-communist
world, accounting for 20.3 percent of all gold production in the
western world,'' according to court papers.
   Gold Fields, meanwhile, has significant gold mining holdings in
South Africa, Australia and the United States, including 90 percent
of Newmont Gold, the largest gold producer in the country.
   Gold Fields ``accounts for 12 percent of the western world's gold
production, making it the second-largest gold producer in the
non-communist world,'' according to court papers.
   The company's Newmont subsidiary claimed that because it costs
less to mine and produce gold in South Africa than in America,
Minorco eventually would shut down U.S. operations if the takeover
was accomplished.
   ``Newmont's claim is that its ability to compete in the
marketplace will be reduced by anti-competitive influence, exercised
from inside its own boardroom'' if the Minorco bid succeeded, wrote
Circuit Judge Jon O. Newman in the 2nd Circuit's 25-page opinion.
   ``Newmont's threatened injury is precisely the type that the
antitrust laws were designed to protect against,'' the court said in
a 2-to-1 decision upholding an injunction imposed by U.S. District
Judge Michael Mukasey.
   Late last year, Mukasey issued a preliminary injunction
preventing Minorco, Anglo American and DeBeers from proceeding with
their tender offer until the antitrust issue was resolved in the
courts.
   Just before Mukasey's ruling, the Minorco bid was referred to
Britain's Monopolies and Mergers Commission for investigation of
possible anti-competitive consequences in the United Kingdom on such
strategic metals as titanium and zircon.
   British law prohibited further action on the takeover bid until
Feb. 2 when the commission found that the acquisition of Gold Fields
would not operate against the British public interest, the 2nd
Circuit opinion noted.
   With that ruling, Mukasey's injunction remained the only legal
obstacle to Minorco's offer. Minorco said it would nopt buy any new
shares unless the injunction was lifted or modified.
   In seeking the injunction, Gold Fields also claimed Minorco
violated the anti-fraud provisions of U.S. securities laws, for
allegedly making and false and misleading statements about how much
control South African corporations and individuals have over it.
   Gold Fields claimed the Oppenheimer family of South Africa
indirectly controls Minorco, Anglo American and DeBeers and that the
stigma of South Africa's apartheid racial policy could make it
difficult to conduct business in some countries.
   The appeals court sent the case back to U.S. District Court for
further consideration of the fraud issue.
   In his decision, Mukasey claimed he lacked jurisdiction in
rejecting a Gold Fields claim that its U.S. investors entitled the
concern to sue in U.S. courts alleging violations of federal
securities law.
   About 2.5 percent of Gold Fields' outstanding shares are held by
U.S. citizens.
   But the 2nd Circuit panel, said ``the tender offer had sufficient
effects within the United States to warrant application of American
securities laws.''
</TEXT>
