<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 0256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OrganicApples Bjt   03-23 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Organic Apples, Bjt,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Growers Eyeing Organic Crop Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alarmed by slumping prices from the Alar
scare, and dazzled by skyrocketing prices for chemical-free fruit,
many Washington apple growers are rushing into experiments with
organic farming.
   The interest is motivated more by economics _ primarily the 300
percent higher prices for organic apples _ than philosophy.
   ``I've had more calls in the past two or three weeks about
growing fruit organically than in the past three years,'' said
Brooke Peterson, the Washington State University tree fruit
extension agent for Yakima County.
   ``Organic growing in the past was a philosophical question,''
Peterson said. ``Today it's economic. There are higher prices for
it.''
   Washington produces half the nation's apples, and the 5,000
growers of the $312 million crop are unlikely to switch more than a
small percentage of the orchards to chemical-free growing.
   But rising consumer interest is creating a niche market many want
to tap.
   At meetings in the apple belt communities of Okanogan, Wenatchee
and Yakima this week, Pacific Fruit Growers-Packers, Inc. will
discuss organic techniques with hundreds of growers.
   ``I think that organic farming is essentially another (apple)
variety for us,'' said Greg McPherson, an assistant general manager
for Pacific Fruit and also a grower. ``There's definitely a market.''
   In the wake of the nationwide Alar scare, prices for organically
grown Washington apples have doubled to $48 per box. Prices for the
top grade of commercially grown Red Delicious apples, in contrast,
slumped another $1 this week to between $11 and $12 per 42-pound
box, barely above the break-even point and $2 to $3 less than before
the Alar scare.
   Diane Dempster, of Charlie's Produce in Seattle, which markets
organic fruit, said the gap between organic and standard apples is
not usually so great.
   ``Normally its 20 to 50 percent higher (for organic),'' she said.
``It's partly the Alar scare and a real increased demand.''
   Organic growing has received a lot of attention in recent weeks,
after a Natural Resources Defense Council report on pesticides in
children's food said eating apples treated with Alar increased
cancer risks in children.
   The industry disputes the findings and the federal government has
reassured consumers that apples are safe to eat.
   But a Louis Harris poll released this week found that 84.2
percent of those surveyed would choose organically grown food if
given a choice.
   Washington, Minnesota and Texas are the only states that have
organic certification programs, where farmers attest they have not
used synthetic fertilizers or pesticides.
   Only about 20 of the state's 5,000 apple growers are currently
certified as organic growers, according to Miles McEvoy of the state
Department of Agriculture.
   And a recent survey in Seattle found that only 1 percent of the
produce is organically grown, he said.
   To be certified in Washington, a grower must not have used
artificial chemicals for two years, he said.
   ``We're seeing a lot of apple growers interested,'' said McEvoy,
who runs the certification program.
   However, many growers contend it is impossible for the entire
apple-growing industry to switch to organic techniques.
   A major reason is that the codling moth would devastate virtually
the entire crop, infesting it with worms, Peterson said.
   But Washington growers are considering experimenting with a
variety of techniques.
   McPherson said he plans to hide 12 acres of organically-grown
apples in the middle of his orchards, surrounded by 48 acres of
chemically-treated apples.
   The pests normally stop at the first available tree to lay their
eggs, and he hopes that surrounding the vulnerable chemical-free
trees with a ring of sprayed trees will keep the moth away.
   There are other techniques being developed to handle the codling
moth without artificial chemicals, McEvoy said.
   But, he added, ``Apples are by far the hardest thing to grow
organically in the state.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
