<FIRST>r f PM-MCorpOffer     03-23 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MCorp Offer,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: First City Interested in MCorp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Houston bank holding company that was saved with
the help of federal regulators last year is now bidding to acquire
troubled MCorp, a newspaper reported today.
   The Dallas Morning News, quoting anonymous industry sources, said
First City Bancorporation of Texas Inc. chairman A. Robert Abbout
has approached federal regulators about bidding to acquire
Dallas-based MCorp.
   Abboud is working on a bid with the New York investment firm,
Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Inc., which helped raise the $500
million last April that allowed him take over Houston-based First
City. That deal included $1 billion in FDIC aid.
   Donaldson Lufkin officials could not be reached for comment
Wednesday. A First City spokesman told The News he could neither
confirm nor deny any interest in MCorp by Abboud.
   Combining First City, with $11 billion in assets, and MCorp, an
$18.8 billion institution, would raise a host of issues for the
government, particularly because of terms of the previous deal with
First City.
   That transaction gives the FDIC a stake in the company's ability
to collect on its bad loans. The FDIC will recoup some of its
investment based on the collections on soured loans made under the
previous First City management.
   A number of observers speculated that Abboud would consider a bid
for MCorp only if federal regulators first declared the company's
banks insolvent, avoiding the process he endured in taking over
First City.
   MCorp's most troubled banks include MBank Dallas and MBank
Houston, two of its largest susidiaries. The Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. reported that nearly a third of MCorp's banks had
exhausted their equity capital by the end of 1988, leaving them
virtually insolvent and opening the door for regulators to seize
assets.
   FDIC figures show that seven MBanks around Texas, including four
of the company's seven largest banks, reported negative equity _
exhausting shareholder funds _ at the end of 1988; representing
$11.8 billion of MCorp's $18.8 billion asset base.
   MCorp's chairman, Gene H. Bishop, has indicated he wants the
company to remain independent. He said last October that the company
could raise new capital to combine with FDIC aid, which analysts
have estimated would exceed $1 billion.
   The government said in November that it would consider
management's proposal while seeking other bids. Few suitors have
surfaced, partly because of complications that might arise in trying
to buy the company's banks without the cooperation of Bishop.
   MCorp's management also has retained about $400 million in cash
and other assets in the holding company. Bishop has indicated that
money may be available for helping the company's banks only as part
of a management-blessed reorganization.
</TEXT>
