<SECOND>BC-Westin Hotels,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Westin Hotels Names New CEO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chieko N. Aoki has been named chief executive
officer and deputy chairman of Westin Hotels and Resorts, the
Seattle-based chain of 64 international luxury hotels.
   Mrs. Aoki succeeds Harry Mullikin, 62, who retired Wednesday
after serving as chairman and CEO of the company for 12 years.
Mullikin had been with Westin for 48 years.
   Mrs. Aoki's husband, John, succeeds Mullikin as chairman.
   Mrs. Aoki was vice-chairman of Westin since 1988, when it was
purchased by the Aoki Corp. Mr. Aoki is president and CEO of Aoki
Corp., a Japanese construction conglomerate. Aoki owns seven hotels
that are not part of the Westin chain.
   Mrs. Aoki said Westin, founded in 1930, plans to double its
number of hotels in domestic and international markets, focusing on
international gateway cities. Projects are being planned in
California, Sao Paulo, Shanghai, Lisbon, Tokyo and Osaka.
   Mullikin will remain as chairman emeritus and senior advisor to
the Aokis.
