<FIRST>r f PM-Japan-USConstruction     03-23 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US Construction,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turner, Largest U.S. Builder, Wins Contract In Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States' largest building contractor said
Thursday it isn't strongly interested in the Japanese market,
despite receiving one of the first private contracts to go to a U.S.
firm since an agreement to open Japan's construction market was
reached last May.
   The Turner Corp. signed a contract Thursday to team up with
Kumagai Gumi, one of Japan's biggest construction firms, in an 11.2
billion yen, the equivalent of about $85 million, construction
project in Tokyo for Japan's Shuwa Corp.
   Shuwa, one of the largest Japanese holders of American real
estate, owns 37 buildings in the United States, including Atlantic
Richfield Plaza in Los Angeles and the ABC Building in New York.
   The companies said Turner's portion of the joint venture would be
10 percent. Kumagai Gumi and Turner agreed last summer to cooperate
in construction projects in the two countries, and are jointly
involved in three projects in New York.
   U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher welcomed Thursday's
contract as a ``fine example'' of private Japanese industry honoring
the spirit of last May's bilateral construction agreement, in which
Japan agreed to give U.S. companies access to a range of public
works projects.
   ``Most significant is that this private-sector project is outside
of that accord, but reflects most clearly our goal that American
companies be given the opportunity to introduce their expertise and
experience to all sectors of the Japanese market,'' Mosbacher said
in a statement.
   ``I want to make a small contribution to alleviating trade
friction,'' Shuwa President Shigeru Kobayashi told a news conference
after the signing. ``Instead of arguing and negotiating, the two
sides should promote more joint activities.''
   U.S. officials have charged that Japanese bidding practices and
other industry customs have blocked foreign entry into the Japanese
construction market. Japanese builders have denied that foreigners
are excluded, and say U.S. construction firms showed little interest
in Japan before the bilateral pact.
   ``I don't think the customs would prevent us,'' Turner Senior
Vice President Ralph Beck said after the contract signing. ``From
our perspective, the Japanese government and certainly Shuwa have
been providing the opportunities.''
   Beck said his company was more interested in increasing its
business in the United States and other countries through the Shuwa
venture than in increasing its access to the Japanese market.
   ``It doesn't make a lot of sense to beat your head against the
wall ... unless there's something that you can bring to the table
that's different than what the very capable industry can deliver
over here,'' he said.
   ``The world's a very big place ... and at the moment there are
more than enough opportunities in the world with better prospects
where we can bring something to the table.''
   Beck discounted what he described as ``paranoia'' in the United
States about an erosion of market share for U.S. contractors
resulting from the arrival of Japanese developers.
   ``The Japanese have brought building opportunities to the United
States which probably wouldn't have been there because there wasn't
anybody to invest in those projects,'' he said.
   Earlier this month, Tishman Realty and Construction Co. Inc.
announced it was forming a joint venture with Japan's Aoki Corp. to
build a luxury hotel in Osaka in what it said was the first private
construction agreement by a U.S. company following the bilateral
pact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
