<FIRST>r f PM-SunElectric-SOQ     03-23 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sun Electric-SOQ,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle For Control Of Sun Electric Escalates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRYSTAL LAKE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partnership seeking to acquire Sun
Electric Corp. is suing the company, claiming management is unfairly
hindering its efforts to wage a proxy fight for control of the firm.
   SOQ Partners, a Delaware limited partnership, announced Wednesday
that it had filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Wilmington,
Del., charging that Sun Electric was illegally soliciting proxies
for its April 11 annual meeting.
   The move comes one day after the Crystal Lake, Ill.-based auto
equipment manufacturer announced it was seeking a rescuer or buyer
to save it from the takeover bid by SOQ, its largest shareholder.
   Sun Electric said it has asked its investment banking firm,
Salomon Brothers, to explore ``finding a strategic partner for Sun,
a merger or an orderly sale of part or all of the company.''
   At the same time, the company said its board had rejected SOQ's
demand that Sun Electric be put up for immediate auction or face a
proxy fight.
   SOQ, led by Connecticut-based investor John C. Page, owns about
12 percent of Sun Electric.
   In its lawsuit, SOQ also charged that Sun Electric's board had
adopted a ``secret bylaw'' aimed at preventing SOQ from waging a
proxy fight. The lawsuit seeks an order invalidating proxies
obtained by Sun Electric's management.
   SOQ said its lawsuit was a response to a U.S. District Court
lawsuit filed in Delaware by Sun Electric, charging SOQ with giving
false information to the Securities and Exchange Commission
regarding its motives for buying Sun Electric stock.
   The general partners of SOQ Partners are CJP Management Inc., a
corporation controlled by Page; the Weinress Group, a corporation
controlled by Stephen D. Weinress, and Campbell Lutyens Inc., a
corporation of which Richard D. Lutyens is president.
   In a separate lawsuit filed in Delaware Chancery Court, SOQ is
seeking an order invalidating the alleged ``secret bylaw.''
   Sun Electric spokeswoman Sharon Evey said in a telephone
interview that the firm's lawyers ``feel the allegations are
groundless.''
   Sun Electric's stock price surged $2.12{ to $17.50 Wednesday on
the New York Stock Exchange in reaction to the latest development in
the takeover battle.
   Sun Electric manufactures diagnostic, test and service equipment
for automobile mechanics and manufacturers. The company also markets
service-station management systems for the retail petroleum industry.
   Sun Electric reported a net loss of $4.2 million on sales of $190
million in 1988.
   Of SOQ's general partners, Page controls CJP Management Inc.,
which is involved in the distribution of automotive and hydraulic
products; Weinress controls the Weinress Group Inc. and is the
marketing director of L.H. Friend, Weinress Frankson Inc., a Los
Angeles-based brokerage and investment-advisory firm; Lutyens is
president of Campbell Lutyens Inc., the U.S. arm of Campbell Lutyens
&amp; Co. Ltd., a London-based merchant banking and investment-advisory
firm.
</TEXT>
