<FIRST>r f BC-Centel-Cable     03-23 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Centel-Cable,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centel Sells Illinois, Central Florida Cable Units</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centel Corp. said Thursday it agreed to sell its
cable TV operations in Illinois and central Florida, and news of
deals involving four other cable units could come in a few days.
   The Chicago-based company did not disclose the sale prices of the
Centel Cable Television Co. properties but said it expects the gross
proceeds from all six sales to total more than $1.4 billion.
   Centel said it would sell its central Florida cable operation,
which has 97,000 subscribers, to American Television and
Communications Corp. of Stamford, Conn., and sell its Illinois cable
business, with 122,000 subscribers, to Jones Intercable Inc. of
Englewood, Colo.
   American Television, which is an 82-percent owned subsidiary of
Time Inc., is the nation's second largest cable operator serving
more than 4 million television homes in 32 states.
   The deal will give Jones Intercable and its affiliates systems
with about 1.3 million subscribers.
   The sales, which Centel expects to complete in the third quarter,
leave the company with cable operations in southeastern Florida,
Kentucky, Michigan and Ohio.
   Centel announced in late November that it would sell its cable
television company, the nation's 22nd largest, so it could
concentrate on its telecommunications businesses, which include
local telephone service in nine states and a cellular telephone
subsidiary that operates in 13 states.
</TEXT>
