<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Tyson-HollyFarms     03-23 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tyson-Holly Farms,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Board Rejects Tyson's $63.50-A-Share Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge in Delaware has ruled that an offer
from Tyson Foods Inc. of Springdale to buy out the Holly Farms Corp.
of Memphis, Tenn., is better than a rival offer from ConAgra of
Omaha, Neb.
   But Vice Chancellor Maurice Hartnett's 29-page decision Wednesday
left it up to Holly Farms stockholders to choose between the Tyson
and ConAgra offers. Hartnett said shareholders would probably reject
the proposed merger agreement from ConAgra.
   Today, Holly Farms announced that its board had decided to reject
Tyson's offer of $63.50 per share and to recommend that stockholders
not tender their shares pursuant to that offer. The board met
Wednesday.
   Last week, Tyson increased its offer to acquire Holly Farms stock
from $60 a share to $63.50 a share in a deal worth about $1.18
billion. ConAgra has offered a stock swap deal worth between $1.09
billion and $1.17 billion. But Don Tyson, chairman and chief
executive officer of Tyson, says his company's offer is worth much
more.
   Hartnett's ruling came in a suit by Tyson asking that the judge
stop a scheduled April 14 vote by Holly Farms shareholders on the
merger. The judge allowed the vote to proceed.
   Should shareholders approve the merger, Hartnett said he wouldn't
allow the agreement to go through until he makes a decision on a
so-called ``crown jewel lockup'' provision worked into the merger.
   The provision would give ConAgra an option to buy prime assets
from Holly Farms if the merger fell through. The provision is
intended to make an acquisition by Tyson diffcult.
   Hartnett said the provision was tainted and probably
unenforceable.
   The Holly Farms board said in a news release today that by
continuuing to condition its tender offer on the invalidity of the
lockup agreement, ``Tyson had failed to provide the board with the
necessary assurance that Tyson would complete an acquisition of
Holly Farms on a timely basis, if at all.
   ``Unless and until Tyson removes from its tender offer the Asset
Option condition,'' a Holly Farms spokesman said in the release.
``Holly Farms' stockholders can have no assurance that Tyson's
$63.50 price represents deliverable value. For this reason,
ConAgra's merger agreement still represents, in the board's view,
the best alternative for our stockholders.''
   Tyson Foods has hired a New York firm to help it sway Holly Farms
stockholders in its direction. But the board of Holly Farms, which
has said it prefers the offer from ConAgra, has also hired a New
York firm in an effort to keep its stockholders in the ConAgra camp.
   The management of Holly Farms needs two-thirds of its
shareholders of record to vote April 14 to approved its merger with
ConAgra.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
