<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DiamondPrices     03-23 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diamond Prices,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>De Beers Raises Prices 15.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The De Beers diamond cartel of South Africa, citing
strong demand, says it is increasing prices for rough gemstones an
average 15.5 percent.
   The price increase for a broad range of uncut diamonds, announced
Tuesday, is effective next week. It follows a 13.5 percent increase
last May and a 10 percent increase in September 1987.
   De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd., which is based in Johannesburg,
controls 80 percent of the world's rough diamond market through its
London-based marketing arm, Central Selling Organization.
   It does not disclose what the prices are.
   The cartel only sets prices for rough diamonds, which it doesn't
disclose, and operates a pipeline of diamonds from its mines in
South Africa and Australia to dealers and cutters in the world's
major diamond cutting centers, Antwerp, Bombay, New York and Tel
Aviv.
   It holds about 10 ``sights'' _ or sales _ for international
diamond dealers a year, with the next one scheduled for next week.
   ``We are responding to prevailing conditions in the market. It
was market-led,'' spokesman Richard Dickson said Thursday about the
price increase.
   Demand for rough diamonds of two carats and less is especially
strong, he said.
   ``The industry is anticipating another good year in 1989 from
retail diamond and jewelry sales,'' Dickson said.
   The generally weaker dollar has helped sales because diamonds are
priced in dollars and holders of Japanese yen and European
currencies get more for their money.
   In addition, sales should improve in Japan after April 1 when a
15 percent tax in Britain on luxury items costing about $300 or more
is replaced with a flat 3 percent sales tax on all items, Dickson
said.
   The markets in Israel and India are particularly strong, with
good advances also in New York and Belgium, he said.
   ``We are bringing rough prices up in line with those prices of
polished diamonds that are prevailing within the diamond cutting
centers,'' he said.
   The organization had record sales of $4.2 billion in 1988, up 37
percent from $3.08 billion in 1987, the previous record.
   Most of the world's diamonds are industrial diamonds, used
primarily in drilling. Between 10 percent and 20 percent are gems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890323-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Liman Adv26   03-23 1150</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Liman, Adv 26,1185</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, March 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Attica To Iran-Contra To Wall Street: Arthur Liman's Career</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur L. Liman, a gangly disheveled man with a
Noo Yawk accent, probably is best known for picking apart Oliver
North on national television as captive nation watched.
   ``Oliver North, isn't it a fact...,'' Liman prefaced each
question to the deposed Marine lieutenant colonel during the
congressional Iran-Contra hearings that made Liman's baggy face and
half-moon ears a household image.
   His simple, direct, persistent style pierced the veil around the
man President Reagan called a ``national hero'' and earned Liman, an
outsider in Washington, the admiration of fellow Democrats and
Republicans alike, as well as bags of hate mail.
   ``It was like Shakespeare,'' said Sen. Warren Rudman, the New
Hampshire Republican who was vice chairman of the Senate committee
Liman served as general counsel two years ago. ``The guy is good.''
   The guy is back in his native New York, returned to the highest
(and highest-paid) echelons of the city's legal community and to the
almost notoriety-free existence he prefers after a summer when every
Washington cabbie knew him by name.
   Liman's career has taken him from investigating the Attica prison
riots, to defending the likes of John Zaccaro and Robert Vesco, to
boardroom negotiating at CBS, to grilling Oliver North.
   At 56, Liman declines specialties, though he is considered a
brilliant trial attorney and the city's most prominent securities
fraud lawyer in a decade permeated with Wall Street crime.
   Liman most recently was lead defense attorney in a major stock
manipulation case against GAF Corp. He also represents Michael
Milken, the Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s financier who expects to
be indicted for fraud and racketeering.
   ``I am not a specialist in criminal securities fraud cases,''
Liman said in an interview during the exhausting 12-day
deliberations in the GAF case, which ended March 22 in a second
mistrial. ``I've always believed that a trial lawyer should be able
to try any kind of case. I have avoided narrow specialization.''
   A sampling of Liman's clients over the last few years
demonstrates the versatility his peers respect.
   On the corporate side, he represented Pennzoil Co. against Texaco
Inc. in 1985 and even delivered testimony on the witness stand that
helped send Texaco into bankruptcy court. Time Inc. and Warner
Communications Inc. are clients _ the two, not coincidentally, just
announced a massive merger.
   In 1986, Liman negotiated a handshake between clients Laurence
Tisch and William Paley that led to the ouster of CBS Inc.'s Chief
Executive Officer Thomas Wyman.
   In the public domain, Liman supervised Richard Nixon's disbarment
and probed allegations of wrongdoing in New York City's medical
examiner's office.
   His clients aren't all saints. In addition to Milken and insider
trader Dennis Levine, Liman has represented Zaccaro, the real estate
mogul and husband of former vice presidential candidate Geraldine
Ferraro, and Vesco, the fugitive businessman.
   ``He's negotiating this case now and he could be negotitating a
takeover deal tomorrow,'' said Robert Fiske, a New York lawyer and
former U.S. attorney who has known Liman 20 years. ``He's extremely
versatile. He handles an enormous variety of cases.''
   Born in Queens, Liman joined the New York law firm of Paul Weiss
Rifkind Wharton &amp; Garrison in 1957 after finishing first in his
class at Yale Law School. But he cut his teeth on white-collar crime
during a 2{-year stay at the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan
under Robert Morgenthau starting in 1961.
   ``I had never worked on a securities case because there really
weren't any,'' Liman said. ``We were breaking new ground.''
   He recalled himself as the office ``garbage pail,'' taking small
cases colleagues shunned. Liman once won a conviction of a bartender
for diluting liquor but got just a $1 fine _ the Irish judge had a
bartender father.
   In 1971, Morgenthau appointed Liman, who had since returned to
Paul Weiss, as special prosecutor to investigate the Attica prison
riots in upstate New York. It was the first probe inside a prison,
and Liman's team interviewed every inmate. His report was nominated
for a National Book Award.
   The Attica hearings were televised, but Liman said they formed an
almost polar contrast to the turbulent and politically charged
Iran-Contra proceedings, during which Liman received at least two
serious threats for his perceived attacks on North.
   ``I knew the hearings were going to be televised but it never
occurred to me they would become such an object of media
attention,'' he said. ``Nor did I really anticipate there was going
to be this wholesale stripping away of my privacy.
   ``All of a sudden we were receiving 100,000 hate letters and a
few fan letters. ... Whenever somebody is very public in this
country it brings out the crazies.''
   With North now on trial in Washington, Liman recalls the hearings
as an exercise in unearthing evidence, not bringing anyone to
justice. The philosophy of the mission, he said, quoting the late
Supreme Court Justice Louis D. Brandeis, was that ``sunlight is the
best disinfectant in a democracy.''
   ``There are some events in American history where it's most
important for the American people to understand how it happened and
why it happened,'' Liman said.
   ``When I went down to Washington on the job there was a rumor a
day on what happened. What people forget is these hearings dispelled
so much of that. If we weren't able to find out everything that
happened we were able to find out much and let the American people
judge.
   ``I told the committee when I took the job that I could never
determine for them what the real truth was _ because too many
documents had been shredded and we'd have to rely on credibility.''
   Liman talks to judges and juries and Oliver Norths in the same
paced, deferential, just-folks manner. Facing the bench, hands in
his pockets, he exposes drooping shirttails behind a tapered suit.
   ``I think juries don't go for the dramatic,'' he said. ``I think
they see the things and decide for themselves.''
   Liman also is notoriously absentmindend. He has appeared in court
in mismatched suits. One oft-repeated story has Liman asking his
secretary to call a client. When she reported the man had died of a
heart attack, Liman replied, ``Just have him call me when he gets
in.''
   Said Rudman: ``What is deceptive is Arthur Liman speaks like the
guy next door. But what is driving the verbiage is a computer in his
head. Even Oliver North came away with great respect for Arthur
Liman. He was fair. He never took a cheap shot at anybody in those
hearings.
   ``I don't know what life holds for Arthur. Maybe someday there'll
be a Democratic president. If there is, I hope Arthur Liman ends up
in government.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, March 26</NOTE>
