<FIRST>r f AM-GoldFields-Minorco     03-23 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gold Fields-Minorco,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Court Ruling Threatens to Sink Minorco Offer; Gold Fields Stock
Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Gold Fields PLC shares plummeted
Thursday on speculation that a U.S. court ruling would block Minorco
SA's hostile takeover attempt for the British mining giant for at
least a year.
   The attempted buyout, valued at about $5.5 billion, is Britain's
biggest ever.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New York late Wednesday
upheld a lower court's preliminary injunction barring the South
African-controlled Minorco from buying more than 30 percent of
shares in Gold Fields, which has both U.S. interests and American
shareholders.
   Minorco, which is controlled by the gold and diamond mining
giants Anglo American Corp. and De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd.,
already owns 29.6 percent of its target.
   The appeals court said the proposed takeover likely would violate
U.S. antitrust laws. The court also ruled that the Minorco bid
should go back to a lower court for consideration of whether it
violates U.S. securities laws.
   The court noted that Minorco, through its various holdings, ``is
the largest producer of gold in the non-communist world, accounting
for 20.3 percent of all gold production in the western world,''
while Gold Fields, a British firm, is the free world's
second-largest gold concern.
   Luxembourg-based Minorco now can either appeal the latest ruling
to the U.S. Supreme Court or take the case back to the lower court
for a trial on the antitrust issues.
   But analysts said they saw little chance the U.S. litigation
could be resolved within the time limit allowed for the bid under
British takeover rules.
   Minorco said it was disappointed with the ruling and said it was
``reviewing the court's opinion with its advisers and studying the
options available to it.''
   Gold Fields shares dropped the equivalent of $3.15 a share to
close at $21.50 in active trading on London's Stock Exchange.
Minorco rose 29 cents to $12.90 a share.
   Gold Fields Chairman Rudolph Agnew called the ruling good news
but said ``the implications for the outcome of the bid aren't yet
clear.''
   Under British takeover regulations, Minorco can't extend its bid
beyond April 26 and must control more than 50 percent of Gold
Fields' outstanding shares by then.
   Minorco then would have until May 17 to satisfy or waive all
outstanding conditions on the bid, which offered one new Minorco
share plus $35.26 in cash for every two Gold Fields shares. One of
these conditions is resolution of the U.S. litigation, which could
continue for weeks, months or years.
   ``What has happened is very bad news for people who were hoping
for more money out of the Gold Fields issue,'' said Christopher
Spreckley, an analyst at CL-Alexanders Laing and Cruickshank. ``Time
is just not on Minorco's side. Unless legal miracles start happening
(in the United States), I think this bid is bordering on dead.''
   Minorco's only incentive to sweeten its offer would be if it
thought it could persuade Consolidated Gold Fields to accept a
friendly buyout and drop the U.S. litigation, said Jeff Summers, an
analyst with the London investment firm Hoare Govett Ltd.
   But, ``It's very unlikely that Minorco would raise the bid,''
Summers said. ``Mr. Rudolph Agnew and his board do seem to be
determined to stay independent. Given some of the vitriolic remarks
which have passed between the two camps...I will be very surprised
if Gold Fields would be willing to consider an offer from Minorco.''
   There was some speculation Minorco might persuade the Panel on
Takeovers and Mergers to extend the time period within which it must
complete the bid until the U.S. court case is resolved.
   Minorco also could clear up the litigation and make a new offer
for Gold Fields sometime after February, when the British takeover
regulations would permit it to launch another bid, the analysts said.
   ``Anglo-American and Minorco have spent many years planning their
attempt on Gold Fields and I again would be surprised if they walked
away from it purely because of a U.S. court ruling,'' Summers said.
``I think Minorco might be willing to take a very long-term view.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
