<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-23 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Drop On Lower Cash Markets, Supply Ideas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply Thursday on
the Chicago Board of Trade in response to weaker cash markets,
forecasts for weekend rains in the Midwest and perceptions of
increasing supplies.
   Corn and oat futures also closed lower while wheat futures
advanced slightly.
   Market participation was thinner than usual, with some traders
getting an early start on the Easter weekend. The markets are closed
Friday.
   Some selling in the soybean market was incited by forecasts for
rain in parts of the Midwest late in the weekend or early next week,
which could reduce lingering dryness from last summer's drought.
   Perceptions that newly harvested Brazilian soybeans are about to
come onto the world market added to the selling pressure.
   Wheat futures traded lower for most of the session amid forecasts
for diminished chances of rain in the central Plains but finished
with slight gains as traders evened up their positions ahead of the
long weekend.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent lower to 2\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.28{ a bushel; corn was 2 cents to
3 cents lower with May at $2.77\ a bushel; oats were 2} cents to 3\
cents lower with May at $2.05\ a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to 9{
cents lower with May at $7.85 a bushel.
</TEXT>
