<FIRST>a f BC-BehindtheWheel Adv01-02   03-23 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 01-02,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, April 1-2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jetta A Stable and Stalwart Car</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 Volkswagen Jetta Carat offers admirable German handling
in a small package and at a competitive price.
   Here is a stable, stalwart car that takes road curves with little
sway. Here is a vehicle that zips along well and takes both city and
highway driving in stride. Here is a compact auto with a spacious
trunk and comfortable seats where the driver doesn't have to feel as
if he or she is sitting low inside the car.
   VW first brought the Jetta to the United States in 1980, and
although sales have fallen from their 1986 peak of 93,000, the Jetta
continues to be VW's best seller in the United States. Last year's
sales remained about flat with 1987's 65,000 level, said company
spokesman Jay Amestoy.
   The 1986 peak came after the Jetta was redesigned with new
engine, suspension and chassis systems.
   Thankfully for today's buyers, the 1989 VW Jetta retains the fine
characteristics of its predecessors even if it hasn't made the
change outside to the fancier, more aerodynamic body styling of some
of the competitors (Honda Accord, Mazda 626).
   Today's Jetta line includes a base, two-door model which starts
at $9,690, the upscale Carat and the performance GLI 16-valve
version.
   The test Jetta Carat (pronounced with the accent on the last
syllable, not like the vegetable) was wonderfully stable at high
speeds. The 1.8-liter four-cylinder engine was mated with a
five-speed automatic transmission to produce 105 horsepower at 5,400
rpm.
   The car cruised the highway well and seemed just as at home in
city-driving maneuvers. The two front seats had nifty height
adjusters that helped position me so I could easily have a clear
view over the front of the car _ a position I can't always find in
other autos.
   Lots of equipment came standard including rear headrests, power
windows, mirrors and antenna, AM-FM stereo with cassette player and
six speakers and a computer that figured fuel economy, average
driving speed, etc.
   The only option on the test car was the $395 manual sunroof and
that really wasn't necessary since the car also had
factory-installed air conditioning.
   However, VW is offering in 1989 for the first time antilock
brakes ($995), and while the test auto didn't have them, they might
be worth a good look, given their remarkable ability to help
maintain vehicle control.
   The Jetta's trunk is one of the largest in its class, with 16.6
cubic feet of storage space. The sturdy backing under the Carat's
carpet make the trunk one of the easiest to keep neat. There's no
sliding or bunching of the carpet.
   The Jetta is built for five passengers, but it could be pretty
uncomfortable with three adults in the back seat. The seats are
sturdy, for sure, but there could be a tight squeeze and whoever has
to sit in the middle will be sitting high up on a hard spot. Legroom
also could be cramped.
   My only other note was the difficulty I had at times in putting
the car in the right gear. The floor console for the automatic
transmission had raised white letters for the gears, but sometimes
it was tough to tell if I was in neutral or drive, drive or second.
That problem disappeared at night when the letters would light up as
the car was put in gear.
   Jetta buyers are young, with median age of 30 and median income
of $43,700. Nearly half are male, and 53 percent are married. The
vast majority have at least some college education and 61 percent
are in upper white collar jobs, Amestoy said. Main purchase reasons
include value for the money, ease of handling and reliability and
durability, the company said.
   Consumer Reports magazine says 1983-86 model Jettas ranked better
than average in owner reports of trouble.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for seven years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 1-2</NOTE>
</DOC>
