<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     03-23 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices spurted Thursday, driven by
a rally in the gasoline pits inspired by speculation the
Environmental Protection Agency will endorse new restrictions
affecting refining in the Northeast.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the April contract for
unleaded gasoline rose 0.66 cent to 58.02 cents a gallon after
posting a 0.21-cent increase on Wednesday.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
heating oil for April delivery went up 0.52 cent to 56.52 cents a
gallon.
   Meanwhile, the May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, finished with a gain of 11 cents
at $20.15 a barrel.
   Andrew Lebow, a senior broker and analyst at E.D.&amp;F. Man
International Futures Inc., said rising gasoline prices lifted the
entire energy market.
   Gasoline buying was triggered by news reports that the EPA was
likely to approve pending applications seeking to lessen
pollution-causing emissions from gasoline sold in Northeastern
states to cut smog in the region, he said.
   Energy market analysts say the restrictions will make the
refining process more costly and complicated and could lead to
temporary shortages as refiners in the Northeast make alterations to
accomodate tighter rules.
   Speculation about how the proposed rules will affect gasoline
supplies is expected to dominate the gasoline pits in the near
future.
   ``Next week's going to be very critical for the gasoline
market,'' Lebow said.``There's potential for very explosive movement
on the up side.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
