<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1744EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-23 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises In Domestic Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher in uneventful domestic
trading Thursday after putting in a mixed performance overseas ahead
of the long Easter weekend.
   Gold prices were mostly lower. Republic National Bank of New York
said gold was bid at $392.00 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down
$1.40 from Wednesday's late bid.
   Traders said the dollar held in a narrow range as they squared
their positions before the holiday weekend.
   ``It was fairly quiet,'' said Stephen Flanagan, a vice president
at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. ``There was no determination to
push the dollar in either direction.''
   While there will be limited domestic dollar trading on Friday,
the European currency markets are closed until Tuesday.
   ``With Europe gone for the weekend, we expect very little
activity,'' said Jeff Mondschein, a vice president at Continental
Illinois National Bank &amp; Trust Co. in Chicago.
   Mondschein noted that there was only ``minimal'' interest in the
government's revision of the fourth-quarter gross national product.
The Commerce Department said the economy expanded at a moderate 2.4
percent annual rate in 1988, up from an initial estimate of 2
percent.
   The GNP report gave the dollar a slight boost earlier in Europe,
but traders there noted that activity was subdued.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.52 Japanese yen to a closing 130.88
yen. Later in London, it fell further to 130.75 yen. But in New
York, the dollar rose to 131.25 yen, from 131.06 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.7205 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7225 late Wednesday. In
New York, it cost $1.7215 to buy one pound, less expensive than
Wednesday's $1.7270.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday, included: 1.8715 West German marks, up from 1.8660;
1.6264 Swiss francs, up from 1.6180; 6.3333 French francs, up from
6.3220; 1,376.88 Italian lire, up from 1,373.00, and 1.1901 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1878.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.8720 West German marks, up from 1.8693; 1.6260 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6225; 6.3315 French francs, down from 6.3345;
2.1025 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1115; 1,370.12 Italian lire, down
from 1,373.10, and 1.1894 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1897.
   Gold prices were mostly lower. On the Commodity Exchange in New
York, gold bullion for current delivery closed at $392.80 a troy
ounce, down from $394.40 on Wednesday.
   In London, gold was quoted at a late bid price of $394.75 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Wednesday. In Zurich, gold rose to a late bid
of $395.00, from $393.65 late Wednesday. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold
fell $2.30 to close at a bid $396.14 an ounce.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery finished at $6.008 a troy ounce, down from
Wednesday's $6.058. In London, the metal was trading at a bid price
of $6.08 a troy ounce, compared with Wednesday's $6.07.
</TEXT>
