<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     03-23 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Edge Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bond market rose modestly Thursday, extending
the gradual recovery of the previous two sessions in quiet
pre-holiday trading.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond rose 3-16 point, or $1.88
per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves inversely to its
price, fell to 9.21 percent from 9.23 percent late Wednesday.
   Trading trailed off by midafternoon as dealers went home early
for a three-day Easter holiday. There is no bond trading on Good
Friday.
   In contrast to earlier in the week, there was no economic news to
move the market. Traders shrugged off as old news the government's
report that the economy expanded at a 2.4 percent annual rate in the
last three months of 1988.
   ``It was very thin today. There's nothing that anybody can grab
on here,'' said Thomas Estes, a trader with Shearson Lehman
Government Securities Inc.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments rose 1-32 point, intermediate issues were up 1-32 point
to 1-16 point and long-term maturities rose 3-32 point to 3-16
point, according to Telerate Inc., the financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 0.67 to 1,113.98.
   In corporate trading, industrials were up. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.34
to 295.70.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose \ point to 89{. The average yield to
maturity fell to 7.84 percent from 7.87 percent late Wednesday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were unchanged at 9.35
percent as the discount remained at 9.02 percent. Yields on
six-month bills rose to 9.55 percent as the discount rose 1 basis
point to 9.00 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 9.67 percent
as the discount fell 1 basis point to 8.91 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 9~ percent, down from 10{ percent late Wednesday,
when it had been pushed up by technical factors.
</TEXT>
