<FIRST>u f AM-GAFMistrial     03-23 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAF Mistrial,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government: GAF Jury Favored Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Wall Street Crime, Bjt ^By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government claimed Thursday that defense
lawyers said most jurors in the GAF Corp. criminal stock
manipulation case favored conviction when a judge declared a
mistrial because the panel was deadlocked.
   Defense attorneys immediately denied the claim attributed to them.
   The GAF case drew wide attention as the first criminal trial
arising from the confessions of imprisoned insider trader Ivan
Boesky. It was the second mistrial in the case and suggested
prosecutors cannot easily win convictions, but the government asked
Thursday for a third trial starting next month.
   It wasn't clear when U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe would
set a new trial date for GAF and Vice Chairman James T. Sherwin.
   ``As we understand it, most jurors felt beyond a reasonable doubt
that Mr. Sherwin is guilty and we're confident that they all will
next time,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Bruce Baird, who heads the
securities and commodities fraud division.
   ``We actually were told about the split by defense lawyers,'' he
said. ``We were told that is what they learned.''
   But attorneys for Sherwin and GAF, a Wayne, N.J.-based specialty
chemicals maker, said they had not spoken to jurors or indicated to
prosectuors which way the jury was leaning.
   ``No one from the defense made that statement to my knowledge
because there would be no basis to make that statement,'' said
Stephen Kaufman, an attorney for Sherwin.
   ``It's speculation. It's surmise without any proof,'' he said.
``There is no public information and the jury issued a communication
that they don't want to discuss the matter.''
   The jury said in a statement through Lowe they would not comment
on their more than 90 hours of deliberations that followed the
six-week trial. Jurors reached by telephone Thursday stuck to their
pledge.
   The panel reported last Saturday it was deadlocked 11-1 but did
not indicate whether the majority favored acquittal or conviction.
On Wednesday it reported a three way split _ some to acquit, some to
convict and others undecided.
   The judge then asked whether further deliberations would be
fruitful. Seven said no, five said yes and Lowe decreed the mistrial.
   ``The original deadlock note of 11 to 1 did not indicate what the
sentiments of the jury were,'' said Alan Levine, an attorney for
Sherwin. ``They only thing that can be said for the next note is
that it appears there was some kind of a shift.''
   ``But I think it's still not possible to tell what the sentiments
were Saturday night or (Wednesday) afternoon,'' he said.
   After the 11-1 note, the defense asked Lowe to declare a mistrial
several times as the tiring deliberations progressed.
   Lowe also declared a mistrial in January after ruling that the
government unintentionally withheld evidence. At that time, jurors
on the first panel said they could not have convicted GAF based on
the testimony.
   GAF, two subsidiaries and Sherwin were charged last year with
allegedly trying to boost the stock price of Union Carbide Corp. in
1986 shortly before selling a large block of shares. They also were
charged with securities fraud, wire fraud and conspiracy.
   The purpose of the alleged deal was to maximize GAF's profits
from the planned sale of a large block of Union Carbide stock after
a failed takeover of the much larger chemical concern.
   The second mistrial was perceived as a setback in the
government's efforts to stage criminal trials in a Wall Street fraud
investigation that began with the insider trading scandals of the
mid-1980s.
   ``It's always disappointing when all 12 jurors don't accept the
government's case,'' Baird said. ``As long as we're confident in the
strength of our cases and confident that most jurors saw the case as
the government saw it, we'll try it again.''
</TEXT>
