<FIRST>u f AM-EasternRdp Bjt   03-23 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Moves Against Pilots in Court, Trains Replacements</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs for UNDATED item on AM-Business News Digest. Version on
general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TD2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines moved against its
striking pilots on two fronts Thursday, asking a federal appeals
court to force them back to work while announcing that the company
will begin to train replacements soon.
   A three-judge panel of the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Tallahassee took Eastern's appeal under advisement after an
hour-long hearing. Eastern asked the judges to overturn a lower
court ruling permitting the pilots to honor striking Machinists'
picket lines under the Railway Labor Act.
   ``The question is whether the RLA expressly forbids a sympathy
strike,'' said Judge R. Lanier Anderson III. ``That is the issue
before us.''
   In New York on Thursday, federal Bankruptcy Court Judge Burton
Lifland said he would appoint an examiner to oversee Eastern during
its reorganization under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy laws. In a
move described as unusual by bankruptcy attorneys, Lifland said the
as-yet-unnamed examiner would be given the power to try to mediate
between Eastern and its creditors and employees, as well as gather
information.
   In the federal appeals court, Eastern attorney David Ross told
the judges that because the Air Line Pilots Association was
negotiating a new contract with Eastern, they could not strike for
any reason.
   ``The Railway Labor Act says you cannot strike in support of your
collective bargaining goals until you have exhausted all of the
procedures of that act, and there is no dispute those procedures
have not been exhausted,'' he told reporters afterward.
   But Jim Lindsey, who represented ALPA, argued that the pilots
have the right to stage a sympathy strike and that the federal
courts don't have the authority to define what a sympathy strike is.
Congress took that right away from the judicial branch in 1932,
Lindsey said.
   Lindsey said he thought the judges might rule sometime next week.
   In Miami, Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said that despite ALPA's
contention the carrier could not find qualified pilots to replace
strikers, training for the first group of replacements was about to
start.
   ``We're hiring, no question about it,'' Matell said. ``The first
class starts on Monday, and that will have 30 or 40 people in it.
These are people who have been interviewed and passed the
examination.''
   In addition, he said, Eastern has received ``into the thousands
of phone calls'' in response to its ads seeking new pilots, which
began running Sunday.
   Ron Cole, spokesman for Eastern's ALPA pilots, dismissed the
hirings as unimportant, saying many pilots meet Federal Aviation
Administration requirements but aren't ready to work at a commercial
airline.
   ``This is a situation that the FAA is going to have to keep a
close eye on,'' he said.
   Eastern has been getting about 115 flights a day aloft recently,
said another spokewoman, Karen Ceremsak, and the new pilots will
increase that number. Before the strike, the company had more than
1,000 flights a day.
   After the bankruptcy court hearing in New York, both Eastern and
the pilots union said they agreed with the judge's decision to
appoint an examiner with power to act as a mediator.
   Eastern had asked Lifland to appoint an examiner to review all
transactions between Eastern and affiliated airlines during
bankruptcy proceedings. The unions have asked the bankruptcy court
to appoint a trustee, a more powerful official who actually would
run the airline during its bankruptcy reorganization.
   Lifland indicated his appointment of an examiner did not
necessarily mean he would not consider naming a trustee later. He
said he would ask the examiner to take on more than just
fact-finding duties in the hopes the examiner could ``mediate
differences'' between the embattled company and its unions and other
creditors.
   ``It sounds like a trustee, not an examiner,'' said Farrell
Kupersmith, chief financial adviser to the pilots' union.
   But Eastern President Phil Bakes also expressed no problems with
the judge's decision, saying, ``We wish we had thought of it.''
</TEXT>
