<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Redpath     03-23 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Redpath,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tate and Lyle Acquire Rest of Redpath Sugar Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British sugar refiner Tate and Lyle PLC on Thursday
said it agreed to acquire the parts of Canadian sugar group Redpath
Industries Ltd. that it didn't already own for about $240 million.
   Tate and Lyle said it would purchase the Canadian government's
49.9 percent holding in Redpath.
   Tate and Lyle said it plans to find buyers for Redpath's
non-sugar businesses, which include automotive, industrial and
consumer products. The company will try to find suitable Canadian
purchasers for these units, Tate and Lyle said, particularly for
operations based primarily in Canada.
   After completing the Redpath deal, Tate and Lyle will own 100
percent of its North American sugar interests. Redpath jointly owns
Tate and Lyle's U.S. sugar refiners Western Sugar and Amstar Sugar.
   The company said the purchase of the rest of Redpath will help it
simplify its North American sugar interests.
   Tate and Lyle also said Redpath had experienced ``significant''
growth over the past five years, with operating profit growing to
about $58.3 million in 1988.
</TEXT>
