<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-89 1950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Ecuador-Debt     03-23 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecuador-Debt,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ecuador To Renew Payments of Foreign Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday it will soon
renew payments on Ecuador's $11 billion foreign debt after a more
than two-year suspension.
   ``Within the process of negotiations with private foreign banks
and after a 26-month suspension of interest payments, Ecuador will
make modest and partial installments this year,'' government
spokesman Washington Herrera said.
   Herrera declined to give further details. But the Central Bank
said payments are expected to be resumed in the coming weeks.
   The small Andean country has balked at repayments since the start
of a financial crisis incited by a major earthquake in March 1987,
which ruptured a key oil pipeline and paralyzed the petroleum export
industry for six months until line could be repaired.
   During the year previous, the economy suffered by drastically
declining world oil prices. Ecuador depends on oil sales for more
than 60 percent of its foreign exchange.
   President Rodrigo Borja called for renegotiations with foreign
creditors shortly after he took office in August 1988, and talks
began earlier this year.
   The Congress has allotted $500 million for debt payments in this
year's budget.
</TEXT>
