<FIRST>u f AM-NuclearFusion-Business     03-23 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Fusion-Business,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fusion Breakthrough Holds No Immediate Profit Potential</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nuclear Fusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The handful of companies involved in nuclear
fusion research aren't expecting any profit windfall as a result of
an advance claimed Thursday by researchers in Salt Lake City.
   Fusion plants built by private industry will some day provide
clean, safe and inexpensive power, but in spite of the announcement
that day remains several decades off, company officials said in
interviews.
   Two researchers said Thursday they produced controlled nuclear
fusion using high school-level chemistry that could lead to a
technology capable of driving electrical generators within a few
years.
   B. Stanley Pons of the University of Utah and Martin Fleischmann
of the University of Southhampton in England cautioned that more
research is needed to determine whether the process will work on a
large scale.
   Officials in the tiny private sector of the nuclear fusion
business said they wanted to learn more about the work, but that
even in the best of circumstances it would only be a first step.
   ``We thought that during the 1980s fusion would be going into
engineering development that would require the private sector. That
would have happened, but the energy crisis went away'' and the
Reagan administration cut spending, said Stephen O. Dean, president
of Fusion Power Associates of Gaithersburg, Md.
   Fusion Power Associates was formed in 1979 as a group of private
companies and organizations involved in fusion work.
   ``We've sort of been in a holding pattern waiting for better
times in terms of government policies,'' Dean said. ``We need a
commitment to engineering development. We don't see how that can be
done in private industry.''
   Only two companies are gathering substantial revenue from nuclear
fusion, and in both cases the money comes entirely from government
funding, he said.
   General Atomics, a privately held company in San Diego, Calif.,
has a $30 million-a-year contract to operate an experimental
magnetic-confinement fusion device. It has other government
contracts worth $5 million to $6 million a year.
   KMS Fusion Inc. of Ann Arbor, Mich., makes fuel capsules that are
used as the targets of experimental laser-confinement fusion
reactors. The company is the only private company receiving
Department of Energy funding for laser fusion research. Its funding
is less than General Atomics', Dean said.
</TEXT>
