<FIRST>u f AM-Pennwalt-Centaur     03-23 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pennwalt-Centaur,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centaur Drops $110-A-Share Bid For Pennwalt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE RULE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centaur Partners ended its months-long
hostile takeover attempt of Pennwalt Corp. Thursday, announcing it
was dropping its $110-per-share offer.
   The withdrawal comes three days after the chemical company
announced it will accept a $132-per-share offer from the French
government-controlled oil and chemical concern Societe Nationale Elf
Aquitaine. Based on the number of Pennwalt's outstanding shares _ 8
million _ Elf Aquitaine's offer amounts to more than $1 billion.
   Centaur's announcement coincided with Elf Aquitaine's formal
commencement of the offer.
   Centaur, which owns about 13 percent of Pennwalt's stock, dropped
the offer because of the Elf Aquitaine development, the New
York-based investment group said in a statement. No officials were
available Thursday evening to comment on the decision, said Centaur
spokesman James D. Daniels.
   Pennwalt had fought Centaur since the investment group first made
its plans known last June.
   During the fight, Pennwalt sold off a pharmaceutical division and
most of its equipment business. The company also went to court to
stop Centaur from calling a shareholders meeting, where the
investment group hoped to replace the directors, paving the way for
the takeover bid to succeed.
   Pennwalt's chairman, Edwin E. Tuttle, maintained throughout the
takeover bid that the company believed Centaur never actually wanted
to acquire the company but merely wanted to drive up the stock
prices.
   Centaur does, indeed, stand to make a profit. The investment
group, headed by Abbey Butler and Melvin Estrin, began buying
Pennwalt stock in June when the price was $65 a share.
   It is estimated that Centaur's stock will bring the investors
more than $60 million.
   ``I can't imagine (Centaur's principals) are too upset,'' said
Don Pattison, an analyst with C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell in New
York. ``Even if they were sincere about wanting to run the company,
a profit like that can certainly soften the disappointment.''
   Pennwalt spokeswoman Sue Kinard could not be reached for comment,
but Elf Aquitaine's spokesman Walter Montgomery said, ``There's not
much to comment on. This doesn't change Elf's position.''
   Pennwalt's stock closed unchanged at $130.25 Thursday in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading. The stock's price
jumped $13.12{ _ about 11 percent _ to $130.12{ when Elf Aquitaine's
offer was made public Monday.
</TEXT>
