<FIRST>u f AM-Tyson-HollyFarms 1stLd-Writethru   03-23 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tyson-Holly Farms, 1st Ld-Writethru,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Rejects Latest Tyson Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st and 2nd grafs to CORRECT that board rejected offer
on Wednesday, announced decision Thursday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. directors have rejected
the latest buyout offer from rival poultry processor Tyson Foods
Inc., saying there is no way to ensure the $1.18 billion bid was
sound, Holly Farms said Thursday.
   Wednesday's rejection of the $63.50-a-share offer came the same
day that a Chancery Court judge in Delaware gave Holly Farms
permission to ask its shareholders on April 14 to approve a friendly
merger with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb.
   But Judge Maurice Hartnett said no merger would be allowed until
legal questions surrounding the proposal were settled.
   The ConAgra-Holly merger would be accomplished through a stock
swap valued at $59.25 a share, or about $1 billion, while Tyson's
$1.18 billion offer is for cash.
   The struggle to acquire Holly Farms, a diversified Memphis
company heavily dependant on fresh fryer sales, began last October.
A takeover by Tyson Foods would permit the Springdale, Ark., company
to keep its standing as the nation's largest poultry processor.
   One of the main snags in the merger proposal announced last year
by Holly Farms and ConAgra is a lockup option that would permit
ConAgra to buy prime Holly assets should their proposed merger fall
through.
   Hartnett has yet to rule on the validity of that agreement, which
Tyson claims was designed to make Holly Farms unattractive to any
buyer other than ConAgra.
   Tyson's buyout offer is contingent on dissolution of the lockup,
which is why Holly Farms rejected it, Holly Farms said in a
statement.
   ``Until Tyson removes from its tender offer the `asset option'
condition, Holly Farms stockholders can have no assurance that
Tyson's $63.50 price represents deliverable value,'' the statement
said.
   John Tyson, son of Tyson President Don Tyson, said the Holly
Farms' rejection was ``about as anticipated.''
   Tyson Foods is filing proxy materials with the Securities and
Exchange Commission and hopes to get it to Holly stockholders
sometime next week, John Tyson said.
</TEXT>
